<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Tehran-Scene     12-01 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tehran-Scene,0801</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Visit to Tehran Gives Glimpses of a City of Contrasts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Missing Iranians</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tehran is a city full of contrasts, showing the
effects of war, tradition and modern lifestyles. An Associated Press
correspondent accompanied West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich
Genscher on a recent visit, and here is his report:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DETLEF RUDEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the bustle of Tehran's main bazaar, young
women wearing blue jeans under their traditional Islamic chador
robes stroll past crippled war veterans hobbling on rickety wooden
crutches between merchant stalls.
   A few blocks away, curious children and young people flock to
gaze at the magnificent former residence of the late Shah of Iran.
   Some people on the streets of Tehran openly indicated their
displeasure with Iran's revolutionary government, which toppled the
shah in 1979.
   A book vendor asked for an up-to-date city guidebook told a
Western reporter, ``There has been nothing like that since the
revolution.''
   The merchant then held up a tattered guidebook dating back before
the Islamic revolution. She pointed to a photograph in the book of
the shah's family. The picture had been crossed out with thick black
censorship marks.
   ``It really is a shame,'' the book vendor said angrily.
   Journalists accompanying West German Foreign Minister
Hans-Dietrich Genscher to Tehran were not allowed to tour the city
freely or take pictures during the three-day state visit that ended
Tuesday.
   But the glimpses they were allowed showed Tehran is a city full
of contrasts. The Westerners witnessed clear evidence of Moslem
fundamentalism, but also signs of modernism.
   Iran has been making efforts to increase its contacts with some
Western nations, such as West Germany, as it tries to recover from
its crippling eight-year war with Iraq after a cease-fire.
   But West German businessmen who accompanied Genscher to Tehran
said it is still not certain whether Iran's commitment to
conservative Moslem principles will hinder efforts to build up the
country.
   ``Whoever plans to invest here must carefully weigh each step,''
said Rochus-Ernst Freiherr von Luettwitz, a West German involved in
business discussions with Iran.
   There are signs everywhere that a fundamentalist Islamic
philosophy that has governed life in Iran since the shah's ouster
still holds sway.
   Iranian Revolutionary Guards carrying automatic rifles were
plainly visible on Tehran's streets, watching the Western
journalists to make sure they did not violate any of the
restrictions under which their presence was permitted.
   The Iranian government's disdain for the late shah, who was
friendly with the United States, becomes bitterly clear with a visit
to the grand palace where he and his family had lived.
   Pictures of the shah have been turned upside-down inside the
rooms of the palace, now a museum. Photographs showing poverty and
squalor during the shah's rule have been placed near tables
exhibiting valuables once owned by the former ruler.
   Plaques tell visitors the purpose of rooms in the palace during
the shah's reign, but in a belittling fashion.
   ``Former Working Room of the Shah Who Fled,'' reads one plaque.
   But along with such clear evidence of Moslem fundamentalism,
there are also signs Tehran's people do not totally reject Western
ways.
   Many of Tehran's young women wear blue jeans or short skirts
under their traditional black chador robes, the fabric pushed back
just enough on their foreheads to reveal a lock or two of hair.
   Several young women were also wearing high-heeled shoes.
   Tehran residents on the streets did not stare at the Western
visitors but actually seemed to welcome them.
   There were also signs of the devastating war with Iraq. Crippled
young men hobbled along the streets and the Westerners saw empty
lots where they were told bombed-out homes once stood.
   There are also signs of stymied progress within Tehran.
   Just behind the Hotel Esteghlal, called the Royal Tehran Hilton
before the 1979 revolution, chickens raced among building materials
at the site of an uncompleted structure. Rusty steel girders were
scattered on the ground, giving the impression the structure had not
been worked on for some time.
   Inside the hotel itself, the climate-control system was able to
churn out only humid blasts of air.
   Genscher and his entourage were greeted with open arms by Iranian
officials.
   But Western journalists were told through the West German Embassy
that while in Iran they would be permitted to write only about
Genscher's meetings and that their visas were valid only for the
duration of the official visit.
   In addition, it was made clear to Western photographers that the
Iranians would not allow pictures to be taken of life on Tehran's
streets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
