<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PhilippinesReactor 1stLd-Writethru a0788 12-01 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines Reactor, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0788,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawsuit Expected As Smokescreen, Westinghouse Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with formal announcement of
lawsuit set; picks up 4th graf: ``What we're ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Electric Corp. said Wednesday it
will not be a scapegoat for what it calls politically motivated
opposition in the Philippines to a nuclear power plant it built
under former President Ferdinand Marcos.
   Philippines President Corazon Aquino says the $2.3 billion plant
60 miles northwest of Manila in Bataan province is unsafe in part
because of its design and its location on an earthquake fault near a
volcano.
   Her government has said it plans to sue Westinghouse for damages
and breach of contract regarding the plant, which never went into
operation because of alleged safety defects.
   Her legal adviser, Adolfo Azcuna, said in late October that a
lawsuit was ready and likely would be filed within a month in the
United States. An agreement barring either the government or the
company from taking legal action was due to expire Thursday.
   Formal announcement of the lawsuit was scheduled Thursday in
Manila for 2:30 p.m. (1:30 a.m. EST) at the presidential palace.
   ``What we're finding here are the results of a political policy
that came to life when they were running for office,'' said
Nathaniel D. Woodson, general manager of the Westinghouse nuclear
fuels unit. ``They now feel they have a political albatross around
their neck and they're trying to blame us.''
   The reactor's opponents also allege that bribes were paid over
the awarding of the prime contract. ``We won fairly and squarly,''
Woodson said in an interview.
   Woodson and Deputy General Counsel Louis J. Briskman said that
Philippines officials have acknowledged during private talks that no
matter how safe the plant is, they don't intend to allow nuclear
power production in the country.
   ``Safety has nothing to do with it,'' Woodson said.
   With all but $20 million to $30 million still due from Manila for
the power plant, Westinghouse could walk away from the 10-year-old
controversy, said Woodson. The bigger risk perhaps is damage to the
company's international standing as a designer and builder of
nuclear power plants.
   ``All over the world we have built plants, and we haven't had
this problem. If they don't want to operate this plant, that's
they're decision, but don't make Westinghouse a scapegoat,'' he
said. ``Westinghouse will not be a scapegoat.''
   The company cited investigations by the U.S. Justice Department
and the Securities and Exchange Commission that produced no evidence
warranting charges.
   Further, a safety study commissioned by the Aquino government
concluded that the plant is safe, Westinghouse said. A trade journal
published a draft of that report. The government says the final
report concludes otherwise, but officials have refused to release
the document.
   The 620-megawatt plant, powered by a Westinghouse-pressurized
water reactor, was completed three years ago.
   In its early stages, the project was shaken by allegations of
kickbacks to officials of the Marcos regime and by safety concerns.
   Communist rebels have bombed transmission towers leading from the
plant, and people have cut and sold the copper lines as scrap. The
plant's corps of operators has largely disbanded, and Westinghouse
has only a handful of employees still in the Philippines, Woodson
said.
   Yet the cost of the plant continues rising, Westinghouse said.
Interest on the loans the Philippines took to build cost an
estimated $300,000 per day.
</TEXT>
