<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DeficitCommission 1stLd-Writethru a0683 12-01 0925</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deficit Commission, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0683,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wright Urges Bush To Move Quickly Against Budget Deficit</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS 3 final grafs with Bowen letter to OMB on health spending
cut proposals</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright on Wednesday called
for George Bush to quickly present Congress with an ``honest and
responsible'' budget, saying the president-elect has a duty to spell
out in detail his plan for attacking the country's deficit problems.
   Wright joined a chorus of witnesses before the National Economic
Commission who urged quick and decisive action on the part of the
new administration and Congress to break the seven-year deadlock
over huge budget deficits.
   Former Federal Reserve Chairman Paul Volcker, who also testified,
said that failure to act could trigger a loss of confidence by
foreigners in the value of the dollar, sparking higher interest
rates and possibly a severe recession in this country.
   ``We are, entirely unnecessarily in my view, undercutting the
economic foundation of United States world leadership,'' Volcker
said.
   Wright said Bush should submit his own spending blueprint no
later than mid-February and this should be followed by the
recommendations of the economic commission by March 1.
   ``We do not have the luxury of a leisurely schedule,'' Wright
said. ``The problems won't wait indefinitely while people try to
read our lips or read our minds.''
   Wright and other Democrats want to force Bush to be specific on
how he would cut the deficit without raising taxes while still
keeping his other campaign promises to boost spending in such areas
as education, day care and environmental cleanup.
   They fear that unless the president-elect is forced to spell out
how his spending cuts would work, Bush will try later to blame
Congress for boosting taxes while ignoring his ``flexible freeze''
approach.
   Bush said last week he intends to appoint people to begin deficit
negotiations with Congress on his first day in office, but he has
not said whether he will submit his own spending plan or simply use
President Reagan's final budget as the starting point for
discussions.
   Wright said if Bush did not want to submit a separate budget then
Reagan should consider allowing Bush to incorporate his own
recommendations into the administration's 1990 budget, which Reagan
will submit on Jan. 9.
   ``This would be an act of smooth transition and the kind of
resolute leadership which could inspire greater confidence both from
the public and from financial markets at home and abroad,'' Wright
said.
   Volcker, in his testimony, sounded many of the same warnings as
his successor at the Fed, Alan Greenspan. In testimomy before the
commission two weeks ago, Greenspan said the deficit had begun to
``eat away at the foundations of our economic strength, and the need
to deal with it is becoming ever more urgent.''
   Volcker said since the current economic recovery began in late
1982 the country has been on a consumption binge, fueled by the huge
budget deficits and large flows of foreign capital into the country.
   To keep foreigners from losing confidence in the U.S. economy,
Volcker said the government needed to launch a credible deficit
reduction program that would bring the deficit down by between $30
billion to $40 billion each year until the budget reaches surplus.
The deficit in the last fiscal year was $155.1 billion.
   Volcker said he would favor using a gasoline tax to raise extra
revenues, saying each 1-cent-per-gallon boost in the tax raises $1
billion annually in new revenues. This tax would promote
conservation, Volcker said, thus reducing U.S. dependence on foreign
oil and helping to trim America's huge trade deficits.
   The Council on Competitiveness, composed of 157 chief executives
from business, organized labor and higher education, presented the
commission with a list of proposals to trim the deficit by $120
billion by 1993 with a combination of spending cuts and $48 billion
in higher taxes.
   Among the taxes the council suggested were a boost in excise
taxes on cigarettes and alcohol, which would raise $8 billion
annually; a 20-cent-per-gallon increase in the gasoline tax, which
would raise $20 billion annually; and higher income tax rates for
families earning more than $220,350 a year, which could bring in $7
billion in additional revenues, the council said.
   Former Rep. Robert Giaimo, D-Conn., and co-chairman of the
Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget, said a nationwide series
of town meetings had shown him that Americans support balancing the
budget, even it means tax increases and a freeze in cost-of-living
hikes for Social Security.
   Charles Bowsher, head of the General Accounting Office, presented
the commission with a GAO transition report which came to the
conclusion that Bush's flexible freeze would not be enough to
eliminate the deficit and consideration would have to be given to
increasing taxes.
   ``When the long-term health of our nation's economy is at stake,
everything must be negotiable, including defense spending,
entitlements and taxes,'' Bowsher said.
   Meanwhile, Health and Human Services Secretary Otis R. Bowen has
registered his objections to proposals by the White House's Office
of Management and Budget to cut Medicaid payments to states next
year and to reduce the growth in spending on AIDS.
   In a letter Bowen wrote to OMB Director Joseph R. Wright Jr.,
reported in Thursday's editions of The Washington Post, the
secretary called the Medicaid proposal ``unrealistic.''
   OMB wants to slash federal Medicaid payments to states by $1.1
billion, and to allow AIDS spending to grow from $1.3 billion to
$1.6 billion. Bowen wants the government to spend $1.9 billion on
AIDS.
</TEXT>
