<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NerveGas     12-01 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nerve Gas,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Investigating Alleged Scheme To Ship Nerve Gas To Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal authorities are investigating an alleged
scheme to illegally ship a chemical used to make nerve gas to Iran
from the United States, the St. Louis Post-Dispatch reported.
   Documents filed in U.S. District Court in St. Louis say a company
in Baltimore attempted to ship thiodiglycol, a chemical precursor of
mustard gas, to Iran via Singapore and Pakistan, the Post-Dispatch
said in its Thursday editions.
   The documents were filed in an application for a search warrant
which sought telexes, computer printouts and records of messages
between Alcolac International Inc. of Baltimore, maker of the
chemical, and two companies in West Germany and Singapore.
   In the 8-year war between Iran and Iraq, both sides _ but
particularly Iraq _ were accused of using chemical weapons. Both
sides denied using the weapons, which are outlawed under the Geneva
Convention.
   Thiodiglycol has permissible applications in the textile
industry, but its export is restricted under U.S. export laws ``to
prevent diversion to Iran, Iraq and Syria for use in chemical
warfare,'' the affidavit says.
   The U.S. Customs Service outlined the scheme in a 14-page
affidavit file in their application for the search warrant.
   The affidavit says Alcolac began shipping thiodiglycol in
February 1987 for Colimex GmbH, a West German company now called
Chemco GmbH & Co. KG.
   Alcolac's shipping documents referred to the cargo by its trade
name, Kromfax, rather by its chemical name. The documents had been
manipulated to make it possible to divert the cargo to Karachi,
Pakistan, in violation of U.S. Export Administration Regulations,
the affidavit says.
   The cargo began its journey by barge from Baltimore to Norfolk,
where customs agents intercepted it and switched the Kromfax drums
with drums of water.
   Customs agents then monitored the cargo's route to Singapore and
its transshipment to Karachi.
   In late June, agents with the Drug Enforcement Administration
learned from customs officials in Karachi that the shipment had been
transferred to an Iranian flagship named ``SS Iran Ekram.''
   The cargo then made its way to the Iranian port at Bandar Abbas.
It was set to be delivered ultimately to a company in Tehran, the
capital of Iran.
   The affidavit says an undated telex from Walaschek to Alcolac
indicates ``that he intended to cause the shipment of thiodiglycol
to be transshipped from Singapore to Pakistan, and ultimately Iran,
and that Alcolac knew that Singapore was not the ultimate
destination for the shipment.''
   Alcolac International was incorporated in Baltimore in 1955. Paul
Jones, vice president and general manager of the performance
chemicals division, said the company manufactured ``specialty
chemicals'' like those in shampoos. Thiodiglycol is a solvent, he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
