<1ST_LINE>r w PM-QuayleInterview Bjt   12-01 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle Interview, Bjt,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle May Preside More In Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President-elect Dan Quayle may spend more
time than his predecessors presiding over the Senate, a move that
could spell conflict between the Democratic-controlled chamber and
the administration.
   In an interview, Quayle on Wednesday also made his strongest
public rejection of the notion that he will act as the link between
the administration and the Republican Party's far right.
   He also said his verbal gaffes during the campaign gave him some
hard lessons about his own tendency to talk too much. Being besieged
with questions and jokes about his qualifications was painful but
educational, he said.
   ``I know myself better now. I'm a stronger person,'' he said.
   Quayle said his focus now is on the task ahead _ picking his vice
presidential staff during the transition period and working with
President-elect George Bush.
   Since the election, conservatives have beaten a path to Quayle's
transition office seeking his ear. Quayle himself is an ardent
conservative who has largely supported Reagan administration
positions during his eight years in the Senate.
   ``I've worked with a number of conservatives in the past; a lot
of good friends are conservatives, but I'm not the point man for the
conservatives in this administration. ... You won't see me being the
so-called spear carrier for all the so-called conservative issues,''
Quayle said.
   Quayle also hinted that he may take a more active role in his
official capacity as president of the Senate, presiding over the
Democratic-controlled chamber more frequently.
   ``It's certainly an option. ... There have been suggestions to me
by many that I consider spending more time in the Senate than my
predecessors have. I have not made a decision on that,'' he said.
   The presiding officer has substantial discretion as to which
senator to recognize for the purpose of offering amendments, bills
and motions. Normally the chair is occupied by a member of the
majority party. A Republican in charge could touch off partisan
parliamentary warfare.
   The vice president may take the presiding chair at any time, and
the presiding officer's decision to recognize a senator is not
subject to a point of order or appeal under Senate rules.
   Bush has said he wants to work with Congress, and Quayle said if
he did decide to preside more often, it would not be done ``in a
contentious manner.''
   ``I would be fair and objective and do what the president of the
Senate should do to protect senators' rights, all senators'
rights,'' he said.
   During the interview, Quayle was relaxed and friendly, but
clearly weighing his words. He has not generally spoken to the press
in depth since the election. He confessed to being ``far more
careful of what I say today than six months ago.''
   ``I also try to discipline myself when I get into a situation ...
instead of being verbose, which is a tendency that I have, to be
concise. Because verbosity leads to unclear, inarticulate things.''
   Also on Wednesday, Quayle met with retiring Indiana Gov. Robert
D. Orr, a Republican who will appoint Quayle's replacement in the
Senate. Quayle will resign effective Jan. 2 so his replacement can
have seniority over other incoming senators.
   Orr has not said whom he will appoint, and Quayle said he made no
recommendation. But he did not reject a reporter's suggestion that
he favors Rep. Dan Coats, who was Quayle's district representative
in Fort Wayne, Ind., while Quayle was in the House from 1976 to
1980. Coats now represents Quayle's old congressional district.
   ``Obviously I think a lot of Dan Coats. He worked for me for four
years. He's been a very good congressman from my old congressional
district. He took my seat. We've had a long and strong personal and
professional relationship,'' Quayle said.
   On another subject, Quayle said the vice presidential mansion in
the District of Columbia may need alterations before his family can
move in after the inauguration. He said the house is not configured
for a family with three children. It does have six bedrooms, but
some of them now serve as offices and servants' quarters and some do
not have closets.
   The Quayles will live at their home in McLean, Va., until they
can move into the official residence. Their three children _ Tucker,
14, Benjamin, 12, and Corinne, 10 _ will continue attending public
schools in Virginia for the time being.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
