<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDSDay-US     12-01 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Day-US,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Letters From Victims Mark AIDS Day Observance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 20-year-old Alabama resident wrote a top
federal health official that the public reaction to disclosing he
tested positive for the AIDS virus would end his life ``sooner than
AIDS will probably take it.''
   The letter from ``D'' _ his identity is known to Public Health
Service officials _ was among eight from people with AIDS being read
today during a World AIDS Day ceremony at the Department of Health
and Human Services.
   ``I live in the Bible Belt of our country,'' began the letter to
Dr. Robert E. Windom, the No. 2 physician in the federal health
department. ``I have lived most of my life in a small town in
Alabama. I attend a large university in Alabama and will soon be
finishing my junior year.
   ``I can't tell you my name because my short life of only 20 years
would be over very quickly. It would be over sooner than AIDS will
probably take it. I'm HIV positive and have been so diagnosed since
spring of 1987.
   ``I sit in classrooms and hear people discuss AIDS and what they
think they know is right. Why can't I speak up and tell them they
can't get it from just being in the same room? Why can't I tell them
the truth?
   ``I'm so afraid of what will happen if I openly admit to being
HIV positive. Would I get kicked out of school? I was so afraid of
what people would think, I didn't even talk to my parents about it
for six months. I was hurting so bad. I was lonely.
   ``Now, my father has never even said the word AIDS and my mother
only makes sure I'm in good health and eating right and taking
vitamins.''
   Windom, the assistant secretary for health, arranged the program,
including an opening minute of silence for the people who have died
of AIDS.
   As of Nov. 7, 1988, AIDS had been diagnosed in 77,994 Americans,
of whom more than half, or 43,888, have died since June 1, 1981,
according to the CDC. No one is known to have recovered from AIDS.
</TEXT>
