<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MissingMarine     12-01 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Marine,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Officers Face Court-Martial Over Missing Marine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A probe into last summer's disappearance of a
young Marine during training maneuvers in California is being
reopened and three officers involved in the mystery face
court-martial, the Marine Corps says.
   The commandant of the corps, Gen. Alfred M. Gray, on Wednesday
ordered a reopening of the investigation into the disappearance of
Lance Corporal Jason J. Rother of Minneapolis.
   The Marines also announced that Rother's squad leader, platoon
sergeant and a third officer would face court-martial on various
charges in trials expected to begin in about two weeks.
   Rother, 19, was helping direct vehicles at Twentynine Palms,
Calif., a Marine base, during combat maneuvers the night of last
Aug. 30. The infantryman, who had been stationed at Camp Lejeune,
N.C., was reported missing two days later and has not been seen
since.
   Hundreds of Marines using dogs searched the base and the
surrounding area for several days and found nothing but a pack and
some rocks positioned into the shape of an arrow.
   A second search, conducted several weeks later, also found
nothing.
   The new investigation into Rother's disappearance is expected to
last one month, said Marine spokeswoman Lt. Elizabeth Kerstens.
   The Marines said that Rother's squad leader, Sgt. Thomas B.
Turnell, will be tried on charges of dereliction of duty and
unauthorized absence. Sgt. Christopher P. Clyde, Rother's platoon
sergeant, was also charged with dereliction of duty.
   And 1st Lt. Allen V. Lawson, who oversaw the placing the road
guides that night, has been charged with dereliction of duty and
willful disobedience of an order for allegedly not posting guides in
pairs, as he had been told to do.
   In addition, a platoon leader and company commander have been
relieved of their commands and reprimanded. Kerstens said the names
of the two officers were not being released.
   Kerstens said she could provide no further details on the alleged
actions by the accused officers that resulted in the charges.
   The three courts-martial will be conducted at Camp Lejeune.
</TEXT>
