<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 0336EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AP-Guild     12-01 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP-Guild,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agreement Reached On New Contract for Guild-Covered Staff at AP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Associated Press and the Wire Service Guild
agreed on a new collective bargaining agreement covering 1,400
employees, including the news service's domestic reporting and
editing staff.
   The two-year accord came minutes before midnight Wednesday, when
the preceding pact was to expire. The Guild's negotiating committee
voted to recommend the agreement for approval by its membership.
   The new contract provides the AP news staff with a top-minimum
salary of $720 per week, after increases of $27 a week in the first
year and $25 a week in the second year. In addition, the agreement
provided significant increases for AP's non-news personnel.
   Among fringe benefit improvements, the contract provides for
extension of dental health coverage to cover part of the cost of
orthodontic treatment, and a doubling of the eye-care reimbursement
benefit to $100 annually.
   New benefits were creation of a non-matching 401K retirement
savings plan and establishment of an account to provide tax deferred
benefits to staffers making arrangements for child care or other
dependent care.
   AP also established a 100 percent reimbursement for certain
preventive cancer screening tests.
   Aside from the general increase, the agreement also provides for
improvements in the economic differential received by AP news
staffers in New York, Washington, Los Angeles, Chicago, Boston and
San Francisco. Staffers in New York and Washington received
increases of $10 in the first year and $12 in the second year,
providing a total differential of $87.
   In Los Angeles, Chicago, Boston and San Francisco, the increase
was $5 in the first year and $7 in the second year, providing a
total differential of $45.
   The contract agreement also resolved a unit clarification
petition filed by the AP and a companion petition filed by the
Guild. The petitions asked the National Labor Relations Board to
clarify the supervisory status of AP News editors and
correspondents, a subject that had been considered but not
definitively resolved by the NLRB in 1982.
   The Guild and the AP agreed that all news editors and
correspondents supervising three or more employes would be exempt
from Guild jurisdiction and thus become members of AP management.
Correspondents who supervise smaller AP operations would remain in
Guild jurisdiction, the parties agreed.
   NLRB hearings, set to begin in December, will be canceled as a
result of the agreement, in which the AP said news editors or
correspondents who wished to maintain their place in the Guild
bargaining unit could relinquish their supervisory duties and
transfer to regular staff positions.
   The parties also resolved several significant pension issues,
striking a mandatory contribution clause that required the AP to
contribute $2,881 per week to a pension trust that was already fully
funded. The parties further agreed that funds held in the AP account
in The Newspaper Guild Commingled Fund could be used for payments of
pension benefits and expenses, retroactive through 1988.
   Bargaining on the contract began in October. The guild was
represented by AP news staffers from around the nation who are
members of the union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881201-0031 </DOCNO>
