<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     12-01 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Down Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar declined marginally against the Japanese
yen in Tokyo Thursday, and prices fell slightly on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 37.44 points
or 0.13 percent, closing at 29,541.46. On Wednesday, the index
closed at a record high of 29,578.90.
   The dollar finished the day at 121.57 yen, down 0.28 yen from
Wednesday's closing. The U.S. currency stayed within a range of
121.28-121.60 yen after opening lower at 121.28 yen.
   In New York Wednesday, the dollar fell after a big sell order
from the Bank of England, which was attempting to keep the British
pound from rising against the West German mark, dealers said.
   In Tokyo, many market participants remained on the sidelines
awaiting the release of the U.S. unemployment rate for November,
said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo. The U.S. Labor Department is
scheduled to announce the jobless rate on Friday.
   ``The dollar rose slightly after some trading companies bought
the currency, but the dollar-yen rate did not move very much,'' said
the dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   On the stock exchange, share prices fell mainly due to
profit-taking following the index's gain earlier in the week, said
an analyst with Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   ``In addition, participants were reluctant to buy issues because
of the approaching release of the U.S. jobless rate,'' he said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
