<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shuttle-Crews     12-01 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Crews,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Black Commander, Nine Rookies On New NASA Shuttle Crews</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA's first black shuttle commander
and nine space rookies are among the astronauts chosen to fly on
four missions in 1989 and early 1990.
   Frederick D. Gregory, an Air Force colonel who piloted Challenger
on a flight in April 1985, will command a Department of Defense
mission on Discovery set to launch Aug. 10, 1989. The 47-year-old
Gregory will be the space agency's first black shuttle commander,
NASA announced Wednesday.
   The four other crew members assigned to the mission are pilot S.
David Griggs, and mission specialists F. Story Musgrave, Kathryn C.
Thornton and Navy Capt. Manley L. Carter Jr. It will be the first
flight for Ms. Thornton and Carter.
   Commanding a mission scheduled to fly Oct. 12, 1989, will be Navy
Capt. Donald E. Williams, who flew one previous mission as a pilot
aboard Discovery in 1985. The five-person crew plans to deploy the
planetary probe Galileo, which will make its way to Jupiter.
   Michael J. McCulley, a Navy commander, will make his first flight
on Atlantis as the pilot. Shannon W. Lucid, Frankling Chang-Diaz and
space rookie Ellen S. Baker were named mission specialists.
   Navy Capt. Daniel C. Brandenstein, the current chief of the
astronaut office at NASA's Johnson Space Center, will command
Columbia on a flight planned for Nov. 13, 1989. The five-person crew
will deploy a satellite and retrieve the Long Duration Exposure
Facility.
   The other crew members will be Navy Lt. Cmdr. James D. Wetherbee,
the pilot, and mission specialists Bonnie J. Dunbar, G. David Low
and Marsha S. Ivins. It will be the first shuttle flight for
Wetherbee, Low and Ms. Ivins.
   Navy Capt. Jon A. McBride will command Columbia on another flight
set to launch March 1, 1990. Air Force Col. Guy S. Gardner, assigned
to the current Atlantis flight, will be McBride's pilot.
   Space veterans John M. Lounge, Jeffrey A. Hoffman and Robert A.R.
Parker will be mission specialists on the flight. Lounge has flown
on two previous flights, including the first post-Challenger mission
aboard Discovery, which launched in late September.
   The payload specialists assigned to the mission, which will
feature use of the ASTRO-1 ultraviolet astronomy telescope, are
rookies Ronald A. Parise and Samuel T. Durrance.
</TEXT>
