<DOCNO> AP881201-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 0417EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Alzheimer'sTown Bjt   12-01 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alzheimer's Town, Bjt,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Holds Daylong Seminar on Alzheimer's</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WESTPORT, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Third-grader Victoria Kennedy told her
classmates in a hushed voice how her grandmother looked at wedding
pictures and could not remember the names of her own family members.
   Matthew Ouelette, another Westport Elementary School pupil,
recalled how his neighbor, an elderly woman, ``forgot how to
drive,'' and ``forgot how to cook.''
   Like practically everyone in their coastal town of 1,850
residents, the pupils were talking about Alzheimer's disease as part
of a day-long series of events Wednesday put together by educators,
doctors and a drug company.
   ``This is a test to see how much you can educate an entire town
in one day,'' said William Connolly of New Jersey-based Sandoz
Pharmaceuticals Corp.
   The program used coloring books, a mascot dog and movies to show
how the debilitating ailment can be battled. For a few hours, the
students put aside their reading, writing and arithmetic to look at
a disease that may not afflict them for 60 years, if at all.
   The children wanted to know how Alzheimer's disease gets started
and, as it happens, that was one question that could not be answered
definitively.
   The purpose of the effort was not so much to understand how the
disease works but to show how the loved ones of an Alzheimer's
sufferer can, with patience, helpful advice and love, minimize the
worst of the disease's effects.
   Westport, which is in the third year of a federal Health and
Human Services grant intended to promote community programs,
developed the Alzheimer's effort in meetings between school
officials and Connolly, who spends summers here. Sandoz manufactures
Hydergine, a drug that can ease some symptoms of Alzheimer's in
milder cases.
   For adults, Wednesday's program included discussions on
``positive approaches to aging,'' a film titled ``There Were Times
Dear,'' dramatizing a family coping with Alzheimer's, and a lecture
by Dr. William Gershell, a specialist in geriatrics at Mount Sinai
Medical Center in New York City.
   Alzheimer's afflicts an estimated 5 million mostly elderly
Americans. Efforts are expanding to help them cope. Until recently,
the focus was on patients, not their families.
   Westport is changing that emphasis because of mounting evidence
that children are often acutely aware of and confused by the decline
of a loved one.
   A coloring book titled ``Helping Grandma,'' by Westport High
School art teacher Betsey MacDonald, told the story of a grandmother
who gradually begins to show signs of memory loss.
   ``Children are often kept in the dark about aging,'' said
MacDonald. ``They automatically think that `old' means `sick.' But
children are wonderfully resilient and surprisingly insightful when
spoken to directly on the subject.''
   The point of the coloring book, geared toward elementary school
children, is to ``teach them understanding and to teach them that
what she needs is support.''
   Connolly said a key problem with the disease is the failure to
recognize that it is a problem.
   ``The feeling is that to be old is to be sick and to be old is to
be confused,'' Connolly said. Children ask what is wrong with an
elderly relative and ``parents say, `Well, Grandma's getting old.'
That's not true.''
   One of the first things relatives can do for those showing signs
of memory loss or other dementia is encourage them to go to a doctor.
   Also, mature, well-behaved dogs from an animal shelter can
provide some stability and love for an Alzheimer's sufferer,
Connolly said. Jeff, a black and white mongrel from a Rhode Island
animal shelter, has become the national poster dog for the so-called
human-animal bonding campaign, and he travels with Connolly to
events on the subject.
   The Alzheimer's event in this southern Massachusetts community
was the second of its kind. Connolly, MacDonald and Jeff tried out
the program earlier this fall in Bloomington, Ind.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881201-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 0457EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KidnappedTwice     12-01 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kidnapped Twice,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Slain Girl Had Been Kidnapped in Similar Incident in 1987, Officers
Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A five-year-old girl who was kidnapped
from her home for the second time in two years was found dead of
strangulation and massive head injuries beside a road, authorities
say.
   The body of Lottie Margaret Rhodes, a kindergarten student, was
found hours after she was kidnapped from her bedroom Wednesday,
Arlington police said. She had been left beside an isolated road
three miles away in neighboring Grand Prairie.
   Police said the girl had also been kidnapped from her home in
1987 by an unknown assailant and released.
   The girl's mother, Toni Rhodes, 23, told police that someone
broke into the apartment through the child's bedroom window sometime
between 2 a.m. Wednesday, when a live-in baby-sitter checked on the
girl, and 8 a.m., when Ms. Rhodes discovered her daughter missing.
   Ms. Rhodes told authorities that the kidnapper had placed some
stuffed animals under the covers on the girl's bed in an apparent
attempt to make it appear that the girl was still in the bed.
   A baby-sitter, Joe Martinez, 18, had been caring for the girl and
her three-year-old brother while the mother worked at an Arlington
diner.
   Neighbors told authorities they did not hear anything unusual
during the night, although one said his dog started barking at 2
a.m. But he said he did not see anything unusual when he checked the
area by looking through a window.
   The Dallas County medical examiner's office ruled the death a
homicide, saying that an autopsy determined that the girl died of
asphyxia, or lack of oxygen, and ``crush force'' injuries to the
head.
   Arlington police spokesman Dee Anderson said evidence also
indicated the girl had been run over by a vehicle.
   Police said they had no leads and no suspects in the case and
could not say whether the homicide was related to the 1987 incident,
in which the girl was found on June 22 wandering about five miles
from her home.
   Then four, the child told police that a thin, black-haired man
about 19 years old, driving a small brown car, had kidnapped her
about 9:30 a.m. outside her apartment. The man released her an hour
later, Anderson said.
   Medical evidence indicated the girl may have been sexually
assaulted in the earlier kidnapping, he said. Police never
apprehended the abductor, Anderson said.
   Police said they had no information on the girl's father, who
neighbors said did not live with the family.
</TEXT>
