<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     12-01 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICOPEE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Help has come nun-too-soon for the sisters
at a small, Catholic women's college stuck with 94,000 cookbooks and
a printer's bill for $400,000 from a fund-raising project that went
awry.
   ``I call it `felix culpa.' It's a Latin expression meaning `happy
fault,''' said Sister Judith O'Connell, assistant development
director for Our Lady of the Elms College, on Wednesday.
   Since the sisters' plight was reported in mid-November, Sister
Judith said she has received hundreds of mail orders daily for the
350-recipe book, ``In Good Taste.''
   ``If it keeps up, we could sell all the cookbooks,'' she said.
``We really do believe in miracles.''
   Although too swamped to take an exact tally, she said more than
5,000 orders already have been filled and some companies have
approached the sisters about distributing the book.
   One man sent a check for $500 for 25 books.
   ``He said that he had been educated by one of the sisters that is
now working at the college,'' Sister Judith said.
   The Sisters of St. Joseph, who run the 750-student college, had
hoped to raise $1 million for scholarships through sales of the
cookbook at $10 a copy. But they only sold 6,000 copies in 12
months, and Sister Mary Dooley, college president, acknowledged the
100,000-book printing may have been ``over optimistic.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small helium balloon launched by
elementary school students carried a birthday greeting 1,500 miles
in two days, landing eventually in Saskatchewan, Canada, officials
said.
   ``The students were shocked that it would go that far,'' said Ed
Little, principal of the Martin Luther King Elementary School.
``They thought that it would go as far as Eastern Washington. But to
have it go to Saskatchewan, Canada, was quite a thrill for them.''
   Each of the school's 450 students released a helium balloon Nov.
10 bearing the school's blue and yellow colors to mark Veterans Day
and the start of the state centennial, Little said.
   Inside the balloons was the message: ``Happy 100th birthday
Washington State from the students and staff of Martin Luther King
Elementary School.''
   One of the balloons reached the farm of Donna Forrester, who sent
the school a letter that said her daughter found the balloon while
riding a horse on Nov. 12.
   ``She was very pleased, to say the least, and we were all amazed
that it had come this far,'' Forrester wrote. ``We estimated it
traveled about 1,500 miles.''
   Forrester enclosed a map of Saskatchewan indicating that her farm
is about 8 miles north of the U.S.-Canada border along North Dakota.
   The students now are getting a lesson in geography and
international relations _ two teachers used the map for a lesson in
Canadian geography and the students were assigned to send a note
back to Saskatchewan.
</TEXT>
