<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSSuit     12-01 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Suit,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dismissed Dental Student Files Suit over AIDS Exposure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A student who was dismissed from the Washington
University dental school for treating patients after testing
positive for exposure to the AIDS virus has sued the school for $3
million in damages.
   The student, whose name is listed in the suit as John Doe, claims
the school improperly barred him from its dental program last
summer. Attorney Norman London contends his client is handicapped
and cannot be discriminated against.
   The suit, filed Wednesday in St. Louis Circuit Court, also names
Washington University chancellor William Danforth and David A.
Bensinger, dean of the dental school. The suit does not seek to have
the student reinstated, but asks for $3 million in damages,
contending the use of rubber gloves and other protective devices
makes the risk of transmitting the virus negligible.
   School officials said the student treated 27 patients at the
dental school for about a year after contracting the disease.
   Bensinger said the student tested positive for antibodies to the
human immunodefiency syndrome _ HIV _ in late March or early April.
The student was dismissed from the school in August and was not
allowed to enroll for the current school year.
   Students and instructional faculty members provide dental care at
the school's clinic.
   University officials refused to comment on the suit. Peter Ruger,
the university's general counsel, said that the dental school was
well within its rights in barring the student from treating patients
and pursuing his education.
</TEXT>
