<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Government 1stLd-Writethru   12-01 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Government, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0464,0771</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Political Reforms Alone Won't Make Soviet Union Democratic</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf, `The 1,500...' to UPDATE with parliamentary
vote. Pickup 4th, `Gorbachev's promise...</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev says
constitutional and electoral reforms are ``a kind of oxygen'' to
revive the body politic, but it is unlikely they alone can make his
society any more democratic.
   Since the proposed reforms appeared on Oct. 22-23, Soviet society
has been engaged in a remarkable debate over an overhaul of the
electoral system and the structure of the government that Gorbachev
says is the first big step toward making Soviet society into one
governed by law rather than dictate.
   The 1,500 members of the Supreme Soviet parliament today
overwhelmingly approved the package, the amended version of which
still has not been published in the official press.
   Gorbachev's promise is a weighty one in a society now reopening
the emotional and physical scars of Josef Stalin's purges and still
suffering from a much more recent history of systematic jailing or
exile of dissidents and overbearing bureaucracy.
   But political reforms do not guarantee change.
   Political repression has been imposed in a Soviet system that on
paper guaranteed citizens' rights. The Communist Party has shown no
interest in sharing power.
   And operating in the current system, critics have used
Gorbachev's policy of ``glasnost,'' or greater openness, to force
some changes in his proposals.
   ``Political reform is a kind of oxygen needed by the public
organism,'' Gorbachev told the Supreme Soviet on Tuesday, the first
day of a special session to consider the reform package.
   ``If we do not carry out political reform to back up the
processes that are now under way in the economy, the social
transformation of society and the recuperation in the cultural
field, and fail to radically update the activities of the governing
councils and our personnel, the drive for restructuring will
inevitably begin to skid,'' he said.
   Gorbachev said his solution is ``our own socialist system of
`checks and balances' ... designed to protect society against any
violations of socialist legality at the highest state level.''
   He called for the formation of a Congress of People's Deputies, a
new 2,250-member legislative body formed not only in elections from
geographic districts and ethnic territories, but from organizations
such as the Communist Party and trade unions.
   Draft legislation gave the presidency, which Gorbachev assumed
Oct. 1, considerably more power, and appeared as well to strengthen
Moscow's hand with the 15 republics that make up the Soviet Union.
   The proposals loosened an avalanche of more than 300,000
suggestions from across the Soviet Union, and protests from at least
a third of the republics that some of the reforms fostered the
opposite of Gorbachev's proclaimed intention to give local
authorities more power.
   In the spirit of ``glasnost,'' Soviet leaders got an earful of
criticism that led them to amend about half of the almost 120
articles before introducing them to the Supreme Soviet on Monday. In
two days of rare debate, deputies of the Supreme Soviet offered many
more.
   ``The discussion itself, I'll tell you frankly, is
unprecedented,'' Soviet Vice President Anatoly Lukyanov told a news
conference.
   The tiny Baltic republic of Estonia, where Gorbachev's policy of
greater openness already encouraged a grassroots political movement
to demand greater autonomy, has declared itself ``sovereign'' in
internal affairs and proclaiming the right to pass judgment on new
Soviet laws.
   Similar organizations in the other Baltic republics of Latvia and
Lithuania were close behind but could not push the legislation
through their parliaments.
   The Presidium of the national Supreme Soviet declared Estonia's
action unconstitutional.
   Gorbachev also must rein in the Communist Party and government
bureaucracies that are stubbornly resistant to change.
   The president told the Supreme Soviet that many initiatives from
working people ``are being lost in bureaucratic mazes, or are even
encountering resistance.''
   He won approval at the June party conference for a plan to get
the party out of day-to-day management of government and economic
affairs, concentrating instead on setting policy. He has called for
taking power from the Moscow and giving it to local economic
managers along with the responsibility of ensuring they make enough
money to pay for their operations.
   But the Soviet leader regularly expresses frustration with both
the party and government bureaucracy's slow pace of change.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Mark J. Porubcansky is a correspondent in the
Moscow bureau of The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
