<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Sweden-Riot     12-01 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sweden-Riot,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Riot in Central Stockholm, 180 Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said today they arrested 180
youths in street fights between ultra-rightists and opponents in
central Stockholm.
   Sixteen policemen were hospitalized for injuries from smoke bombs
in Wednesday night's riot, the national news agency TT said. No
injuries were reported among the rioters.
   Police Superintendent Evert Karlen said the clash centered on a
park where the nationalist Swedish Socialist Workers Party had
gathered to honor Karl XII, an 18th century ruler known as the
``King of Wars.''
   He said about 100 members of the ultra-rightist party and 250
opponents of the group threw stones and snowballs at each other
after the annual gathering.
   The Swedish king was slain in a battle in Norway in 1718, after a
life of warring in Russia and Poland. For the Socialist Workers
Party, supported by bands of ``skinheads,'' Karl XII is a symbol of
national power.
   A group of 50 youths, wearing green jackets and close-cropped
hair, later stormed into the central subway station and smashed up
one car before police surrounded them, Karlen said.
   ``Most of these youths, on both sides, have no idea why they
fight,'' Karlen said. ``And they haven't got the slightest idea who
Karl XII is.''
</TEXT>
