<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 0633EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-LaLanne     12-01 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-LaLanne,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LaLanne: Living Is The Hard Part</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KINGSPORT, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anyone can die; living is the tough part,
according to exercise guru Jack Lalanne.
   LaLanne, 73, and his 62-year-old wife, Elaine, say they feel like
spring chickens and want others to feel that way, too.
   ``Habits, habits, habits. That's what it's all about is habits,''
said LaLanne during a recent telephone interview from his Southern
California home.
   ``If you're sick, tired, unattractive, whose fault is it? God's?
The devil's? There's only one person that can account for you and
that's you,'' said LaLanne, an exercise and diet evangelist for more
than 50 years.
   A staple in his pep-talk routine is to pump up non-exercisers
with words of encouragement.
   ``Pride and discipline. That's the key. When you lose pride in
life, you lose everything. Have you ever watched the birds, the
animals. How clean they are? They have that pride in what they can
do,'' said LaLanne, who is scheduled to give a lecture here Monday.
   Lalanne, who has lent his name to health and fitness centers, as
well as television workout programs, has developed his own program
of walking in combination with other exercises, but he said the key
is getting off the couch and sticking to a nutritious diet.
   ``Anything is good if you do it consistently,'' LaLanne said.
``You'd be surprised what can happen in 30 days if you just do
something about it.''
</TEXT>
