<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PartyLineRape     12-01 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Party Line Rape,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maryland Man Suspected of Raping Party Line Acquaintance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 26-year-old baker has been charged with
raping a mentally retarded woman who became an acquaintance through
conversations on a telephone ``party line,'' police reported.
   Timothy Moals of Columbia was charged with second-degree rape in
the Nov. 21 incident outside the victim's mobile home, said Sgt.
Joseph H. Bisesi, a spokesman for Anne Arundel County police.
   Moals was charged with second-degree rape ``because she is
mentally handicapped and therefore incapable of consent to the
act,'' court records said.
   Bisesi said that before the attack, Moals and the woman had
spoken three or four times on ``The Party Line,'' a Baltimore-based
telephone introduction service that enables up to eight people to
carry on a conversation at once.
   Moals subsequently telephoned the woman directly and invited
himself to her house, Bisesi said. The 20-year-old victim later told
her mother she had been raped in front of a storage shed, and the
mother notified police, he said.
   Moals was arrested at his home late Tuesday. District Court Judge
Lawrence R. Rushworth on Wednesday set bail at $10,000 and ordered
Moals to submit to a psychological examination to determine his
competence to stand trial.
   Web Chamberlin, a spokesman for the Chesapeake & Potomac
Telephone Co., said ``The Party Line'' is sponsored by a New York
resident, Brendan Corrigan.
   Chamberlin said that although telephone introduction services
have come under increasing scrutiny lately, he had never heard of a
crime being committed as a result of the relationships forged
through them.
</TEXT>
