<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Steinberg     12-01 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steinberg,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nussbaum to Testify in Steinberg Murder Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Trial scheduled to resume at 9:30 a.m. EST.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joel Steinberg's former live-in lover rehearsed
her prosecution testimony, anticipating the most dramatic
confrontation in his trial on charges he beat his 6-year-old
illegally adopted daughter to death.
   Hedda Nussbaum, who has not faced Steinberg in more than a year,
was expected to testify today that he beat Lisa Steinberg to death.
   ``That confrontation will be electrifying,'' New York University
law professor Stephen Gillers said Wednesday. ``That experience
could free her. Telling her story could be cleansing.''
   ``She is the key, crucial witness,'' state judge Harold Rothwax
said during pretrial hearings.
   Nussbaum, 46, spent about 10 minutes Wednesday with a detective,
prosecutors and her lawyers in the Manhattan courtroom where the
trial is being held and spent eight hours with prosecutors outside
the courtroom, according to several reports. There were no
proceedings in the case Wednesday.
   Steinberg has denied he hit Lisa. He says she fell unconscious
after choking on food the night of Nov. 1, 1987, and that he caused
the bruises on her chest and back while trying futilely to revive
her.
   Lisa, described as a bright, outgoing first-grader, was removed
bruised, unconscious and barely breathing early the next morning
from the Greenwich Village apartment Steinberg and Nussbaum shared.
The girl was pronounced dead at a hospital three days later.
   Police also found a 16-month-old boy the couple raised in the
apartment.
   Steinberg's attorneys have suggested during the trial that
Nussbaum struck the blow that killed Lisa.
   ``She's nervous,'' Nussbaum's attorney, Barry Scheck, said
Wednesday.
   In the weeks following Steinberg's arrest last year, ``Hedda felt
protective about Joel,'' Scheck said.
   ``Despite the almost total destruction of her personality by
Joel, her feelings have changed,'' he continued. ``She's come to
have a lot greater insight into her relationship with Joel.''
   Nussbaum has spent the past year recovering from the
psychological and physical injuries which Scheck blamed on
Steinberg. She has had several operations, faces more, and has been
living at a nursing facility.
   In a $3.6 million lawsuit filed against Steinberg this week,
Nussbaum charged he beat her, brainwashed her, plied her with drugs
and made her beg for food. She said Steinberg forced her to take ice
water baths if he caught her eating without permission.
   The jury hearing the murder trial saw a police videotape showing
serious wounds and bruises over Nussbaum's body which Scheck says
were inflicted by Steinberg.
   Steinberg, 47, is a disbarred lawyer who illegally obtained Lisa
at birth from a Long Island teen-ager. The child's natural mother,
Michele Launders, now 27, watches the trial daily from a front row
seat.
</TEXT>
