<DOCNO> AP881201-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 0803EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TrainingReforms     12-01 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Training Reforms,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Training Council Approves Police Cadet Training Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEEDHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state council on police training
approved reforms, including minimum physical fitness standards for
cadets and certification for instructors, in the wake of a
25-year-old cadet's death.
   The Criminal Justice Training Council voted overwhelmingly for
the new measures in this Boston suburb Wednesday as a coroner's
inquest into the death of Cadet Timothy Shepard continued in
Springfield.
   The council reiterated its abolition of ``modified stress
training,'' which combined constant exercise with unexpected
situations and conflicting orders.
   Such methods were partly blamed for the dehydration suffered by
cadets at the Agawam training academy near Springfield in September.
   Shepard collapsed on the first day of training Sept. 19 at the
academy after a day of rigorous training with few breaks for water.
He died six weeks later of complications from heat stroke, a coroner
has ruled.
   Fifteen other cadets were hospitalized the first week of training.
   The measures approved Wednesday are part of a 120-day ``action
plan'' which will go into effect with the start of new training
classes in January, according to Peter W. Agnes Jr., the council's
interim executive director.
   The plan is intended to become part of a permanent, comprehensive
program for teaching police recruits.
   ``We will have made a clean break with the past,'' Agnes told
council members and a panel that included Attorney General James
Shannon. ``We will set the agenda for the future by laying the
groundwork now.''
   Among other rules adopted Wednesday:
   _ Injuries to student officers must be documented and recorded;
   _ Physical or academic punishment to teach, enforce or maintain
discipline is prohibited;
   _ Establishment of a new discipline policy, including a
merit-demerit system;
   _ Pre-admission drug screening and physicals by qualified
physicians;
   _ More rigorous rules for academic performance, including
standardization of all written tests;
   _ Creation of new qualifications and certification for all
academy directors and instructors;
   _ All academy directors and instructors must read the attorney
general's report of what happened during training this year;
   _ Pre-admission orientation on physical and academic aspects of
police training.
   The council also accepted the resignation of Assistant Director
James Canty and authorized the dismissals of Judith Crossen,
director of training; Martin Michaelman, pre-screening coordinator
and Earl Harrington, former zone manager for western Massachusetts.
Brian Daley, director of standards, will be reassigned to new
duties, the council said.
</TEXT>
