<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ArtTheft     12-01 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Art Theft,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Manet Work is Recovered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAPHANK, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bandit was ``remorseful, crying and
upset'' that he stole an Impressionist painting worth more than $1
million from a museum, but not sorry enough to turn himself in,
police said.
   Suffolk County Detective Sgt. Gene Gross said the tearful thief
called police Wednesday morning to tell them Edouard Manet's
``Bouquet of Peonies,'' taken Sunday from the Heckscher Museum in
Huntington, could be found at an apartment complex in the New York
City borough of Queens.
   The thief told police the painting could be found in the basement
laundry room, but it was not there when police arrived shortly
before noon, according to Suffolk County Police Commissioner Daniel
Guido.
   The building's superintendent had found it, Guido said, and put
it in a storage room. The superintendent had thought about hanging
it in his apartment but decided against it because he didn't think
it was attractive.
   Guido said the superintendent was ``quite shocked'' to learn the
value of the painting.
   Heckscher museum Registrar William Titus said the recovered
painting was authentic and undamaged.
   The painting, in its gold frame, measures about 16{ by 21{ inches
and could have been smuggled out of the Long Island museum under a
coat, said police spokesman Lt. William Kiley.
   Police said the thief apparently took the painting from the wall,
walked out a basement door and escaped. Two uniformed guards were
patrolling the five-room exhibition area at the time.
   Investigators are trying to uncover the identity of a blond man
who witnesses said they saw putting a painting into the trunk of a
silver car outside the museum, Guido said.
   But he said police will not use laser equipment to try to
retrieve fingerprints from the painting because it would be a
``cultural felony'' to risk damaging the work.
   Guido said it was ``clearly a miracle that we have recovered the
painting. It is amazing we got it back.''
   The 1880 Manet is a still life of red and pink flowers in a glass
vase. It had been lent to the Heckscher by its owner, who has
remained anonymous.
   The full value of the painting was not made public, but police
and museum officials said it was more than $1 million.
</TEXT>
