<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Kimball,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kimball Pleads Guilty To Throwing Object at Football Game</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Olympic medalist Bruce Kimball, who already
faces drunken-driving manslaughter charges in the deaths of two
teen-agers, has pleaded guilty to throwing an object at a policeman
after a college football game.
   Kimball was seen throwing apples and a plastic, juice-filled
lemon at police officers during a wild celebration at Michigan
Stadium after the University of Michigan Wolverines clinched a trip
to the Rose Bowl with a 38-9 victory over Illinois Nov. 12,
according to police in Ann Arbor, Mich.
   Kimball, 25, pleaded guilty Monday in Ann Arbor and is scheduled
to be sentenced Dec. 13 on the misdemeanor charge, which carries a
maximum penalty of 90 days in jail or a maximum fine of $100.
   Kimball, a Michigan alumnus who was a silver medalist in diving
at the 1984 Olympics, faces manslaughter charges stemming from a car
accident in suburban Brandon Aug. 1 that killed two youths and left
four seriously injured.
   Frank Quesada, one of the attorneys defending Kimball on the
manslaughter charges, said the Michigan incident was nothing more
than celebrating at a football game.
   ``He was never on the field and never throwing apples,'' Quesada
said. ``He was among a group of 15 to 18 who were given citations
for throwing rolls of toilet paper. ... It's a common thing, and he
didn't know it was an infraction.''
   Ann Arbor Police Capt. Richard DeGrand said misdemeanors like the
one for which Kimball was cited are not unusual on football
Saturdays.
   Also Wednesday, Tampa Judge Harry Lee Coe III moved the date for
Kimball's manslaughter trial from Dec. 12 to Jan. 9.
</TEXT>
