<BYLINE>James Neely</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DANVILLE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James R. Neely, a high school dropout who
went on to develop heart research procedures used around the world,
died Tuesday of a heart attack. He was 52.
   Neely was the senior research scientist at Geisinger Medical
Center's Sigfried and Janet Weis Center for Research. In 1967, he
developed a technique for keeping the hearts of laboratory rats
alive outside the body.
   The procedure allowed researchers to study the effects of heart
attacks in relation to oxygen and other nutrients in the heart,
according to Dr. Howard Morgan, director of the Weis Center.
   Neely's published work on the technique was classified as a
``citation classic'' by the Philadelphia-based Institute for
Scientific Information, which monitors published works on research.
The term means other scientists referred to Neely's work at least
500 times in published articles.
</TEXT>
