<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Jackson     12-01 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Sees `Qualitative Change' Between Bush And Reagan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, who once said George Bush was
morally unfit to be president, said today he expects a ``qualitative
change'' on civil rights when Bush takes over from President Reagan.
   Jackson said Bush indicated to him during a White House meeting
Wednesday that he would strengthen the Civil Rights Commission,
engage in a comprehensive anti-drug battle and be more open to
advice on social issues.
   ``I suppose just having lines of communications open is a step
towards being kinder and gentler,'' the former Democratic
presidential candidate said, referring to a pledge Bush made when he
accepted the Republican nomination. Jackson said Reagan has been
``unkind and harsh'' in some of his actions.
   Interviewed on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America,'' Jackson said
Reagan closed the door against the congressional Black Caucus and
others concerned about civil rights and added, ``I think there will
be a qualitative change'' under Bush.
   He said Bush was ``awfully mum'' during the Reagan years but
added, ``I suppose there's a certain presidential loyalty that goes
along with being vice president.''
   Jackson said he had been encouraged by past meetings with Bush
over Haitian refugees, the extension of voters' rights and the
condition of blacks in South Africa.
   ``I'm concerned that President-elect Bush will now put forth the
initiative to set a new moral tone for our country,'' he said. ``No
one can set a moral tone better than the president can.'' He
described Bush as ``quite positive and quite upbeat'' during their
90-minute discussion.
   ``I am ... persuaded that his commitment to have a credible Civil
Rights Commission is going to make some difference in race relations
in this country,'' he said.
   Jackson said he was also encouraged by Bush's willingness to meet
with hard-pressed farmers.
   ``That kind of openness and access and willingness to expand and
to hear other people certainly is the highest and most effective use
of the pulpit called the White House,'' he said.
   Jackson said Bush did not indicate whom he would pick to lead the
war on drugs, but he said both men agreed it must be someone who has
the complete confidence of the president and the secretary of state.
   He said an anti-drug war that focuses only on children _ an
apparent reference to first lady Nancy Reagan's ``Just Say No''
efforts _ was not enough, with $150 billion being spent on drugs.
``Children are not buying that amount,'' he said.
   ``My impression is he (Bush) really wants to fight a
comprehensive drug war, and I'm willing to help in any way I can.''
</TEXT>
