<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0446 12-01 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0446,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede BEIJING</HEAD>
<HEAD>Chinese Foreign Minister Arrives In Moscow</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Qian arriving in Moscow.
Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``China, the...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Qian Qichen of China arrived today
for the first foreign-ministry level talks between the two communist
powers on Soviet soil in 31 years.
   ``China and the Soviet Union, as two great neighboring countries,
must live in peace and good-neighborly relations,'' Qian said in a
statement distributed by the Soviet news agency Tass. ``We are glad
that in recent years Chinese-Soviet relations gradually are
improving. I sincerely hope this visit will end with the expecte
results.''
   Qian was greeted at Moscow's Sheremetyevo 2 airport by Foreign
Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze, with whom he will conduct two days
of talks that will include laying the groundwork for a
Chinese-Soviet summit meeting next year.
   The Chinese foreign minister also said he expects to meet with
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Before leaving Beijing, Qian said the focus of his talks will be
the war in Cambodia, the major stumbling block to restoring normal
Chinese-Soviet ties.
   China, the main backer of anti-Vietnamese resistance forces in
Cambodia, insists that Moscow exert pressure on its ally Vietnam to
end its 10-year military occupation of that Southeast Asian country.
   The last Chinese foreign minister to visit Moscow was Chou En-lai
in 1957. No Soviet foreign minister has made an official visit to
Beijing since Andrei Gromyko accompanied then Soviet leader Nikita
Khrushchev in 1959.
   In 1960, China and the Soviet Union split after Mao Tse-tung
accused Khrushchev of ``revisionism'' and compromising with the
capitalist West. The Soviet Union responded by withdrawing Soviet
engineers and technology from hundreds of joint projects, dealing a
painful blow to China's fragile industrial base.
   Relations reached a low in 1969 when the two sides fought a short
war along their disputed border. Mao called on the nation to prepare
for all-out war, and each side stationed at least 1 million troops
along the border.
   The countries began normalization talks in 1982, opening the way
for a general easing of tensions and a gradual increase in trade,
scientific and cultural exchanges.
   Qian noted that the two sides held vice foreign minister-level
talks in Beijing last August on Cambodia and that he had discussed
the issue with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze in a
meeting at the United Nations in September.
   Both sides, Qian said, ``have indicated their willingness to make
an effort to bring about an early settlement to the Kampuchean
(Cambodian) question on a just and reasonable basis, including the
Vietnam troop withdrawal.''
   Qian also indicated that the first Chinese-Soviet summit since
Khrushchev met Mao in Beijing in 1959 was a certainty, regardless of
further progress on Cambodia. That summit is scheduled next year in
Beijing.
   Asked if the summit was linked to solving the Cambodian question,
Qian said, ``Now the conditions for the summit meeting in the view
of both sides are getting ready and both sides are making
preparations for his summit.''
   He said his visit and a return visit to Beijing, probably next
month, by Shevardnadze ``will all be part of the preparations.''
   Chinese leaders have said a summit could take place in the first
half of 1989. Gorbachev is expected to come to Beijing because
China's senior leader Deng Xiaoping, 84, rarely travels abroad.
   China has continued to insist ``three obstacles'' remain, headed
by Cambodia, that must be solved before full normalization can be
realized.
   Moscow has taken steps to remove the other two obstacles by
pulling out of Afghanistan and reducing tension along the border by
withdrawing one army division facing China from Soviet ally Mongolia.
   Qian said he will discuss the estimated 50,000 Soviet troops
still in Mongolia, ``which should be pulled out,'' border disputes
and ``the Soviet military gathering along the Chinese-Soviet
border.''
</TEXT>
