<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FalseReport     12-01 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-False Report,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Allegedly Made Her Own Death Threats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who spoke out in favor of
housing desegregation in Yonkers has been charged with fabricating a
death threat after being videotaped vandalizing her own home.
   A complaint filed Wednesday in federal court said a camera
concealed by the FBI taped Laurie Recht, 35, writing a racist,
anti-Semitic death threat on her house Saturday.
   The complaint also charges that Ms. Recht reported receiving
death threats by telephone Aug. 16, although a police tracing device
failed to pick them up.
   Ms. Recht was the only speaker among 50 people at a Yonkers City
Council meeting last January who supported a court-ordered
desegregation plan, and she received extensive media attention.
   She later claimed she had received hundreds of death threats and
that swastikas and racist remarks had been written on the outside
walls of her apartment. After two incidents were reported, the FBI
installed a camera outside her apartment.
   A former legal secretary and a law student at an undisclosed
school, Ms. Recht was charged with a single count of filing a false
statement, a felony which carries up to five years in prison and a
$250,000 fine upon conviction.
   U.S. Magistrate Joel Tyler arraigned Ms. Recht and released her
on her own recognizance, pending a Dec. 30 court appearance.
Assistant U.S. Attorney Lisa Margaret Smith said she had no
objection to Ms. Recht being released because Ms. Recht had lived in
the area all her life, lived in the apartment for eight years and
had no previous criminal record.
   The Yonkers desegregation case stemmed from a 1985 ruling by U.S.
District Judge Leonard Sand in which the city was found liable for
40 years of segregated housing and schools.
</TEXT>
