<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GandhiAssassins     12-01 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gandhi Assassins,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Blocks Executions Of Gandhi Assassins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today blocked the
executions of two Sikhs condemned to death for the 1984
assassination of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi, the United News of
India reported.
   The decision came 14 hours before the two men were to hang.
   A panel of three Supreme Court justices granted the request for a
stay of execution filed by the son of Kehar Singh, one of the
condemned men.
   The stay will remain in effect until Tuesday to give the court
time to hear an appeal challenging the president's denial of
clemency.
   Lawyers for Satwant Singh, one of the two guards who shot Mrs.
Gandhi, and Kehar Singh, convicted of conspiracy, filed a variety of
petitions with the Supreme Court and the Delhi High Court. They
sought to block the hangings scheduled for Friday morning, but those
petitions were rejected.
   President Ramaswamy Venkataraman last week turned down an appeal
for clemency by Kehar Singh, a Home Ministry official disclosed
Wedesday. The reason for the denial was not disclosed.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Satwant
Singh, 30, cannot be hanged while that petition was pending for
Kehar Singh, 54.
   The two men are not related, but like all members of Sikh faith
they use the name Singh, which means lion.
   Satwant Singh and another Sikh bodyguard, Beant Singh, shot Mrs.
Gandhi in the garden of her residence on Oct. 31, 1984.
   Mrs. Gandhi was killed in apparent retaliation for an army raid
she ordered four months earlier to rout militants from the Golden
Temple in Amritsar, the Sikhs' holiest shrine. More than 1,200
people died, most of them Sikhs.
   Her murder triggered anti-Sikh riots across northern India by
members of the majority Hindu religion. More than 2,700 people died,
nearly all of them Sikhs.
   Sikh violence since then has escalated, with more than 2,300
people killed this year alone in Punjab.
   Tihar prison, where the two are being held, was under heavy guard
today, with dozens of extra security guards armed with rifles and
yardlong bamboo canes. Sentries watched from sand-bagged bunkers
outside the salmon-colored prison walls. The watchtowers atop the
walls also were sandbagged.
   In Punjab, heavily armed security forces manned checkpoints along
the roads and officials ordered schools and universities closed as a
precaution.
</TEXT>
