<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PatuxentEscape     12-01 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Patuxent Escape,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Patuxent Institution to Review Furloughs Today</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christmas furloughs for a triple murderer and
other inmates of a maximum security prison may be revoked because of
public outcry, while police sought an escapee from the same prison
in the rape of a 40-year-old woman.
   While the Patuxent Institution review board ponders the furloughs
and may decide the matter today, a warrant has been issued for James
M. Stavarakas, the prime suspect in a rape of a 40-year-old woman in
the Washington, D.C., suburb of Hyattsville. The attack bears a
startling resemblance to the crime that landed Stavarakas in prison
in 1979, authorities said. He escaped Monday from the prison in
Jessup, about 20 miles southwest of Baltimore, where he was serving
a 25-year sentence.
   The victim's general description of the attacker matched that of
Stavarakas, and she noted distinctive tattoos, said Maryland Capital
Park Police spokesman Steve Davis. In addition, the rape occurred
near the same park as Stavarakas' 1978 assault.
   Meanwhile, a Howard County Circuit Court judge on Wednesday
issued a temporary injunction blocking Patuxent officials from
granting additional furloughs to triple murderer Robert Angell for
at least 10 days.
   The order was requested by the Montgomery County Police
Association, which has filed suit to force Angell's transfer to
another prison.
   Angell, 31, was sentenced to three life terms for the murders of
two Montgomery County police officers and a teen-ager.
   Judge Cornelius Sybert said the injunction would expire at
midnight Dec. 9. A police association attorney said he would apply
then for a 10-day extension of the order.
   Lt. Gary Smith, a spokesman for the police association, said he
was pleased with Sybert's ruling.
   ``I don't think we can afford the luxury of gambling on Angell,''
he said. ``He forfeited his right to freedom when he murdered three
people.''
   The association filed the suit after reports that Angell had been
granted 11 furloughs to visit his family since April. The
corrections department put an end to the visits in the ensuing furor
and canceled Angell's planned Thanksgiving leave.
   Patuxent is the only institution in the country which has
independent powers to grant paroles and supervised furloughs, a
power some state officials want to review because of the outcry
caused by the Angell case.
</TEXT>
