<1ST_LINE>r i PM-WorldAIDSDay     12-01 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-World AIDS Day,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World AIDS Day Opens With Messages From Reagan, Pope, AIDS Victim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA WATSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, Pope John Paul II and one of the
longest living AIDS victims sent messages to the World Health
Organization today on the first World AIDS Day.
   The messages called for a stepped-up fight against AIDS and for
compassion for its victims.
   The agency organized World AIDS Day to encourage governments and
communities to talk about the disease, which affects an estimated
300,000 people worldwide. It said 140 countries planned special
television and radio programs and dances, parades and song contests.
   Entertainer Pearl Bailey told officials at WHO headquarters that
she knows a 29-year-old man with AIDS and that she wants to dedicate
her life to the fight against the disease.
   Also present was Richard Rector, a 32-year-old San Francisco man
who has had AIDS for six years. Rector said World AIDS Day should be
``the opening paragraph in a new chapter of our worldwide effort to
stop AIDS.''
   Rector, currently based in Berlin, said he has traveled to three
continents to teach people about AIDS.
   Officially, 142 countries have reported 129,385 cases of AIDS to
the World Health Organization. But the agency estimates that the
true number is more than twice that, and that 5 to 10 million people
may be infected with the virus that causes AIDS. Once a person is
infected with the virus, he or she has a 50 percent chance of
developing AIDS within 10 years.
   There is no known cure for AIDS, which attacks the body's immune
system.
   The agency has emphasized education as a primary means to fight
the spread of the infection, which can be transmitted through blood,
sexual intercourse, and from an infected mother to her unborn or
newborn child. People at high risk of infection include those with
numerous sex partners and intravenous drug users who share needles.
   Dr. James Mason, director of the U.S. Centers for Disease Control
in Atlanta, told the opening ceremony that the ``spread of infection
in some high risk groups in the United States is clearly declining.''
   He said this was because ``some infected and non-infected
individuals practicing risky behavior have adopted safe or less
risky lifestyles.''
   Mason noted that the first cases of AIDS were recognized in 1981,
in the United States, and that 78,985 Americans have gotten AIDS and
44,334 have died from it. But he also said: ``AIDS has stimulated an
unprecedented scientific and medical research effort that will have
long-term benefit in combating AIDS and other diseases as well.''
   Reagan called knowledge ``a critical weapon'' in fighting AIDS,
and said knowledge must also lead to individual responsibility.
   ``It is the responsibility of each individual to learn about HIV
and to treat those infected with HIV with respect and compassion.
And it is the responsibility of infected individuals not to infect
others,'' Reagan said in a message read by Miss Bailey.
   The pope's statement urged ``respect for all individuals'' and
said ``the degree of civilization of societies may be judged by how
civilization responds to the suffering of man.'' He said AIDS
victims ``meet with my affection and are the subject of my prayers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
