<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Amnesty-Aliens 1stLd-Writethru a0488 12-01 0864</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amnesty-Aliens, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0488,0888</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Illegal Aliens Travel Far For Amnesty</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with comments from INS director.
Picks up 6th graf pvs, `Illegal aliens ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Basharat Mirza, an illegal alien from Pakistan,
woke up well before dawn on the final day of an opportunity to keep
his American dream alive.
   Mirza left New York City at 4:30 a.m. Wednesday and drove about
100 miles to a U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service office
here.
   The 30-year-old Mirza, one of more than 1 million alien farm
workers to apply for a work permit under a nationwide amnesty
program that expired at midnight, said he chose the Lima office
because New York's INS office was crowded with other applicants.
   ``Too much rush there. Too much people there,'' Mirza said. ``Not
so many peoples here.''
   The INS initially estimated that 600,000 farm workers would pay
the $185 fee to apply under the sweeping program mandated by the
1986 immigration act. But by the deadline, 1.1 million to 1.2
million applications were taken, the agency said.
   Aaron Bodin, who heads the amnesty program for the INS, said
today that the agency did not turn away any applicants who were
waiting in line at INS offices at midnight.
   He said the agency believed many of those applying were not farm
workers, but other aliens who missed a May 4 deadline for non-farm
workers to apply for amnesty.
   ``I think it's because the standards of proof were so lenient
that many aliens, feeling increasingly desperate because of employer
sanctions (against hiring illegal aliens), took advantage of that
(farm program) to get legal status,'' Bodin said on ``This Morning''
on CBS.
   ``We really don't know how many people are truly eligible,'' he
said.
   Those aliens whose applications are rejected ``are back where
they were and the service takes no action. It's expected, however,
because of the employer sanctions provisions making it illegal for
employers to hire illegal aliens, these people will eventually be
discouraged and return home of their own volition.''
   Illegal aliens like Mirza came from as far away as Boston to the
INS office in Lima, said Jesse R. Peterson, chief legalization
officer in Philadelphia, 20 miles northeast of here.
   In the weeks before the deadline, some applicants traveled by
taxi from New York City, Peterson said. One arrived in a Mercedes
equipped with a car phone.
   ``I didn't know there was so much money in farm work,'' Peterson
joked.
   Under the first phase of the immigrant legalization program that
ended May 4, temporary residency was granted to more than 1.7
million illegal aliens who proved continuous residency in the United
States since Jan. 1, 1982.
   Under agricultural phase, illegal aliens had to prove they
harvested perishable crops for at least 90 days between May 1, 1985,
and May 1, 1986. Those accepted will receive temporary residency
status and eventually will be able to apply for permanent status.
   Effective today, agricultural employers now face fines up to
$10,000 per illegal alien for hiring undocumented workers.
   Many applicants provided false documentation that cost them up to
$3,000 in a desperate attempt to gain legal status, immigration
officials across the country said.
   Ten applicants were arrested Wednesday at the New Orleans INS
Office when they produced fake documents, and four others were
arrested in connection with an organization that supplied illegal
aliens with phony papers, INS officials said. In Liberal, Kan., five
people were arrested late Tuesday and early Wednesday for selling
fraudulent employment letters to illegal aliens.
   More than half the applications under the program, or about
500,000, have come from California, followed by Florida with about
10 percent and Texas with about 8 percent, officials said.
Significant numbers were filed in the Northwest, Arizona and New
York.
   At the Lima office, applicants from around the globe sat for
hours, clutching paperwork and awaiting a chance to see an INS
officer.
   Many spoke in their native tongues. One man wore a turban, others
sported cowboy or baseball hats.
   By 7:30 p.m., about 125 people had met with INS officers, with
100 more to go before midnight and beyond, Peterson said.
   ``We'll take anyone in line at midnight,'' he said.
   Mirza said he qualified for amnesty by picking grapes and
cherries in California.
   ``Since (I was a) child, I have dream to come to New York. Here,
good money,'' he said. Mirza said he came to New York in 1984 via
Greece, the Caribbean island of Bimini and an illegal boat landing
in Miami.
   Hardev Singh, a 45-year-old man from India, said through an
interpreter that he paid $600 to hide in the back of a truck from
Mexico to Los Angeles to escape political strife and unemployment.
   For Jose Villagomez, a 36-year-old mushroom worker in nearby
Kennett Square, winning residency status and thus keeping his job
was a matter of life and death for his impoverished wife and four
children back in Mexico.
   Villagomez, who speaks only Spanish, said he sends some of the
money he makes to his family.
   ``If I don't they'll die of hunger,'' he said.
</TEXT>
