<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Pakistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0482,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Pakistani Diplomats Accused Of Spying, Expelled</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Pakistani officials leave,
identity of Indian contact. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Pakistani military attache and a
Pakistani Embassy staffer left for home today after the government
accused them of spying and ordered them expelled, news reports and
officials said.
   Brig. Z.I. Abbasi and a senior embassy clerk, Mohammad Ashraf
Khatib, were arrested Wednesday night while accepting a highly
sensitive Indian defense document, External Affairs Minister P.V.
Narasimha Rao told Parliament.
   Indian officials refused to describe the nature of the document
but said the two men paid $3,500 to an Indian who handed it to them
in a New Delhi hotel. All three were arrested, but the Pakistanis
were released because of their diplomatic status.
   The United News of India news agency said Abbasi and Khatib left
New Delhi for Islamabad by plane.
   The news agency said Pakistani Ambassador Niaz A. Naik expressed
regret over the incident when he was summoned by Foreign Secretary
K.P.S. Menon.
   A spokesman at the Pakistan Embassy in New Delhi declined to
comment on the matter.
   The Press Trust of India identified the arrested Indian as a
local lawyer, Subhash Chandra Dutt. Dutt appeared before a city
magistrate today and was ordered held in police custody until Dec.
14 pending investigation, the news agency said.
   Under Indian law, people can be held for 90 days without charge.
   Rao told Parliament investigations could be hampered if any
details of the case were released.
   India and Pakistan have fought three wars since gaining
independence from Britain in 1947. Both countries have massed tens
of thousands of troops along their 970-mile border.
</TEXT>
