<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SavageJob 1stLd-Writethru a0555 12-01 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Savage Job, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0555,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fauntroy Denies Violating House Rules In Hiring Colleague's Son</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs graf 2, Thomas John, to include Fauntroy's first name,
party</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The District of Columbia's non-voting House
delegate says he did not violate any of the chamber's rules when he
hired a colleague's son while the son maintained a legal residence
in Chicago and waged an unsuccessful campaign for the Illinois state
legislature.
   Thomas John Savage, son of Rep. Gus Savage, D-Ill., received
$21,398 while employed on Democrat Walter F. Fauntroy's staff from
September 1987 to June 1988, according to House payroll records. The
younger Savage took six weeks' leave last February and March to
campaign for the Illinois legislature.
   Savage's hiring was reported Wednesday by The Associated Press.
Fauntroy did not return a reporter's repeated phone messages last
week, Monday and Tuesday. The younger Savage also did not return
several phone calls.
   In today's editions of the Washington Post, Fauntroy said Savage
lived with his father in Washington and showed up for work at the
Capitol every day while drawing a congressional salary, with the
exception of the six weeks he took off to challenge Illinois state
Rep. Nelson Rice, a Democrat.
   Rice and other sources, however, told the AP Savage had been in
Chicago during the time he was on Fauntroy's payroll.
   Thomas Savage told the AP he was in Washington full time,
``except for a couple of weekends,'' during the period in question.
   Thomas Savage signed a statement swearing he was a resident of
the Illinois district for the required period of time when he filed
for the legislative contest, according to Illinois election
documents.
   According to an ethics guide for members of Congress prepared by
the House Committee on Standards of Official Conduct, House staff
employees can be paid only for services performed in Washington or
in the state or district that the member _ in this case, Fauntroy _
represents.
   Fauntroy said the younger Savage ``didn't have to come in'' all
the time.
   ``We had a desk here for him,'' the delegate told the Post.
``Sometimes he worked out of my subcommittee office and at times he
used the full committee phones.''
   According to Fauntroy, Savage was hired as a Midwest regional
coordinator to drum up grass-roots support to pressure members of
Congress to vote for the D.C. statehood bill. Savage had no direct
contact with members of Congress or their staffs, Fauntroy said, nor
did he become involved with D.C.-based statehood activists.
   Arrington Dixon, chairman of the D.C. Statehood Compact
Commission, and Josephine Butler, head of the D.C. Statehood
Commission, said Wednesday they had never heard of or met Savage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
