<HEAD>Bush Appointment Watch Focuses on Defense Job</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 5 grafs with Bush's Tower comments, picking up
in 5th graf pvs, ``No. All</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush maintains that
``all is tranquil'' among his campaign staff despite reports of
warring opinions on whether to name former Sen. John Tower of Texas
as secretary of defense.
   ``We're not going to do everything in a great rush. We're trying
to be prudent and do the proper work required to back up
appointments at all levels,'' Bush said today.
   ``Any time there seems to be stories that may be hurtful to
somebody it concerns me no matter who it is. Senator Tower's a
friend of mine but he knows that the process takes a while to go
forward.''
   A day earlier, Bush had told reporters ``Stay tuned,'' when asked
about Tower, who still is considered the likely choice for the top
Pentagon job.
   Asked then if there were indeed a raging battle in his staff over
the prudence of naming Tower, former chairman of the Senate Armed
Services Committee, Bush laughed.
   ``No. All is tranquil. There's a thousand and one points of light
out there,'' he said in a play on an obtuse quotation he used often
in his campaign to describe the many facets of society.
   Denying any delay in filling that job, he said, ``I'm going to
stay on my schedule, make these decisions in my own time, thorough
decisions.''
   Sources close to the transition say part of the delay in the
decision on Tower results from an attempt to find a complementary
person to fill the No. 2 Pentagon spot.
   Among others mentioned for defense secretary are Paul O'Neill,
chairman of Alcoa, and Norman Augustine of Martin Marietta.
   In other transition developments:
   _A coalition of some 30 environmental groups met with Bush on
Wednesday and said he asked them for personnel recommendations for
the departments that deal with environmental matters. They gave him
a list of some 40 people.
   _Texas State Rep. Terral Smith, chairman of the state House
Natural Resources Committee, said he was heading to Washington on
Wednesday to talk to Bush about heading the Environmental Protection
Agency.
   Also being talked about for the post is former Michigan Gov.
William Milliken, whose wife, however, said her husband has not
heard from Bush's transition team. Other EPA candidates include Mike
Deland, regional administrator in Boston, and Francis Blake, former
general counsel to the regulatory relief task force and also
formerly EPA's general counsel.
   _Transition sources said former Transportation Secretary
Elizabeth Dole, wife of Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole, is a
contender for United Nations ambassador.
   _To head the Interior Department, former House Minority Leader
John Rhodes of Arizona is being touted by supporters. He is a
longtime friend of Bush and an intense lobbying effort on his behalf
is being led by political consultant Jay Smith, his former press
secretary. Sen. Dan Evans, R-Wash., is also mentioned as a serious
contender for the top job at Interior.
   Another contender is former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, who
headed President Reagan's Commission on Americans Outdoors.
   _For transportation secretary, word is that Samuel K. Skinner, a
longtime Bush supporter in Illinois and now the chairman of the
Regional Transportation Authority in the Chicago area, has emerged
as the leading contender.
   Skinner met in Washington on Tuesday with members of Bush's
transition team, a source said. Newly-elected Sen. Connie Mack,
R-Fla., said Wednesday that he has recommended Florida's
transportation secretary, Kaye Henderson, to head Bush's
Transportation Department.
   Another possible candidate, Rep. Lynn Martin, R-Ill., said she
really wants to become chairman of the House Republican Conference.
House GOP members will vote on that job Dec. 5.
   _Former Rep. Thomas Loeffler of Texas, one of Bush's top campaign
supporters, is a leading contender for energy secretary. Another
name recently emerging is Charles Imbrecht, chairman of the
California Energy Commission and a big booster of alternate fuels.
Evans also is a contender for this post.
</TEXT>
