<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1031EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-BoeingCrash     12-01 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Boeing Crash,0743</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Recommend Prosecution In 1985 Jumbo Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today sought criminal charges against
employees of Boeing Co., Japan Air Lines and the Transport Ministry
after a three-year investigation into the cause of the world's worst
single-plane crash.
   Police said the crash, in which 520 people died, was caused by
the professional negligence of 20 people, including four Boeing
employees, 12 Japan Air Lines workers and four employees of the
ministry of transport.
   The people accused of negligence were responsible for aircraft
repairs, maintenance and inspection.
   It was the first time that criminal charges arising from a plane
crash investigation have been sought against officials of the
Transport Ministry, which is responsible for aviation safety.
   Boeing, the Seattle-based aircraft manufacturer, said in a
statement it believed the accident did not involve a criminal act.
   ``Boeing does not believe that criminal acts were committed by
anyone and hopes that the district prosecutor's office also will
conclude that there was no criminal conduct,'' the company said.
   Gunma Prefectural Police handed results of the probe to the
Maebashi District Prosecutor's Office, which will decide whether to
press charges for negligence, which is an offense under Japanese
criminal law.
   The police said they were unable to question the four Boeing
employees.
   But they said documents confiscated from Japan Air Lines provided
enough evidence to substantiate their involvement. The four
reportedly supervised a repair of the aircraft in 1978 that was
performed improperly.
   Boeing sources said that police already have names of people who
performed the repairs, but Boeing employees have rejected repeated
police requests for questioning.
   The Boeing 747 with 524 people aboard crashed into a mountain
during a flight from Tokyo to Osaka on Aug. 12, 1985, killing all
but four on board.
   The police action highlights the different legal customs
regarding air accidents and corporate criminal liability in Japan
and the United States.
   Japan is one of a few countries where criminal charges are sought
against individuals responsible for airplane accidents, said Hiroshi
Itakura, criminal law professor at Nihon University in Tokyo.
   In the United States, individuals involved in an airplane
accident are usually granted criminal immunity in exchange for
cooperating in investigations into the cause of an accident, Itakura
said.
   ``The most important thing in an accident like this is to
pinpoint the cause of the accident rather than to prosecute
individuals,'' he said. ``But unlike the United States, under
Japanese criminal law corporations cannot be charged for wrongdoing.
   ``In order to disclose causes of accidents, police have to seek
criminal charges against individuals,'' he said.
   Susumu Yamachi, president of Japan Air Lines, said his company
would take the matter seriously and continue its efforts to prevent
the recurrence of such an tragic accident.
   Boeing rejected Japanese allegations that the company had
hindered the investigation, saying that it had cooperated with
Japanese authorities.
   Boeing sources said the company planned to respond to the police
inquiry, but was unlikely to allow Japanese police to question
individual employees.
   The airplane maker has disclosed that repairs it performed on the
rear bulkhead, the metal partition that protects the pressurized
cabin, of the aircraft after a minor accident in 1978 were faulty.
   The aircraft skidded on its tail during a rough landing in 1978
at Osaka International Airport, damaging its tail section, and
underwent major repairs, according to JAL.
   A government report issued in 1987 concluded that improper
repairs had accelerated metal fatigue, which caused the bulkhead to
burst, blowing off part of the plane's tail fin and sending the
jumbo jet out of control.
   The report accused the Boeing, JAL, and Transport Ministry
personnel of faulty repairs and inadequate inspection.
   Police said the accident could have been avoided if Boeing had
performed the repairs properly, if Japan Air Lines had checked the
repairs adequately, and if the Transport Ministry had inspected the
aircraft properly.
   A group of relatives of passengers who died in the crash have
presented signatures of 34,120 people to the Trasnport Ministry
requesting a criminal prosecution against JAL and Boeing.
   JAL said about 70 percent of compensation negotiations have been
settled. The company and Boeing have agreed to share the cost of
compensation to the victims' families and the four survivors of the
crash, according to JAL.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
