<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Demjanjuk 1stLd-Writethru a0533 12-01 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Demjanjuk, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0533,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Assailant Throws Acid at Demjanjuk Attorney</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with bystander injured, details. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Holocaust survivor threw acid in the face of
an Israeli attorney for Nazi war criminal John Demjanjuk during a
funeral today for another Demjanjuk lawyer who died in an apparent
suicide.
   The attack on attorney Yoram Sheftel injured one of his eyes,
police and a hospital spokesman said. A woman standing nearby
suffered a minor eye injury from the splashed acid, police said.
   Police said they detained the assailant, a 70-year-old survivor
of the Nazi Holocaust, immediately after the attack, which occurred
at the Sanhedria Cemetery during the funeral for Demjanjuk lawyer
Dov Eitan.
   Reporters who covered the 14-month trial of Demjanjuk said the
assailant, whose name was not released, was a frequent spectator at
the proceedings.
   The assailant was seen being dragged away, covering his face with
his hands. The Itim news agency quoted an unidentified witness as
saying the assailant told Sheftel ``Eitan died because of you.'' The
man then took a bottle out of his pocket and threw the acid.
   Sheftel was rushed to Bikur Holim Hospital, where doctors washed
the eye. His eye had ``slightly blurred vision and was shut,'' said
hospital spokesman Yehuda Kingslinger.
   Eitan, a 53-year-old former judge, died Tuesday in a fall from a
15th floor hotel window in Jerusalem. Police said the death was a
suicide.
   The death has delayed Demjanjuk's appeal of a death sentence to
Israel's Supreme Court for six months. The appeal had been scheduled
to begin Dec. 5.
   Demjanjuk, a 68-year-old retired autoworker from Cleveland, Ohio,
was sentenced in April for committing crimes against humanity and
the Jewish people as an operator of gas chambers at Treblinka Death
Camp in Poland, where 850,000 Jews perished during World War II.
   Sheftel was sent for further treatment to a special eye unit at
Jerusalem's Hadassah Hospital, Kingslinger and officials at Hadassah
said.
   The woman injured in the attack was identified as Edna Shabtai of
Tel Aviv, said Elhanan Pels, spokesman for Shaarei Tzedek Hospital.
Israel radio said she was a writer. Pels said her eye was cleaned
and covered with a patch and that she was discharged from the
hospital.
</TEXT>
