<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Snowmobilers     12-01 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Snowmobilers,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survivor of Mountain Ordeal Walks to Safety After Friend Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRANBY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man trapped in the Never Summer Mountains
for five days walked to safety three days after his snowmobiling
companion died of an apparent heart attack.
   Jim Edson, 38, stumbled onto a logging road Wednesday morning
where he was picked up by a truck driver. He and Ray Owens, 65, had
traveled to the snow-whipped mountains 50 miles northwest of Denver
last Friday on an afternoon snowmobile outing.
   Owens died Sunday, and Edson waited two more days in vain to be
rescued before walking out on his own.
   In recounting the ordeal from a hospital bed in Granby, Edson
said the men's snowmobiles became mired the day they left in a
high-country gulch 16 miles northwest of Grand Lake.
   ``When it became obvious the weather was not going to clear up
and they weren't coming after us, I decided to go out the way we
came,'' Edson said.
   Heavy winds had drifted snow over their tracks, and it took Edson
nearly five hours to walk about two miles through snow up to 2 feet
deep before he came to the logging road.
   Edson's face and hands were black from sitting by a campfire in
subzero weather. On his way out, Edson found snowmobile tracks
indicating searchers had not been more than two miles from his
campfire.
   Tony Winter, the logging truck driver, later led searchers to the
spot where he found Edson, and the searchers followed Edson's tracks
back to his camp and recovered Owens' body.
   Freezing winds sent wind-chill factors to minus 30 degrees
Fahrenheit in the area and blinding white-outs plagued would-be
rescuers during the search.
   They had called off their ground search Tuesday night, after
three days of searching.
   Edson said when they tried to free their machines Friday
afternoon, ``that was when Ray had his first heart attack. He was
feeling pretty poorly so we rested.''
   Although they had brought along trail mix, cheese, crackers and
fruit for their afternoon outing, neither man had any matches.
   Edson said they soaked a piece of cardboard in gasoline from a
snowmobile, and cranked an engine, using a sparkplug to light the
cardboard.
   ``The first night or two, when Ray was still alive, we traded
turns taking care of the fire. After he died, I'd build the fire up
and the smoke would blow in my face and choke me when it was getting
low and I'd wake up again.''
   Before he died Sunday, Owens wanted to try again to get out.
   ``He said, `Let's go real slow,' but we didn't get more than 15
feet from the camp and he decided he wasn't going,'' Edson said.
   Owens collapsed about noon Sunday and died.
   After Owens' death, Edson decided to ``stay where we were at, and
wait to be rescued.'' At one point he heard a plane overhead, but
the weather was too bad for the pilot to see them, even with a smoky
fire.
   ``I'm tired and I'm thirsty but I feel fine,'' Edson said
Wednesday night. ``I'm thankful for all the people who looked for
us, and I'm sorry to have put them to so much trouble.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881201-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1109EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i BC-BhuttoProfile     12-01 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bhutto Profile,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Leader Wins Effort To Restore Family Name, Pakistani Democracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Benazir Bhutto's selection as prime
minister triumphantly ended an 11-year effort to restore her family
name and Pakistani democracy.
   At 35, she also becomes one of the world's youngest heads of
government and the first woman prime minister to lead a Moslem
nation in modern times.
   Ms. Bhutto, who was educated at Harvard and Oxford, inherits the
political mantle of her father, the late Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali
Bhutto, who was ousted by Gen. Mohammed Zia ul-Haq in a 1977 coup
and hanged two years later.
   Zia's death in an Aug. 17 plane crash made Ms. Bhutto, who had
pledged to restore democracy, the nation's only nationally
recognized political leader.
   Although a daughter of affluence, Ms. Bhutto's appeal lies mainly
among the poor masses of this country's 107 million people. They are
the strength of her left-leaning Pakistan People's Party, which
captured the most seats in the Nov. 16 National Assembly elections.
   Ms. Bhutto drew massive, adoring crowds during her campaign for
the country's first free elections since her father's death.
   Mindful of Moslem and local custom, she always is clad in
traditional clothes with a scarf draped over her head.
   The poised and articulate leader, who speaks English fluently,
shocked her Western friendsby consenting to an arranged marriage
last December with Karachi businessman Asif Ali Zardari.
   Ms. Bhutto, who has kept her maiden name, was groomed for
politics by her doting father as the eldest of his four children. He
sent her to study government and politics at Harvard in the United
States then at Oxford.
   It was at the British university that she tasted her first
political success when she was elected president of the prestigious
Oxford Union debating society in 1976.
   The prime minister's post is Ms. Bhutto first paying job. Her
only previous employment began in early 1977 as a non-paid trainee
in the Foreign Ministry.
   It was short-lived, however, as Zia toppled her father's
government a few months later on the pretext that elections that
year were rigged.
   Bhutto was hanged in 1979 after his conviction for helping plot
the murder of a political foe, a charge his family has denied.
   Despite years of detention and foreign exile during Zia's
authoritarian rule, Ms. Bhutto and her mother, Nusrat, kept the
party alive as Zia's disenfranchised opposition.
   Ms. Bhutto's party critics claim she has inherited her father's
domineering ego but has renounced his socialist ideals.
   Her supporters say that with Zia gone, she is Pakistan's only
nationally recognized political leader and a unifying force in the
country's volatile ethnic mosaic.
   Her party commands 105 votes in the 237-seat National Assembly,
and Ms. Bhutto says she has enough support from independents and
minor parties to command a majority.
   Ms. Bhutto espouses prosperity for the poor but has appeased the
business community with promises of a market-oriented economy, and
the military by pledging to continue Zia's staunch backing with the
United States of Moslem anti-communist rebels in neighboring
Afghanistan.
   She started her election campaign in late October, following the
Sept. 21 birth of her first child, a son named Bilawal.
   Ms. Bhutto rarely has appeared with her husband in public and has
not yet allowed public photographs of their baby.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881201-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1118EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ConstructionExplosion     12-01 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Construction Explosion,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Seek Clues In Blast That Killed Six Firefighters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ammonium nitrate that exploded during an
arson fire and killed six firemen had been mixed with other
compounds that made it far more explosive than usual, police say.
   A reward for information on the arsonists has reached $35,000
with an anonymous donor's offer of $25,000, and donations are
pouring in for the victims' families, city officials said.
   Firefighters from across the nation and Canada are expected at a
memorial service.
   Officials initially thought that only ammonium nitrate,
considered one of the milder and more stable explosives, had been
stored in two trailers that blew up early Tuesday at a highway
construction site.
   But the ammonium nitrate had been mixed with diesel fuel, pink
dye and powdered aluminum to form ``Maynes mix,'' a blasting agent
usually detonated by a small amount of dynamite, police said.
   The mixture explains why the blasts were powerful enough to kill
the firefighters, demolish two firetrucks and create a shock wave
that broke windows up to 10 miles away and was heard up to 40 miles
away.
   ``All it requires is a heat source'' to detonate, said police
Sgt. Gregory Mills.
   Mills said there were no significant developments Wednesday in
the arson investigation.
   Officials announced a $35,000 reward for information on suspects
in the fire. Sandy Berkley, wife of Mayor Richard Berkley who is on
a trade mission in the Far East, said a donor who wishes to remain
anonymous had given $25,000 toward the reward fund. An additional
$5,000 came from the Heavy Equipment Construction Workers and $5,000
from the Arson Hotline.
   Donations also have been pouring into Union Bank in Kansas City,
where a fund has been established to help the victims' families,
bank spokesman Carl Eichenberger said.
   ``Everyone has been so extremely helpful in trying to donate. All
they're concerned about is the families,'' Eichenberger said. He
said the total amount of money donated was not available Wednesday.
   A public memorial service for the six firefighters is scheduled
Saturday at Arrowhead Stadium and firefighters from almost every
state, including New York, California, Texas and Washington, have
called to ask about the ceremony. Even a fire department in Canada
said firefighters plan to attend, said Harold M. Knabe, a Fire
Department spokesman.
   The six firefighters had been warned by a dispatcher there could
be explosives at the scene of a fire that police believe was started
by an arsonist, according to transcripts of conversations with
dispatchers. But fire officials said the six apparently saw no signs
at the site indicating that explosives were stored in the trailers.
   The City Council on Wednesday discussed drafting tougher laws
regarding the regulation of explosives.
   The president of the International Association of Fire Fighters,
Alfred K. Whitehead, called for a congressional investigation into
the construction site explosion and what he called ``a tragic
addition to the growing list of hazardous material accidents.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881201-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1122EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest 3rdLd-Writethru   12-01 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0534,0708</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>28 Reported Dead In Ethnic Unrest; Kremlin Leaders Meeting On Issue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Kremlin urging calm,
announcing plans for meeting regional officials. Pickup 8th graf
pvs, ``Azerbaijan and...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party newspaper Pravda today said 28
people have been killed in two weeks ofethnic violence in the
republics of Armenia and Azerbaijan. Kremlin leaders issued an
urgent appeal for calm.
   Official reports said thousands of people were fleeing the unrest.
   ``We are losing our people,'' Interior Ministry spokesman B.
Mikhailov was quoted as saying in Pravda.
   The situation in the southern region remained tense, with mass
meetings in many towns in Azerbaijan despite the presence of Soviet
troops, tanks and a strict curfew, Azerbaijan Interior Minister A.
Mamedov said.
   Authorities have confiscated homemade pistols, sawed-off rifles
and explosives from young people in Armenia and Azerbaijan,
Mikhailov said.
   He said said the death toll includes Armenians, Azerbaijanis, a
Russian, a Byelorussian and a Ukrainian.
   In Moscow, at the end of a three-day conference of the Supreme
Soviet, the Kremlin leadership announced plans for the parliament's
Presidium, the highest state executive body, to hold a meeting of
party, state and social organizations with national deputies from
Armenia, Azerbaijan and the disputed Nagorno-Karabakh region.
   ``The Supreme Soviet appeals to workers of Armenia and Azerbaijan
to display wisdom and restraint,'' said a directive signed by
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev that called for the meeting.
   Azerbaijan and Armenia, two southern Soviet republics, are locked
in a bitter dispute for control of the Nagorno-Karabakh region. The
area is part of Azerbaijan, but its predominantly Armenian
population has been agitating since February for annexation by
Armenia.
   Both Azerbaijan and the Kremlin have rejected annexation.
   Arkady Volsky, the Kremlin's special representative in Armenia
and Azerbaijan, told the Supreme Soviet just before it adjourned
that in Azerbaijan, ``nothing was done to eliminate the tension
right away.''
   ``The situation is boiling in both republics,'' Volsky said. ``We
are appealing to the peoples of Armenia and Azerbaijan, it is time
to stop.''
   In Baku, the capital of Azerbaijan, Pravda correspondents
reported activists wearing red headbands gathered around bonfires on
the streets at night, engaged in heated discussion of the violence.
   Many cities in the region are under military rule and strict
curfews as a result of the unrest between Armenians and Azerbaijanis.
   Official media in Baku and in the Armenian capital, Yerevan, said
thousands of refugees were streaming across the border to their
respective ethnic homelands.
   The official Armenian news agency Armenpress said the latest
round of killings began Nov. 22 and included a Moslem mullah.
   Leon Azruyan, the night editor in charge of Armenpress, said in a
telephone interview Wednesday that the Azerbaijani mullah fired into
a meeting of Armenians in the city of Kalinino in northern Armenia
last week, ``but they threw stones at him. One hit him in the head
and killed him.''
   He said other deaths occurred in the cities of Kirovakan,
Krasnoselsk and Spitak in northern Armenia but that there was no
detailed information on how many died in each city or the
circumstances.
   Earlier, four soldiers were killed protecting Armenian residents
of the Azerbaijani city of Kirovabad, and soldiers shot and killed
three civilians there for violating curfew. Violence also was
reported in Nakhichevan, an Azerbaijani enclave between Armenia and
the Iranian border.
   The dispute over Nagorno-Karabakh began in February. Mass
demonstrations broke out, and at the end of February ethnic rioting
in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait killed at least 32 people.
   The latest unrest began in mid-November.
   Azerbaijanis accused Armenia of sending settlers into
Nagorno-Karabakh to pad the Armenian majority there, of forcing
Azerbaijanis out of work, and refusing them food and medical
supplies.
   Official Yerevan radio, in a report monitored in London by the
British Broadcasting Corp., said more than 20,000 ethnic Armenian
refugees from Azerbaijan had arrived since Nov. 22. It said many
arrived in Armenia without clothing, money, or documents, and in
need of medical treatment. It said empty houses had been
requisitioned to shelter them.
</TEXT>
