<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Joy     12-01 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Joy,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Centralia Editor and Publisher Was 60</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CENTRALIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Verne Joy, editor and publisher of
the Centralia Evening and Sunday Sentinel since 1964, died today
after a brief illness. He was 60.
   Joy, who died at Barnes Hospital in St. Louis, was the fourth
generation of the Joy family to serve as editor and publisher of the
126-year-old newspaper in southern Illinois.
   Born in Centralia, Joy attended Hill School in Pottstown, Pa. He
was a 1950 graduate of Cornell University and served two years with
the U.S. Army in Korea.
   Following his Korean duty, Joy served 1{ years as an intern at
the Rockford Evening News and six months at Illinois Daily Newspaper
Markets in Springfield.
   He returned to Centralia in 1955 to work under his grandfather,
editor and publisher Verne E. Joy, and also played a key role in the
building of the city's Carillon Bell Tower and adjoining Tower Park.
   Survivors include his wife, Judith, and son, Thomas Frazier Joy,
both of Centralia.
</TEXT>
