<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HominyPolice     12-01 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hominy Police,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Police Chief Charged With Nepotism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOMINY, Okla (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A misdemeanor charge of nepotism is the only
charge that came out of an investigation of the town's former police
chief, a black man who charged racial bias after he was fired amid
allegations of misconduct.
   The nepotism charge was filed against former chief Charles
Crawford, 45, who had been accused of sexually harassing female
employees.
   Crawford is accused of appointing a sister-in-law as a temporary
police department employee Sept. 7. He was fired Oct. 6, and his
sister-in-law no longer works in the department.
   District Attorney Larry Stuart said Tuesday that state law
prohibits an elected official from appointing or hiring any person
related to him by marriage or blood within the third degree. The
charge carries a fine of between $100 and $1,000 and forfeiture of
office.
   Allegations against Crawford had included sexual involvement with
dispatchers and juveniles, sexual harassment of other female
employees, preferential treatment for some residents and harsh
handling of others. One former dispatcher has filed a paternity suit
against him.
   Crawford said city officials who opposed having a black chief
conspired to oust him, using allegations that he had affairs with
white police dispatchers to raise the ire of the all-white City
Council. The town of 3,000 people has about 150 blacks.
   Stuart issued a statement saying the nearly two-month
investigation by his office and the Oklahoma State Bureau of
Investigation ``failed to produce substantiated evidence, or victims
who desired to pursue criminal charges.''
   He said matters alleged to have occurred more than three years
ago were not investigated because the statute of limitations had
expired.
   Stuart said he expected no other charges against Crawford.
   Crawford and the city have been named in a $4.4 million civil
rights lawsuit in federal court that alleges the former lawman
sexually harassed employees and strong-armed residents to collect
merchants' debts.
</TEXT>
