<DOCNO> AP881201-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1154EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChelseaSchools     12-01 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chelsea Schools,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BU Takeover Offers New Hope, City Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chelsea school officials are close to accepting
Boston University's proposal to manage their beleaguered public
schools, but opponents vow to continue their legal challenges.
   ``I think it presents a new hope for the community,'' John
Zimini, president of the Chelsea Board of Aldermen, said Wednesday,
the day after school committee officials tentatively backed the plan
by a 5-2 vote.
   Officials said they expect to have a contract within the next few
weeks.
   The unprecedented offer has been under negotiation for three
years. Chelsea's 3,400-student district has the highest dropout rate
in the state and has not built a school since 1923.
   But union lawyers say public officials are willing to cede too
much power to the university and they will continue their legal
challenge to the plan despite failing to get an injunction to stop
Tuesday's vote.
   ``It's not over yet,'' said Paul Devlin, president of the
Massachusetts Federation of Teachers.
   The unions are challenging the plan on the grounds it is against
state law to put a tax-funded institution under private management.
   University officials maintain they will not be taking the public
schools private but will simply be managers who have to answer to
the School Committee.
   ``I think that it takes an awful lot of courage on the part of
the city to say, `Hey, look we've tried our best, the money's just
not there,''' Zimini said. ``Unfortunately in our society any kind
of change is always a fear factor.''
   The working-class town on Boston Harbor, with its influx of
Hispanic and Southeast Asian immigrants, has been strained
financially by a small tax base, elderly population and a 1980 state
tax-limiting law.
   Zimini said he cannot predict how aldermen will vote but believes
the contract will be approved. The pact also requires enabling
legislation by state lawmakers.
   The university proposes to revamp the curricula, build new
schools, provide mothers and pregnant teen-agers with counseling on
nutrition and child-rearing, tailor learning plans to individual
students and set up after-school programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
