<DOCNO> AP881201-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1202EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugSpelling     12-01 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Spelling,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Acquitted On Drug Charge Because of Misspelling in Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HASTINGS, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has been acquitted of a charge of
manufacturing and distributing a so-called designer drug known as
``ecstasy'' because the drug's lengthy scientific name was
misspelled in state law.
   David Burling, 19, of Kenesaw, was charged with making and
selling methylenedioxymethamphetamine, more commonly known as MDMA
or ``ecstasy.''
   Designer drugs are formulated to have the effect of an illegal
drug without being specifically outlawed.
   Adams County District Judge Bernard Sprague ruled Tuesday that
Burling did not violate the law since he did not possess the drug
named in the state statute.
   Adams County Attorney James Hatheway argued that the discrepency
was a typographical error and that the intent of the law was to make
MDMA illegal.
   Burling's attorney, Jim Smith of Hastings, said the misspelling
was significant but other factors contributed to Burling's
acquittal. He said Hatheway failed to prove the drug Burling
possessed was illegal.
   Hatheway said he was disappointed in the verdict but does not
plan to appeal. He said he discovered the spelling error in June and
notified the state Legislature.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
