<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1202EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChessMates     12-01 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chess Mates,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newlywed Chess Mates Visit New York</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top Soviet chess player Elena Akhmilovskaya and
her new husband, John Donaldson, captain of the U.S. men's chess
team, said today they hope the Soviets will allow Akhmilovskaya's
daughter to join them soon in the United States.
   Speaking on ``CBS This Morning,'' Akhmilovskaya, who received an
immigrant visa Tuesday, said that she hoped the spirit of glasnost,
or openness, would carry over and that the Soviet authorities ``let
her join me very, very soon.''
   The couple secretly wed Friday during the Chess Olympiad in
Greece. Akhmilovskaya's 7-year-old daughter lives in Soviet Georgia.
   Donaldson said he met Akhmilovskaya during a qualification
tournament for the women's world championship in Cuba in 1985.
Donaldson was trainer for the U.S. women's team and Akhmilovskaya
was playing for the Soviets.
   Donaldson said they did not necessarily plan to elope in Greece,
but that ``I think it was something in the back of each of our minds.
   ``We hadn't seen each other since 1986 in Dubai, when they had
the previous chess tournament in the (United Arab) emirates. So we
knew that there was a good chance that it might be our only
opportunity,'' the 31-year-old Donaldson said.
   He said they wrote to each other during their separation but ``we
had to be a little circumspect because it wasn't good to draw
attention to it (the relationship).''
   Akhmilovskaya, who speaks broken English, said she will ``try to
speak with Mr. Gorbachev'' when he visits New York next Tuesday for
a meeting with President Reagan and President-elect George Bush.
   Donaldson said he hopes authorities will be sympathetic to their
plight to get his wife and her daughter reunited.
   ``I think that they understand that sometimes these things
happen,'' Donaldson said.
   The couple plans to stay in the New York area until Gorbachev's
visit. They plan to settle eventualy in Seattle, Donaldson's home,
where they will work for Biweekly Chess magazine.
</TEXT>
