<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ScientistControversy     12-01 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scientist Controversy,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Officials Cut Off Grants to Two Harvard Scientists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials have cut off funds to two Harvard
University-affiliated scientists involved in controversial research
at the Massachusetts Eye and Ear Infirmary.
   National Institutes of Health officials told The Boston Globe the
decision to cut off the funds did not indicate wrongdoing by the
scientists. But they said investigators were in Boston on Wednesday
inspecting hospital records to see if patients were hurt or grant
money was misused.
   Officials of the NIH terminated the last two years of funds for a
five-year, $850,000 grant to Sheffer C.G. Tseng, a former Harvard
scientist now at the University of Miami.
   The two scientists have been the focus of growing attention since
October, when Tseng was reported to have tested an experimental eye
drug on hundreds of Massachusetts Eye and Ear patients between 1984
and 1986 while helping to organize, and profiting from, a company
that made the drug, which has proven largely ineffective.
   NIH officials also suspended consideration of a $191,000 grant
application submitted by Tseng's Harvard supervisor, associate
professor Kenneth R. Kenyon, and demanded Kenyon be replaced as
director of an NIH-funded fellowship program at the Eye Research
Institute, a private organization associated with the eye and ear
hospital.

</TEXT>
