<2ND_LINE>AM-Fake Doctor,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police: Impostor Doctor Roamed Hospital Halls For Weeks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An impostor wearing a lab coat, surgical gloves and
stethoscope wandered through hospital halls for weeks, sat in on
medical school classes and was arrested after asking to examine a
patient, police say.
   Jonathan Ashley Battle, 23, who has no medical degree, spent at
least three weeks at Jackson Memorial Hospital and had acquired 21
keys to doctors offices, Metro-Dade police say.
   ``They were keys even security didn't have access to,'' said
Robert NeeDelman, an officer assigned to the hospital. ``This guy is
really something else.''
   Police were investigating whether Battle, arrested Nov. 20 and
charged with burglary and theft, ever actually examined patients
during his hospital rounds.
   A nurse became suspicious of Battle when he entered a
labor-delivery scrub room wearing gloves from a neighboring
hospital. Questioned about what he was doing, Battle gave the name
of a patient he planned to examine. After the patient's name didn't
show up in hospital records, the nurse called security.
   Battle had created his own University of Miami medical school
photo ID card identifying him as a doctor, NeeDelman said.
   Battle was scheduled to be arraigned Dec. 12 on charges of
burglary, a second-degree felony, and petty theft, a misdemeanor.
   He can't be charged with impersonating a doctor because no
statute exists, said Leslie Rothenberg, assistant state attorney in
the felony screening unit.
</TEXT>
