<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Landfill Celebration,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents Celebrate Closing Of Landfill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents popped champagne corks and
cut a cake as they celebrated the closing of a nearby landfill that
fouled the air and lured thousands of seagulls into the area.
   About 50 residents on Wednesday applauded from across the street
as they watched a city worker close the gate for the final time.
   ``We're celebrating. The seagulls will finally leave,'' said
David E. Gann.
   The 137-acre landfill opened 14 years ago and received about
1,500 tons of garbage daily. Garbage is piled more than 100 feet
high.
   ``It's long overdue. The odor is terrible,'' said Regan Askwith.
   Although the dump is now closed, some residents fear groundwater
filtering through the dump will pollute nearby Greenfield Creek, a
tributary of the St. Johns River.
   The closing of the landfill means that Jacksonville's 3,000 tons
of garbage a day will be trucked to the city's remaining landfill on
the Northside.
</TEXT>
