<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Visas,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>France Expected to Drop Visa Requirements for Americans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France is expected to end its visa requirement for
American visitors before the end of the year, Tourism Minister
Olivier Stirn said.
   ``It is a governent decision and not just mine,'' he said on
French radio Tuesday. ``I can tell you that we think, effectively,
that before the end of the year a positive decision will be made.''
   France began requiring visas of foreign visitors previously
exempted following a September 1986 bomb wave in Paris which killed
11 people.
   Only visitors from the European Community remained exempt.
   ``Today, terrorism has been suppressed,'' Stirn said. ``Security
reigns in France.''
   Stirn said the United States envisaged doing away with visas for
French citizens as well as ``a certain number of other Europeans.''
   ``This would be a measure that would go well with the
bicentennial of the French Revolution'' being celebrated in 1989,
the minister said.
</TEXT>
