<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--CityHall-Tree     12-01 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--City Hall-Tree,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Council Votes to Erect Holiday Tree and Menorah in City Hall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Los Angeles City Council ignored its own
policy when it voted to display a ``decorated tree'' and an unlit
menorah in the City Hall lobby during the holidays.
   Council members interpreted the Christian and Jewish symbols as
secular rather than religious when they approved the display
Wednesday.
   According to council policy, only displays sponsored by city
offices and which relate to the official function of those offices
are allowed.
   Councilman Hal Bernson warned that allowing the tree and menorah
would open the door to any group seeking to put a display at City
Hall.
   Bernie Evans, a spokesman for City Councilwoman Joan Milke
Flores, said city policy prohibits such displays in the rotunda, but
not in the Main Street lobby where the tree and menorah are to be
set up Friday.
   ``It's the holiday season and it's just pretty ridiculous not to
have anything representing the holiday spirit at City Hall,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
