<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Australia-Yugoslavia 2ndLd-Writethru a0568 12-01 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Australia-Yugoslavia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0568,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yugoslavia Rejects Australian Ultimatum To Turn Over Consulate
Guard</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Yugoslavia rejecting
ultimatum, other details. Pickup 10th graf pvs, ``Yugoslav
Ambassador...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Australia said today it will close the
Yugoslav Consulate and expel its staff if authorities there don't
turn over a security guard who shot a teen-age demonstrator.
Yugoslavia rejected the demand.
   The moves were the latest in a diplomatic wrangle over the
wounding of the youth on Sunday and Yugoslavia's refusal to
apologize formally for the shooting at its consulate in Sydney.
   In a statement carried by the official Tanjug news agency in
Belgrade, the Yugoslav government said Australian officials ``failed
to undertake measures to protect our consulate'' from attackers.
   The security guard ``had no choice but shooting into the air to
warn Australian organs...that lives and security of workers in the
consulate and their families were directly imperiled,'' the
statement said.
   The statement was in response to one issued earlier by Foreign
Minister Gareth Evans saying the Australian government had
sufficient evidence to prosecute the security guard who fired the
gun.
   Evans demanded that the guard, identified as Matijas Zoran, be
handed over to police by 6 p.m. Friday or ``the Australian
government will immediately close the consulate-general.''
   About 1,500 people protested at the consulate on Sunday, Yugoslav
National Day. Police said a security guard fired on hundreds of
demonstrators when several Croatian youths began climbing the walls.
   Jospeh Tokic, 16, was shot in the throat and was in stable
condition at a Sydney hospital. Croatians are among several ethnic
groups in Yugoslavia.
   About 200,000 Yugoslavs live in Australia.
   Tanjug said the Yugoslav government referred to the demonstrators
as Ustashas, Croatian fascists who allied with Nazi Germany against
Yugoslav resistance forces during World War II.
   Yugoslav Ambassador Boris Cizelj allowed police to question the
guard after consulting with his government in Belgrade. But he
insisted the interview be conducted inside the consulate and in the
presence of the consul-general.
   He said Zoran would not leave the country until police complete
their investigation.
   The Belgrade government lodged an official protest over what it
called a lack of police protection during the demonstration.
</TEXT>
