<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FernaldLayoffs     12-01 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fernald Layoffs,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fernald Plant to Lay Off 350 Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government's Fernald
uranium-processing plant will lay off about 350 employees soon
because of decreased demand for the enriched uranium it produces,
officials announced today.
   The layoff, the second since April at the U.S. Energy
Department's Feed Materials Production Center, will include both
management and production-line employees and could begin before
Christmas, said Pete Kelley, a spokesman for the plant's operator,
Westinghouse Materials Co. of Ohio.
   Workers to be affected will be notified Dec. 9, he said.
   Kelley said the layoffs have nothing to do with a strike by 625
unionized production workers, which has idled the plant since Oct.
7. Westinghouse Materials laid off 70 employees at the government
plant in April because of declining orders for uranium and said then
that another layoff was likely later this year.
   ``They would have occurred anyway, because the production is down
substantially for this fiscal year from last,'' Kelley said.
   The plant's operating budget last year was $145 million but was
cut to $107 million this year, he said.
   Westinghouse Materials Co. said it will provide affected
employees with job counseling, asistance with resume writing,
interview skills training and a placement center.
   The plant now employs about 1,500 people. It has supplied uranium
recently for the Energy Department's Rocky Flats plant in Colorado,
the Hanford reactors in Washington state, the Savannah River plant
in South Carolina and the Oak Ridge, Tenn., nuclear complex. The
Savannah River reactors are shut down because of problems there, and
the Rocky Flats plant reportedly is under consideration for eventual
closure by the Energy Department.
   The Fernald plant, located 18 miles northwest of Cincinnati, has
been under heavy criticism in recent years. The Energy Department
recently admitted that the plant has released at least 300,000
pounds of radioactive uranium dust into the atmosphere during its 37
years of operation.
</TEXT>
