<1ST_LINE>r i PM-MafiaSweep     12-01 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mafia Sweep,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italian, U.S. Authorities Cooperate in Drug Sweep</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Italy-Mafia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALERMO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested members of the Mafia in
cities throughout Italy today as a similar sweep targeting
drug-trafficking rings took place in the United States.
   The ANSA news agency said authorities involved in operation
``Iron Tower'' began arresting people during the night in Palermo,
Bologna and Florence.
   FBI Director William S. Sessions, in a statement released in Rome
and Washington today, said drug charges have been filed against 75
people in the United States and 133 people in Italy.
   He said the arrests were under way in nine unspecified Italian
cities and in Baltimore; Buffalo, New York; Miami; Newark, New
Jersey; New York; Philadelphia; San Francisco; and Rockford, Ill.
   The Italian news agency ANSA said the people named in the Italian
arrest warrants were members of the Satola, Gambino and Inzerillo
crime families in Italy and the United States. The state-run RAI-TV
said several top Mafia figures were among those arrested.
   Italian news agencies said the drug raids resulted from an
investigation that stemmed from the ``Pizza Connection''
international drug ring that sold $1.6 billion of heroin, mostly
through pizzerias in the United States.
   A U.S. court convicted 18 people in connection with that ring and
Italian prosecutors indicted 28 people for their alleged involvement.
   ANSA and the Italian news agency AGI said the investigation that
led to today's raids was triggered by the arrest of women drug
couriers at airports in Palermo and New York two years ago.
   It said the women were paid about $7,800 for every 2.2 pounds of
heroin they smuggled from Italy to the United States inside money
belts.
   FBI agents used court-authorized wiretaps, physical surveillance
and heroin and cocaine buys to develop the evidence that led to the
arrests in Italy and the United States, Sessions said.
   He said the FBI also discovered cocaine was being sent from South
America to a laboratory 300 miles north of Madrid, Spain, to be
processed and sent to Italy. In Italy, the cocaine was then
exchanged for heroin that was smuggled into the United States. He
said the information led to arrests in Spain.
</TEXT>
