<DOCNO> AP881201-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1321EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NATO     12-01 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Defense Ministers Urge U.S. Allies to Play Greater Role</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO defense ministers Thursday urged
U.S. allies to boost defense spending, upgrade military equipment
and play a greater role in maintaining a strong Western alliance.
   The recommendations came in a ``burden-sharing'' report that
responds to criticism from U.S. congressman who argue the United
States is picking up too much of the defense tab.
   Ministers adopted the report at the start of a two-day meeting.
   The report acknowledged ``significant differences between
individual national contributions.''
   But it contended countries such as West Germany bear high social
costs because of 400,000 foreign troops stationed there.
   West German Defense Minister Rupert Scholz said the review on his
country was ``rather positive. I didn't expect it any other way.''
   U.S. critics have suggested the United States withdraw some of
its 326,000 troops stationed in Europe if the Europeans do not pay
more.
   ``As the alliance approaches its 40th anniversary, its strength
and cohesion remain as firm as ever, with continuing major
contributions being made by both the European and North American
pillars,'' the report said.
   But it noted both rich and poor countries have earmarked for
defense less and less as a percentage of total economic activity or
gross domestic product.
   Italy, Luxembourg, Norway and Spain were singled out for
maintaining or increasing slightly their levels of defense spending.
   Allocating money for defense was crucial. ``But making available
people and space, accepting limitations in personal freedom or the
quality of life, braving internal or external tensions, and
different degrees of exposure or vulnerability are by no means less
important elements of the overall burden,'' the report said.
   It estimated the United States tagged an average 5.98 percent of
its economic output to defense from 1983 to 1987. Well ahead was
Greece, which spent 6.52 percent.
   Britain devoted 5.01 percent of its GDP to defense; Turkey
averaged 4 percent, and Germany 3.2 percent.
   Others were: Belgium, 3.26 percent; Canada, 2.17 percent;
Denmark, 2.2 percent; Italy, 2.16 percent; Luxembourg, 1.18 percent;
Netherlands, 3.32 percent; Norway, 2.93 percent; Portugal, 3.22
percent; and Spain, 2.37 percent. Iceland was not included in the
table.
   All NATO's 16 nations except France and Spain are members of the
Defense Planning Committee, which approved the report.
   The report praised the Reagan administration for ``an exceptional
and sustained effort to modernize and upgrade all aspects of its
armed forces.''
   But it said the defense spending surge ``seems to have come to an
end and is likely to be followed by a period of stabilization.''
   European countries, it said, provide 90 percent of the manpower,
80 percent of combat aircraft, 70 percent of tanks and 80 percent of
artillery in the alliance.
   But it urged many European members and Canada to make bigger
contributions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
