<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Crew Thumbnails,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlantis Crewmen At a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Space Shuttle Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are brief sketches of the five
military astronauts assigned to Atlantis:
   NAVY CMDR. ROBERT L. GIBSON: Commander. Gibson also commanded
Columbia on a January 1986 flight that was the last mission before
the Challenger explosion and was a pilot aboard Challenger on his
first flight in February 1984.
   Gibson, 42, was born in Cooperstown, N.Y., but considers
Lakewood, Calif., his hometown. He graduated from California
Polytechnic State University with a degree in aeronautical
engineering.
   In 1969, Gibson entered active duty with the Navy and later flew
combat missions in Southeast Asia. He was selected as an astronaut
in January 1978.
   Gibson is married to Dr. Rhea Seddon, who also is an astronaut
and has flown on one previous shuttle flight. He has two children,
Julie 12, and Paul, 6.
   He is a member of an all-astronaut rock 'n' roll band called
MAX-Q, the abbreviation for the point in the shuttle's ascent when
aerodynamic stress is at its maximum. The band does informal gigs in
the Clear Lake area south of Houston.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   AIR FORCE LT. COL. GUY S. GARDNER: Pilot. Gardner, an astronaut
since May 1980, is making his first shuttle flight.
   Gardner, 40, was born in Alta Vista, Va., but considers
Alexandria, Va., his hometown. He received a bachelor's degree in
engineering sciences, astronautics and mathematics from the U.S. Air
Force Academy, and a master's degree in astronautics from Purdue
University.
   He flew 177 combat missions in Southeast Asia in 1972 while
stationed in Thailand and later was an Air Force test pilot and an
instructor test pilot.
   Gardner and his wife, Linda, have three children, Jennifer, 15,
Sarah, 11, and Jason, 10.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   AIR FORCE COL. RICHARD M. MULLANE: Mission specialist. Mullane
first flew on Discovery's maiden voyage in August 1984. The
seven-day mission featured the deployment of three satellites.
   Mullane, 43, was born in Wichita Falls, Texas, but he grew up in
Albuquerque, N.M., where he also attended high school. He is a
graduate of West Point and earned his master's degree in
aeronautical engineering from the Air Force Institute of Technology.
   He completed 150 combat missions in Vietnam as a weapon system
operator. In July 1976, he was assigned as a flight test weapon
system operator at Eglin Air Force Base, Fla.
   Mullane was selected as an astronaut in January 1978. He and his
wife, Donna, have three children, twins Patrick and Michele, 20, and
Laura, 17.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   AIR FORCE LT. COL. JERRY L. ROSS: Mission specialist. During his
first flight aboard Atlantis in November 1985, Ross twice walked in
space while demonstrating construction techniques for a space
station.
   Ross, 40, born in Crown Point, Ind., received a bachelor's and a
master's degree in mechanical engineering from Purdue University.
While with the Air Force, he worked extensively in testing the B-1
bomber.
   In February 1979, Ross was assigned to the Payload Operations
Division at NASA's Johnson Space Center as a payload officer-flight
controller and was responsible for integrating payloads into the
space shuttle.
   Ross was selected as an astronaut in May 1980. He and his wife,
Karen, have two children, Amy, 17, and Scott, 16.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   NAVY CMDR. WILLIAM M. SHEPHERD. Mission specialist. Shepherd, who
was selected as an astronaut in May 1984, is making his first
shuttle flight.
   Shepherd, 39, was born in Oak Ridge, Tenn., but he grew up in the
Washington D.C. area. He received a bachelor's degree in aerospace
engineering from the U.S. Naval Academy in 1971, and the degree of
ocean engineer and a master's in mechanical engineering from the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology. He is single.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
