<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EmbarcaderoBlaze     12-01 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Embarcadero Blaze,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Man Dead in Pier Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRO BAY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire burned an oil-soaked pier today,
killing one man and destroying at least 11 boats and two cars,
authorities said. A tower of black smoke hung over the area, and
some people were evacuated.
   The dead man was asleep in his boat when the fire broke out and
spread to his vessel, said Morro Bay Fire Department spokesman Fred
Harpster. At least two other people were injured in the early
morning blaze.
   Authorities ordered the evacuation of an area downwind from the
fire for about a quarter-mile after hearing reports that the pier
was treated with creosote, a carcinogenic substance.
   The waterfront of this town 175 miles northwest of Los Angeles is
lined with restaurants and souvenir shops along a strip known as the
embarcadero. The pier that burned was known as the T Pier because of
its shape.
   Bill Morgan and his wife, Mary Ann, said they saw the fire break
out and after Morgan called the Fire Department they returned to the
pier to knock on boats and awaken the live-aboard occupants.
   Shortly afterward, Morgan said, ``The fire just went whoosh'' and
engulfed the pier off the city's waterfront.
   ``There's a huge cloud of dark, oily smoke,'' said Fred Peterson
of radio station KSLY. ``The pier is an old pier and soaked with oil
from over the years. It's a stubborn fire.''
   The crew of the Coast Guard cutter Point Winslow towed the
burning boats away from the pier. The boats, both fishing and
pleasure craft, were left burning as firefighters turned their
attention to controlling the pier blaze.
   Coast Guard spokesman Fred Smith said the Point Winslow also was
putting water on the fire, and another cutter, the Point Judith, was
en route to the scene.
   Shortly before 8 a.m., the fire appeared to be under control,
witnesses said, with Harbor Patrol and Coast Guard craft maneuvering
to douse hot spots.
   Smith said a Coast Guard Marine Safety crew was en route from San
Francisco to check for pollution in the coastal area of the town.
</TEXT>
