<HEAD>With PM-Pakistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Hopes for Democracy in Pakistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan sent a letter of
congratulation to Paskistan's new prime minister, Benazir Bhutto,
and it was delivered today in Islamabad, the White House announced.
   ``In his letter, the president expressed his hope that the
recently conducted elections will usher in an era of democratic rule
in Pakistan,''presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said.
   ``On this historic occasion, we also wish to congratulate
President (Ghulam Ishaq) Khan and the people of Pakistan for the
successful conclusion of their elections,'' he said.
   ``We are encouraged by this renewed commitment in Pakistan to
constitutional procedures and look forward to continuing our close
relations with Pakistan's new government.''
   In Islamabad, Khan announced that he was appointing Mrs. Bhutto
as prime minister on the basis of her showing in the recent
elections.
   At the State Department, spokeswoman Phylis Oakley said, ``We
welcome the continued unfolding of the constitutional process in an
orderly way in Pakistan.''
   The nomination of Ms. Bhutto as prime minister is ``an historic
event of which the people of Pakistan can be truly proud,'' she said.
</TEXT>
