<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Dissident     12-01 0734</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Dissident,0754</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissident Speaks Out 10 Years After Quashed Democracy Movement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An accountant who was jailed four years for
criticizing the ruling Communist Party has appealed to the U.N.
Human Rights Commission to intercede on behalf of fellow dissidents
still in prison.
   Ren Wanding also renewed his call first made a decade ago that
the party allow the Chinese people to decide in free elections who
should rule them.
   ``I say what everything thinks,'' Ren said in an interview
Thursday marked by a frankness rarely seen in China's tightly
controlled political atmosphere.
   ``The people are not satisfied. When the time is ready they will
stand up,'' he said. ``I have no plans to organize an uprising. It's
a historical necessity.''
   Ren, 44, helped lead the 1978-79 Democracy Wall Movement, a brief
thaw during which authorities tolerated unprecedented calls for
multiparty democracy. He and dozens of other dissidents were
imprisoned in 1979 as counterrevolutionaries.
   Ren, who said he was never given a trial, was released in 1983
after four years of ``education by labor,'' including two years in
solitary confinement.
   He said he was speaking out after nearly a decade of silence in
order to mark the movement's anniversary and draw attention to
colleagues still in jail.
   ``If the U.N. Human Rights Commission and international society
do not expose the human rights violations of their members ... this
will promote evil and do damage to justice and the lofty purpose of
the United Nations,'' Ren wrote to the United Nations.
   He urged the world community to investigate the conditions of
China's jailed dissidents. Human rights groups, he wrote, should
ask, ``Are they dressed warmly in prison, and are they bothered by
flies in summer?
   ``What is their nutrition and medical treatment like? Are these
people still beaten in prison? Are they required to donate blood
even though they suffer from poor nutrition? Are they still given
meat and canned food that has gone bad? ... Are they still allowed
out just once every month or two months, and given only a minute or
two for a trip to the toilet?''
   ``Having been in prison, I am familiar with the suffering,'' Ren
said in the interview. He said he was held in solitary confinement
for two years, and was allowed books only after the first year.
   Ren also issued a statement this week to the foreign media urging
foreign businesses to demand China improve its human rights policy
before investing.
   The Democracy Wall Movement began with a few pro-democracy
posters plastered on a brick wall in Beijing. Encouraged by
reformist statements by top leader Deng Xiaoping, students and
workers put hundreds more posters on the wall and similar walls in
other cities. Home-printed magazines circulated openly demanding
rule by law, multi-party elections and an end to party privileges.
   Ren, along with more than a dozen friends, edited a journal
called Chinese Human Rights, mimeographing hundreds of copies in
their homes.
   By 1979, however, Deng had consolidated his hold over leftists in
the party and cracked down on the democracy movement.
   More than a dozen of its leaders remain jailed, Ren said. The
best known is Wei Jingsheng, who wrote an impassioned plea for
democracy as a ``fifth modernization'' to go along with the official
program of modernizing agriculture, industry, science and the
military.
   Last year, Amnesty International said it had unconfirmed reports
Wei had died in prison, but China denied it. Ren said he had no
direct information on Wei but believed him to be at a labor camp in
western China's Qinghai province.
   Other activists in the Democracy Wall Movement have remained
silent since. Thousands of students in Beijing and other cities
joined in pro-democracy marches in the winter of 1986-87, but no
nationally renowned leaders emerged and the demonstrations subsided
under a government crackdown.
   Since then, the only dissident who has openly criticized Marxism
and one-party rule is Fang Lizhi, an astrophysicist who says his
fame gives him some protection from government retribution. He was
expelled from the Communist Party in 1987 for allegedly having
helped incite the student protests.
   Ren said he also has no plans to form an opposition, but will
continue to speak out.
   ``How can I not speak?'' Ren said. ``I can't be afraid of arrest,
if I am I can't do anything. If they arrest me, they arrest me.''
</TEXT>
