<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Marcos'Defense     12-01 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marcos' Defense,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marcos: Nobody's Proved Anything Against Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippines President Ferdinand
Marcos, charged with conspiring to steal more than $100 million from
his homeland, writes in a journal to be published this month that he
is being unfairly judged.
   Marcos, whose lawyers claim he's too ill to stand trial or even
to travel from his exile home in Hawaii, writes his defense in the
winter issue of Orbis, to be distributed Dec. 28 by the Foreign
Policy Research Institute, a Philadelphia think tank.
   An advance copy of the article was made available to The
Associated Press.
   Marcos insists in the six-page, 2,500-word essay that he didn't
raid the treasury of more than $5 billion during the 21 years he led
the Philippines until his ouster in 1986, and he didn't allow
friends to siphon off huge sums.
   ``The fact is that none of these charges, which are criminal in
character, has been made subject to judicial scrutiny,'' Marcos
wrote.
   ``Many of the so-called Marcos cronies are in the Philippines
today. They are within the reach of the present administration in
Manila. Although presumably possessed of all the evidence necessary
to establish their guilt, the Aquino administration has not
prosecuted any of these putative malefactors.
   ``Private property has been seized; moral declamations have been
broadcast; but not one single case has been brought before a court
of law. With criminals in such abundance, whose guilt is so evident,
one might have expected that at least one of them would have had to
face prosecution by this time.''
   Marcos wrote that he has asked the government in Manila to allow
him to return and ``afford me the opportunity to face my accusers
(but) it has steadfastly refused my demand for a day in court.''
   Marcos' article was in response to one written in the last issue
of Orbis, distributed in September, by Theodore Friend, former
president of Swarthmore College and currently head of Eisenhower
Exchange Fellowships.
   Friend accused Marcos of wrecking the Philippines politically and
economically through corruption and murder..
   Marcos said the ``omnibus charges repeated by Friend (that) I am
personally responsible for the murder of political opponents, and
the massive derogation of human rights in the Philippines merit
little further comment'' because his request to return and be
subject to his country's courts had been rejected.
   ``To date, the authorities in Manila have refused my request,
have failed to indict, and display a singular unwillingness to
prosecute,'' Marcos wrote.
   Friend, in an answer to Marcos in the same Orbis, called him an
astute lawyer ``who shielded himself with legalisms, many of them
contrived.'' He also said 39 civil suits against him in the
Philippines seek a total of $96.17 billion, and that criminal suits
also are pending there.
   ``Marcos used his regime as a means to preserve and enhance his
own political power; as a means to engorge his friends; and as a
means to enrich his family and himself _ not by `peculations' but by
systematic parasitic robbery,'' Friend wrote.
   Marcos, who rejected every suggestion he was guilty of anything,
said U.S. intervention into Philippine affairs that led to his
ouster and the election of Corazon Aquino as president backfired.
   ``The strangest feature of all this is that not only have U.S.
interests now been placed in serious jeopardy, but all the charges
that made my administration a pariah among policy makers in
Washington have recently resurfaced as charges against the present
regime,'' Marcos wrote.
   Marcos and his wife, Imelda, were indicted Oct. 21 in New York on
federal criminal racketeering charges accusing them of plundering
the Philippines' treasury and stashing much of the money in the
United States.
   Mrs. Marcos pleaded innocent to the charges Oct. 31 in New York
and was released on $5 million bail.
   Defense lawyers contend Marcos is too frail to make the 10-hour
flight to New York for arraignment or trial. A court-appointed
physician decided in late November that Marcos is healthy enough to
face charges in New York.
</TEXT>
