<DOCNO> AP881201-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1427EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Nuclear     12-01 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Nuclear,0791</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Berlin Marks 50 Years of Nuclear Fission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty years ago, German scientists Otto Hahn and
Fritz Strassmann discovered nuclear fission, a breakthrough that led
to the atom bomb and nuclear energy.
   On Thursday, Berlin held the first of several events marking the
fateful work.
   The discovery by Hahn and Strassmann also was intertwined with
the Nazi era. Albert Speer, a former top aide to Adolf Hitler,
strongly implied that Hahn was one of a group of German scientists
seeking ways to build an atomic bomb before the Americans beat them
to it.
   Hahn, a physicist and chemist who won the 1944 Nobel Prize in
chemistry for his discovery, worked closely with a Jewish colleague
forced into exile by the Nazis.
   The December 1938 work at the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute for
Chemistry in Berlin also represented one of the many feats of the
proud German scientific tradition.
   On Thursday, scientists and officials of the Technical University
of West Berlin outlined the impact of Strassmann's and Hahn's
discovery at an exhibition of models, photographs and scientific
equipment documenting the work.
   ``The development of nuclear physics and its technology has found
interest among the public like no other discovery,'' said Ulrich
Steinmueller, vice president of the Technical University.
   ``The technology carries implicitly in its use _ both in war and
peace _ a threat for mankind,'' Steinmueller said. ``The
well-founded worries and fears of people give scientists a challenge
to be aware of their responsibilities to society.''
   West Germans have been sensitive to some of the end results of
Hahn and Strassmann's discovery: the stationing of nuclear rockets
on their soil and the fallout from the Chernobyl nuclear accident in
1986 in the Soviet Union.
   ``That day 50 years ago in Dahlem (the Berlin district where the
discovery took place) must also be remembered along with the day of
Hiroshima and Nagasaki and the day of Chernobyl,'' Steinmueller told
the news conference at the Technical University.
   Steinmueller added that the peaceful use of nuclear energy
``leaves open more problems than it solves.''
   Hahn and Strassmann found that bombarding the uranium atom with
neutrons leads to its splitting. At first, they were unsure of what
they had discovered.
   From her exile in Sweden, Jewish colleague Lise Meitner and her
partner, Otto Robert Frisch, furnished the theoretical basis showing
such a splitting could release huge amounts of energy through chain
reactions.
   The experiments took place in the middle of December, with the
key test starting Dec. 16, 1938.
   In the years before his discovery, Hahn had worked closely with
Meitner, who had been forced to emigrate in 1938 as the Nazis
stepped up their attacks on the Jews.
   ``It was unusual at that time to have a man and woman working
together when they weren't married,'' said Jost Lemmerich, chief
organizer of the exhibition.
   When Hahn won the prize, no mention was made of the work by
Meitner or Strassmann. Hahn died in 1968 in West Germany.
   During Thursday's news conference, Lemmerich was asked why the
exhibition stops in 1939, without covering the Nazis' scientific
research in World War II.
   ``We stopped there because the history is incomplete,'' he
responded. ``We didn't have access to the documents.''
   But he hinted another exhibition is possible to show the darker
sides of Hahn's discovery.
   ``Couldn't we, say in five years, have another exhibition about
Hiroshima?'' he asked rhetorically.
   West Berlin's Tagespiegel newspaper on Nov. 27 said Hahn wrote in
his diary of the Hiroshima attack that he had a clear conscience
``that neither during the discovery nor later did I want to work for
the use of uranium fission as a war weapon.''
   At the time, Hahn and other top German atomic scientists were
being detained in a British camp, according to the newspaper.
   Speer, Hitler's armaments minister and the Third Reich's top
architect, said that in 1942 he had heard of ``a group of scientists
who were on the track of a weapon which could annihilate whole
cities, perhaps throw the island of England out of the fight.''
   He continued that two months later he visited with scientists in
Berlin to be briefed on ``atomic research,'' as the Nazi Reich
struggled to find a way to win World War II.
   ``Along with scientists whose names I no longer recall, the
subsequent Nobel Prize winners Otto Hahn and Werner Heisenberg were
present,'' Speer wrote in his memoirs, ``Inside the Third Reich.''
   Heisenberg told Speer that building such a bomb was possible but
it would take at least two years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
