<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1648EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TV-Sweeps     12-01 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TV-Sweeps,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Looks to Next Year; `War and Remembrance' Helps ABC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The results of the November television rating
sweeps period indicates that, among the three networks, CBS took the
worst hit from the summer writers' strike.
   ``The strike really hurt CBS,'' said David Poltrack, CBS vice
president for marketing. ``We didn't have any big events to fill
in'' such as ABC's 18-hour miniseries ``War and Remembrance.''
   He said CBS also had fewer established half-hour sitcoms than the
competition. Those shows got back into production quicker than hour
dramas.
   ABC was the only one of the three networks to show a rise in
ratings this November compared to last November, when it came in
third in the sweeps. Its ``Roseanne'' was the highest-rated new
series in November.
   CBS and ABC tied for second in terms of regular series
programming, according to CBS' analysis of the A.C. Nielsen Co.
numbers. But ABC had a three-point lead on CBS when it came to
miniseries and movies.
   NBC, with five of the top 10 series and the five top-rated
movies, handily won the sweeps, one of four months a year when
network affiliates' ratings are measured for purposes of negotiating
local advertising rates.
   NBC had an average, prime-time rating of 15.4. ABC had an average
rating of 14.0 and CBS 12.0. Each rating point represents 904,000
households with televisions.
   ``The Cosby Show'' was the highest-rated network show with a
rating of 26.3, down from the 32.3 the show got in November 1987. In
fact, all the top-rated series suffered ratings declines.
   Because of strike-caused production delays on its regular series,
ABC rushed to the air with the first part of its more than 30-hour
``War and Remembrance,'' a sequel to ``The Winds of War.'' Except
for two two-part movies, ``War and Remembrance'' was the only
miniseries of the November sweeps. It ended with a disappointing
18.6 rating and 29 share, but was good enough to save ABC from third
place in the sweeps. ABC will run the remainder of the miniseries
next May, said spokeswoman Janice Gretemeyer.
   Sweeps programming brought more viewers to their sets. More
households used television, but 3 percent fewer sets were tuned to
networks. That was an improvement, though, on the season-to-date 6
percent decline in network viewing. And some of the November decline
was attributable to low network viewing on election night.
   One of the most significant numbers was the increase in viewing
of independent stations, which have become more aggressive during
sweeps periods.
   Fox Broadcasting Co., whose affiliates are counted as independent
stations, experienced a dramatic rise in ratings, an average 5.5
compared to 3.7 a year ago. Part of that increase was because Fox
was running new episodes of its most popular programs, ``America's
Most Wanted'' and ``Married ... With Children'' during the summer
when the networks were in repeats. Those shows apparently developed
a following that stuck with them in the fall when the networks were
struggling to get delayed shows on the air.
   But independent stations also did well by taking over what was
previously a network source of programming _ theatrical release
movies. The networks have all but abandoned theatrical movies as a
source of ratings, Poltrack said. Meanwhile, independent stations
are able to garner competitive ratings by running such films as ``48
Hours'' and ``The Godfather.''
   Pay cable also experienced an increase in viewership during the
sweeps. HBO was up to an average rating of 8.3, compared to 6.9 a
year ago. That was the first increase for HBO in the five years
since the networks began analyzing pay cable performance during
sweeps.
   Poltrack predicted that January will be ``critical'' for the
networks, because it will be their first chance in the
strike-delayed season to recoup regular series viewers.
   ``We look to the future, not to the past,'' he said.
</TEXT>
