<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BlackBook     12-01 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Black Book,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Casino Executive Barred From Casinos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nevada officials have listed former Las
Vegas casino executive Frank ``Lefty'' Rosenthal in the state's
``black book'' of people barred from casinos.
   Rosenthal said he wasn't surprised by the unanimous Nevada Gaming
Commission decision, but said he will fight it.
   Commission Chairman John O'Reilly ended an eight-hour hearing
Wednesday by saying his main concern was Rosenthal's ``notorious and
unsavory'' reputation over the years.
   During the hearing, Rosenthal, 59, said politics rather than his
reputation created problems for him in Nevada during the 1970s. ``I
know people in the gaming industry today who make me look like a
choir boy, frankly,'' he said.
   Rosenthal said another reason for his trouble with authorities
over the years was his reputation as an expert bookmaker _ something
that was viewed as ``less than desirable.''
   Rosenthal was an executive for Argent Corp., which ran four Las
Vegas casinos in the 1970s, before he left Las Vegas after an
attempt on his life in October 1982. He since has lived in
California and Florida.
   The state Gaming Commission ruled in 1976 that he was unsuitable
to work as a key employee with Argent because of alleged organized
crime ties. Rosenthal challenged the ruling all the way to the U.S.
Supreme Court, but the high court let the Nevada decision stand.
   The FBI has linked Rosenthal to organized crime figures but he
never was charged with any crime.
   Rosenthal, a one-time Chicago hot dog stand owner, has denied
having ties to organized crime.
</TEXT>
