<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1655EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Soviets     12-01 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviets,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Says Moscow Not Qualified for Human Rights Conference Yet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite an apparent end to the jamming of most
Western radio broadcasts, the Soviet Union still is not entitled to
have a human rights conference in Moscow, the State Department said
Thursday.
   ``We will be looking for further Soviet movement on other
issues,'' department spokesowman Phyllis Oakley said.
   The jamming of American-financed Radio Liberty and two other
foreign radio stations ceased Wednesday. ``This is a positive
development which, if it becomes permament, will further contribute
to the improvement in East-West relations,'' the State Department
official said.
   But, she said, Czechoslovakia and Bulgaria were continuing to jam
Radio Free Europe, which broadcasts to Eastern Europe. ``We urge
those two nations to end this practice, which conflicts with their
international obligations,'' Mrs. Oakley said.
   The Soviets long have been eager to hold an international human
rights conference in Moscow. One of the U.S. conditions was an end
to jamming Russian-language broadcasts.
   Mrs. Oakley said ``the end to jamming enhances the prospects for
a Moscow meeting.'' But the Soviets must make other improvements in
human rights and also provide ``credible guarantees'' that the
meeting would be open to all Soviet citizens, the U.S. official said.
   The Reagan administration also is demanding that curbs on
emigration be eased further.
   On a related subject, Mrs. Oakley said the State Department was
concerned with developments in the troubled Caucasus region where
the Soviets on Wednesday reported 11 new deaths and there was a
rising flood of refugees from ethnic violence.
   ``We deeply regret the loss of life there,'' she said. ``We hope
and expect that Soviet authorities will continue making every effort
to protect the lives and welfare of people in the region while
seeking a just and peaceful resolution.''
</TEXT>
