<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NotDead     12-01 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Not Dead,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Dead' Man Not Dead, And His Drug And Weapons Charges Reinstated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 32-year-old man who had drug and
weapons charges against him dropped when a prosecutor heard he had
drowned is not dead, and charges against him will be reinstated,
officials said.
   The 9th Circuit Solicitor's office had received word that William
Wilson III drowned in September in a James Island creek.
   Assistant Solicitor Mark C. Moore said charges of possession of
marijuana for distribution and possession of a firearm by a
convicted felon were dismissed Nov. 3 because of the belief that
Wilson had died.
   The confusion arose when a 31-year-old William Wilson of James
Island drowned while shrimping in September.
   Solicitor Charles Condon said the mistake occurred because an
employee in his office said she knew the man and that his name was
listed on court dockets.
   Moore said he asked the employee to confirm that by checking
court files. But the description of both Wilsons was similar in year
of birth, race and size, and both men had been charged with weapons
offenses.
   Moore said the staff believed that William Wilson III was the man
who drowned and the charges were dismissed.
   They learned their mistake when Wilson was stopped by police Nov.
25 and they found three bags of marijuana in his car.
   ``I never had anything like this happen,'' Condon said. ``I'm
grateful it was caught.''
   Condon said he will begin asking defense lawyers to supply death
certificates when their clients die before coming to trial. Moore
said he will attempt to indict Wilson on the April charges.
</TEXT>
