<HEAD>Dukakis to Meet With Democratic Leaders, Bentsen Before Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, the defeated Democratic
presidential nominee, will meet with his party's congressional
leaders and running mate Lloyd Bentsen before sitting down Friday
with President-elect George Bush, spokesmen for the Massachusetts
governor said Thursday.
   He also will hold a private meeting with Washington-based
campaign aides to thank them for their work in his unsuccessful
White House bid, Dukakis spokesman James Dorsey said.
   Dukakis was to arrive in Washington Friday morning and meet on
Capitol Hill with House Speaker Jim Wright of Texas and new Senate
Majority Leader George Mitchell of Maine, Dorsey said.
   Also on the governor's agenda was a luncheon with Bentsen, the
Texas senator who Dukakis selected as his vice presidential nominee.
   Dukakis likely would ask the Democratic leaders if they had any
concerns they wanted relayed to Bush, Dorsey said.
   The afternoon meeting of the former presidential rivals, which
was requested by Bush, was to be held at the vice president's
residence. It comes a day after the president-elect met with
Mitchell and two days after he had lunch with Jesse Jackson, one of
the men Dukakis bested to win the Democratic nomination.
   Spokesman Steve Crawford said Dukakis planned to talk to Bush
about a number of issues he raised during the campaign.
   ``Education, health care, day care, drugs, housing and other
issues that he felt were important during the campaign and still
feels are important,'' Crawford said when asked to outline Dukakis'
agenda for the Bush meeting.
   Since the election Dukakis also has expressed concern over
reports quoting Bush transition aides as saying Medicare and other
entitlement programs could face spending cuts as part of a
deficit-reduction plan.
