<1ST_LINE>r i AM-RadioLiberty-Glance     12-01 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Radio Liberty-Glance,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radio Liberty, Radio Free Europe At-A-Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Radio Liberty, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Facts about the Radio Liberty and Radio
Free Europe broadcasting networks:
   _ The Munich-based Radio Free Europe network was founded in 1949.
Radio Liberty, an associated service for listeners in the Soviet
Union, was founded in 1951 and was once operated under the U.S.
Central Intelligence Agency. It went on the air in 1953. The two
services were merged in 1976 and are now controlled by the
Washington-based Board for International Broadcasting and funded by
the U.S. government.
   _ Radio Liberty broadcasts news and commentary in Russian,
Byelorussian, Ukrainian, Georgian, Armenian, Azerbaijani, Kazak,
Uzbek, Kirghiz, Turkmenian, Tadzhik, Tatar-Bashkiri, Pashtu and Dari.
   _ Radio Free Europe broadcasts in Estonian, Latvian, Lithuanian,
Bulgarian, Czechoslovakia, Polish, Hungarian and Romanian.
   _ The sprawling, high-security compound encloses separate
newsrooms for each language service, as well as the networks'
reference library on Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union used
frequently by American and Western scholars.
   _ The two radio networks employ about 1,700 worldwide.
</TEXT>
