<DOCNO> AP881201-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1935EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AllegedNazi     12-01 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alleged Nazi,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department Reaches Agreement With Alleged Nazi War Criminal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA PARZIALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Lithuanian immigrant who the Justice
Department claims helped murder Jews during World War II has agreed
to surrender his U.S. citizenship, but he will not be deported, an
official said.
   Under an agreement signed this week, Jonas Klimavicius, 81, will
provide evidence on other members of the Nazi paramilitary outfit
known as the Lithuanian Shutzmannschaft, Eli Rosenbaum, deputy
director of the Justice Department's Office of Special
Investigations, said Wednesday.
   That information is being used in two cases in Boston and in the
investigations of dozens of other members of Klimavicius' battalion,
he said.
   In the court agreement, Klimavicius admitted serving in the fall
of 1941 in the battalion, but did not admit taking part in what
Rosenbaum said were the persecutions of thousands of Jews and other
unarmed civilians. He also did not admit misrepresenting or
concealing facts about his past on his citizenship application.
   The Justice Department decided to drop its case because of
Klimavicius' age and the length of time it might take for hearings
and appeals to be conducted, Rosenbaum said.
   The agreement does not preclude Klimavicius' extradition to
another country to stand trial for alleged war crimes.
   U.S. District Judge Gene Carter signed the agreement Monday.
   Carter had earlier stripped Klimavicius of his citizenship
because he refused to testify about his past, but he was overturned
by the U.S. Circuit Court in Boston last July and a second
deportation hearing was ordered. That hearing was scheduled to begin
Dec. 12.
   Klimavicius came to the United States in 1949 via New York City
and became a U.S. citizen five years later. He lived on Long Island,
retiring from his job as a machinist in the early 1970s, and moved
to Maine in 1983.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
