<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LaRouche 1stLd-Writethru a0705 12-01 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LaRouche, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0705,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LaRouche Aide Sang For Boss, Cooked For Dogs</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 6 grafs after 12th graf pvs, bgng: `Asked how,' to
UPDATE with further testimony from Magraw. Picks up 13th graf pvs,
`LaRouche was'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political extremist Lyndon H. LaRouche was
waited upon hand-and-foot by employees who cooked for him, his wife
and his dogs, bought his clothes, cleaned his house and performed
concerts for him, a federal jury heard Thursday.
   Pam Cowdery, a former employee of a LaRouche graphics company,
testified at LaRouche's conspiracy trial that she played the violin
and sang at his Leesburg, Va., estate when he and his wife ``just
wanted to hear some music.''
   She also said she cooked for the LaRouches, helped clean the
house and even prepared ``very special meals'' featuring boned
chicken breasts for the couple's dogs.
   LaRouche's security chief, Richard Magraw, testified that
LaRouche carried no money, and that he would buy suits, underwear,
tobacco and even haircuts for his balding boss.
   Prosecutors contend LaRouche was living this upscale life in
Virginia's horse country while LaRouche-controlled organizations
were failing to repay more than $30 million in loans from
individuals. A federal grand jury has charged LaRouche and six
associates on trial with him in U.S. District Court with conspiring
to defraud the lenders.
   LaRouche alone is charged with conspiring to defraud the Internal
Revenue Service by failing to declare as income the household and
personal services he received from his organizations.
   Ms. Cowdery, who stopped working for LaRouche in 1986 but still
supports him politically, said that before 1984 LaRouche staffers
were encouraged to attend and perform in cultural events. But she
said the program suffered during LaRouche's 1984 presidential
campaign when a defendant in the case, William Wertz, took over
fund-raising operations and made staffers work longer hours.
   Ms. Cowdery said that when performers complained, LaRouche
replied, ``You have to understand that everything that Will does is
under my directions. I make the policy and Will just carries it
out.''
   She said LaRouche also commented that people in his organization
``had become more stupid.''
   Magraw, who is responsible for safety at LaRouche's house and for
his personal security, said he usually acted on his own to make
purchases for LaRouche and did not discuss them beforehand with his
boss.
   Asked how he would know the size of items such as trousers,
Magraw said, ``I took an old pair of trousers hanging in the closet
to the tailor and told him to make it the same length.''
   Under cross-examination from defense lawyers Magraw _ testifying
under a grant of limited immunity from prosecution _ described
LaRouche as a workaholic who never told his security detail to buy
any personal items.
   Magraw, referring to his purchase of suits for LaRouche, said,
``I bought them at odd times when they were on sale.''
   ``You were more concerned with his appearance than he was?''
asked LaRouche attorney Odin Anderson.
   ``Certainly more than he was,'' Magraw said.
   Magraw added that LaRouche spent 80 percent of his time at a
typewriter or computer keyboard and ``when he got working on a
political project he would work for 24 hours straight.''
   Magraw said, ``I don't believe Mr. LaRouche has ever gone on a
vacation'' and never takes days off.
   LaRouche was indicted in October on 13 counts of mail fraud,
conspiracy to commit mail fraud and conspiracy to defraud the IRS.
The mail fraud counts stem from promissory notes and letters of
credit sent through the mails by the LaRouche organization.
Conviction on all counts could carry a maximum penalty of 65 years
in prison and fines of $3.25 million for LaRouche.
   The six associates face lesser sentences if convicted of the mail
fraud and conspiracy charges, which cover the years 1983 to 1987.
   On trial with LaRouche are his chief fund-raiser Wertz; his legal
adviser, Edward Spannaus; and four fund-raisers: Michael Billington,
Dennis Small, Paul Greenberg and Joyce Rubinstein.
</TEXT>
