<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 2007EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-RiceProgram     12-01 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rice Program,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ag Secretary Unveils 1989 Rice Program With $6.50 Support Level</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng on
Thursday unveiled the government's 1989 program for rice farmers
with a national average price-support level of $6.50 for each 100
pounds.
   That is down from a national average of $6.63 in 1988.
   Price support loans are paid by the government's Commodity Credit
Corp. to farmers who post their crops as collateral. Because
producers are free to forfeit the crops and keep the cash, the
system puts a floor under prices.
   Farmers must meet program requirements to qualify for federal
subsidies.
   Lyng announced a required acreage reduction of 25 percent. This
represents land that farmers cannot plant and is designed to prevent
surpluses.
   He set the established target price at $10.80 for each 100
pounds, down from $11.15 this year.
   Target prices are used in calculating so-called deficiency
payments that the government provides as income supports to
participants in some programs.
   Other provisions of the rice program:
   _Whole kernel milled rice price support rates were set at $10.81
per hundredweight for long grain and $9.81 for medium and short
grain rice. The broken kernel rate for all rice classes is $5.41.
   _Producers who pledged 1989 crop rice as collateral for price
support loans will not be permitted to purchase marketing
certificates when repaying loans at the marketing loan repayment
rate.
   _The discretionary inventory reduction program will not be
implemented.
   _Farmers may sign up for the program between Dec. 19 and April 14.
</TEXT>
