<DOCNO> AP881201-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1653EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SovietRefuseniks 1stLd-Writethru a0737 12-01 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Refuseniks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0737,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More than 40 Jewish Dissidents Notified Barrier To Emigration Being
Removed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 4 grafs NEW to give emigration totals, relate it to
Gorbachev-Reagan meeting; Picks up 3rd graf pvs, bgng: ``Among the
...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet authorities have notified at least 42
Jews who had been denied exit permits on grounds of state secrecy
that the barrier to emigration is being removed, the National
Conference on Soviet Jewry said Thursday.
   Assistant Secretary of State Richard Shifter said he heard of the
barrier being lifted from Jewish sources after several conversations
with Soviet officials. He said he had no official confirmation from
Moscow.
   The move followed the apparent ending of Soviet jamming of
American-financed Russian language broadcasts. Together, the two
steps represent a major improvement in human rights by Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev before his meeting next week with
President Reagan and President-elect George Bush.
   The Jewish group announced, meanwhile, that 2,334 Soviet Jews had
been granted exit permits in November _ the largest monthly total
this year. Permits this year total 15,640, making the exodus the
biggest since 1980.
   Among the ``refuseniks'' informed of the change was Yuli
Kosharovsky, who has been waiting for more than 17 years for
permission to go to Israel. He had been denied a visa for classified
work he performed as an electronics engineer until 1968.
   Kosharovsky, who lives in Moscow and first applied for a permit
in 1971, was also a strong human rights activist, said Jerry
Strober, public information officer of the National Conference on
Soviet Jewry.
   ``He was told his secrecy ban had been lifted and to submit
papers to leave the country,'' Strober said. ``He expects to hear in
a month.''
   The official of the private group, which has lobbied in behalf of
Soviet Jews since 1971, said OVIR, the Soviet emigration office, had
told ``refusenik circles'' in Moscow that a total of 120 people
would have their secrecy restrictions lifted.
   Shoshana Cardin, chairman of the conference, welcomed ``the
lifting of secrecy imposed for many years on former prisoners of
conscience and long-term refuseniks. We look forward to the speedy
drafting of permission to emigrate to all those whose secrecy has
been lifted.''
   Also among those notified were Vladimir Kislik, a Moscow
physicist who first applied for an exit permit in 1973, and Roald
Zelichonok, a Leningrad electrical engineer who has been trying to
leave the Soviet Union since 1978.
   Kislik was arrested in 1981 on charges of malicious hooliganism
and served a three-year labor sentence. Zelichonok was arrested in
1985 on charges of defaming the state and served eight months.
   Strober said he knew of 42 Soviet Jews who had been notified the
restriction was being lifted.
</TEXT>
