<HEAD>Suspect Found In Break-In At Governor's Mansion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID Bday who are</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   willing to die to protect him,'' State Police Superintendent Thomas
Constantine said of the governor Wednesday. ``When something like
this happens, it hurts.''
   Two men arrested on burglary charges in Oneida County were found
with stolen goods that included jewelry and other items from the
mansion.
   State Police are responsible for guarding the mansion, a mission
that for a time on Monday ``was not performed,'' Constantine said.
   Mrs. Cuomo didn't see the intruder, but two or three mansion
employees did before he slipped away, Constantine said.
   ``It would be an understatement to say that I'm extremely upset
about it,'' Constantine said. ``It's the type of thing that
shouldn't happen. It's not in keeping with the tradition of the
State Police being very professional.''
   The incident came a week after Cuomo revealed that he was on the
hit list of prominent people targeted by the Medellin drug cartel
for assassination. Constantine said there's no connection between
the intruder and the Colombian drug dealers.
   Security had been beefed up at the Executive Mansion after an
October 1984 break-in, when silverware, a video recorder and other
items were stolen while Cuomo and his wife slept upstairs.
   Cuomo press secretary Gary Fryer said it was his understanding
that one of the two men arrested this week had been able to get into
the mansion Monday and move about freely by identifying himself as a
repairman.
   Oneida County District Attorney Barry Donalty said he believed
the intruder didn't know he'd entered the governor's home at first.
   Cuomo called the security breach ``disconcerting,'' but said he
has his own personal security system.
   ``I have a 36-inch Louisville Slugger. No license, no nothing,''
Cuomo said, referring to a brand of baseball bat. The governor is a
former minor league baseball player.
