<1ST_LINE>r w AM-OilImports     12-01 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Imports,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commerce Reports to Reagan on Restricting Oil Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commerce Department on Thursday sent to
President Reagan a secret recommendation on whether oil imports
should be restricted.
   Some domestic energy producers organized as the National Energy
Security Committee filed a petition with the department a year ago
requesting an investigation of whether imported oil threatens
national security.
   The report to the president is the outcome of the investigation.
President Reagan has 90 days to decide what to do, which means he
could leave the whole question to President-elect George Bush.
   ``The report is secret until the president makes a decision,''
said department spokeswoman Desiree Tucker.
   Under provisions of a 1962 law, the president may limit imports
of items found to threaten national security.
   The crude oil price collapse of 1986 devastated U.S. producers,
who had gone all-out to find new oil following the price increases
of the 1970s.
   From 48 percent of U.S. consumption in 1977, imported crude and
refined products fell to 32 percent of consumption in 1985, but rose
to 40 percent for all of last year.
   For the first 10 months of 1988, imports were 41 percent of
consumption compared with 39 percent in the same 1987 period.
October's imports were 43 percent vs. 41 percent in October 1987.
   Several government reports have warned that imports could reach
50 percent in the 1990s. ``At this rate we could hit 50 percent by
1990,'' said William C. McCord, chairman of Enserch Corp. and
spokesman for the National Energy Security Committee.
</TEXT>
