<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MarineLesbian     12-01 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marine Lesbian,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marine General Grants Clemency to Female Corporal Jailed as Lesbian</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of the Marine Corps' Parris
Island, S.C., Recruit Depot, rejecting the advice of his legal
adviser, granted clemency to a female corporal convicted of
homosexual conduct, the corps said Thursday.
   Maj. Gen. Jarvis D. Lynch, in an order signed Wednesday but not
released until late Thursday, ordered the one-year prison term
handed Cpl. Barbara J. Baum reduced to 226 days, said Maj. Robert
McLean, a spokesman.
   He also ordered her dishonorable discharge upgraded to a bad
conduct discharge, the spokesman said, but left untouched the
portions of the sentence that reduced her in rank to private and
required forfeiture of all pay and allowances.
   ``Combined with routine credit for good behavior, this
effectively means she will be released from the brig on December
15,'' McLean added.
   ``I'm obviously extremely happy that Major General Lynch saw fit
to reduce her time so that she'll be out for Christmas,'' said L.
Barrett Boss, one of Baum's defense attorneys.
   ``But this does not change the fact that Barbara Baum has had to
spend more than five months in prison as punishment for her sexual
preferences,'' Boss added.
   Lynch had been urged by his staff judge advocate at Parris Island
to deny a defense bid for clemency, even though Baum claimed to have
been promised leniency by a prosecutor in exchange for her
cooperation with investigators.
   The Marine Corps denied the prosecuting attorney in the case had
ever made a binding promise to the enlisted woman in soliciting her
cooperation with investigators, but promised Lynch would review all
the arguments in the case.
   Baum, 24, of Mishawaka, Ind., was convicted at court martial last
June and sentenced to a year in prison as part of a wide-ranging
investigation of alleged lesbian conduct among Parris Island
instructors.
   She is serving her sentence in a brig at the Quantico, Va.,
Marine Base.
   Last month, in a memorandum dated Nov. 8, the top staff lawyer at
Parris Island recommended Lynch deny Baum any clemency.
   Col. Gerald W. Jones, the staff judge advocate, noted briefly in
his memo that the prosecutor in Baum's case _ Maj. David Beck _ had
recommended a reduction in sentence because of her ``post-trial
cooperation'' and because of ``corroboration'' of claims that she
had been sexually abused as a child.
   Nonetheless, Jones recommended the general ``approve the sentence
as adjudged.''
   The only explanation Jones offered was a single sentence stating:
``No corrective action based upon trial error or the review
procedure is appropriate.''
   McLean said Thursday he could not elaborate on Lynch's reasons
for granting clemency despite that recommendation.
   ``The general took this action after reviewing all the facts and
concluding that this sentence modification was in the best interest
of good order and discipline in the corps and of Corporal Baum,''
McLean said.
   According to Boss, Baum agreed to cooperate with investigators
after her conviction and spent 14 hours in interrogation. While no
written agreement was ever signed, ``she had a clear understanding
that in exchange for her cooperation, she would get clemency,'' Boss
said.
   Boss also argued that over and beyond Baum's decision to
cooperate with investigators, the Marine should be released early
from prison in order to seek psychological treatment.
   Baum has testified she was sexually abused by several men while a
child and now wants to obtain therapy, the defense attorney said.
   ``We do not intend to lay the matter to rest after she gets out
of prison,'' Boss said Thursday. ``We will continue to appeal the
conviction on a variety of grounds.''
</TEXT>
