<HEAD>Pier Fire Kills One Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRO BAY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A swift-moving fire destroyed an
oil-soaked pier early Thursday, killing one man and burning at least
11 boats and two cars, authorities said.
   Authorities ordered a brief evacuation of a nearby area after
hearing reports the pier was treated with creosote, a carcinogenic
substance.
   One man asleep in his boat when the fire broke out died when his
craft caught fire, said Morro Bay Fire Department spokesman Fred
Harpster. The man was not immediately identified.
   A man and a woman also were taken to Sierra Vista Hospital for
treatment. Their conditions were not immediately available.
   Firefighters were able to save shops and restaurants near the
pier.
   The fire was reported at about 6:15 a.m.
   Firefighters were told by people at the scene that the pier was
treated with creosote, a carcinogen the federal Environmental
Protection Agency has banned from over-the-counter sales as a wood
treatment and from use as a pesticide.
   Authorities ordered an evacuation of businesses and residences
downwind from the fire for about a quarter mile.
   A Coast Guard Marine Safety crew was en route from San Francisco
to check for pollution, said Coast Guard spokesman Fred Smith.
