<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-01 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Falls Around Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Up to a foot of snow fell Thursday around Lake Erie, with lesser
amounts around the rest of the Great Lakes, and parts of Arkansas
had lowland flooding from recent heavy rain.
   By the midday, snow fell from central New York state and the
northeast two-thirds of Pennsylvania across the lower Great Lakes,
northern Ohio, northern Indiana, northern Illinois, southern
Wisconsin and Michigan.
   On the downwind side of Lake Erie, in western New York state,
about 12 inches of snow fell at Colden, Dunkirk and Springville.
Seven inches fell at Glenfield, with 6 inches at Gowanda and 5 at
Silver Creek.
   Along the southern shore of the lake in Ohio, about 8 inches of
snow covered North Perry, Madison and northern Geauga County by
early afternoon. Lesser amounts over northeastern Ohio included 4
inches at Mentor, Ashtabula and Thompson, 2 inches at Chardon and an
inch at Burton.
   Traverse City, Mich., got 3 inches of snow in the six hours up to
1 p.m. EST.
   Elsewhere, snow was scattered across central Kentucky into
central Tennessee.
   In eastern and northeastern Arkansas, lowland flooding continued
along sections of the lower White, Black, Cache and St. Francis
rivers.
   Flood warnings were posted over the Sulphur River and Cypress
Creek basins of northeastern Texas and the Sabine River basin in
eastern Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 16
degrees at Faribault, Minn., to 81 at Oceanside and Point Mugu,
Calif. Thursday morning's official low was 9 degrees below zero at
Hibbing, Minn.
   For Friday, rain was forecast over the northern section of the
Pacific Coast.
   Highs only in the 20s were predicted over northern Maine; near 30
over southwestern Pennsylvania; in the 30s and 40s from central
Maine across the Virginias, over the Ohio Valley, the Great Lakes,
the upper Mississippi Valley, the Rockies, and from the central
Rockies to much of the northern half of the Pacific Coast; in the
60s to near 70 over the Florida Peninsula; in the 70s across central
Texas and from southern Arizona across southern California; and in
the 50s and 60s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
