<1ST_LINE>u w AM-NursingHomes 1stLd-Writethru a0753 12-01 0783</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nursing Homes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0753,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Nusing Homes List</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nursing Homes Rated in Consumer Guide</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after pvs 7th graf bgng ``Dr. Paul ...'' to
include comment from AARP</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most recent surprise inspections of the
nation's nursing homes showed that 43 percent failed to meet food
sanitation standards and nearly 30 percent didn't properly
administer drugs or ensure good personal hygiene, the government
reported Thursday.
   In a 75-volume guide for consumers, federal officials released
grades for each of the 15,000 nursing homes on 32 of the
approximately 500 standards by which they are measured at least once
a year in on-site inspections.
   Overall, the failure rate exceeded 15 percent in 10 categories.
But about 2,400 nursing homes received passing marks in all 32
categories.
   The massive report, a compilation of material previously
available only on a piece-meal basis through state regulatory
agencies, amounts to the first federally sanctioned catalog for
people looking for a nursing home.
   ``I think this is a landmark achievement, not because it an end
to itself but because it will help people pose thoughtful, further
questions in seeking out a nursing home,'' said Dr. William L.
Roper, head of the Health Care Financing Administration that
oversees Medicare and Medicaid.
   But neither the nursing-home industry nor its severest critics
greeted the report with enthusiasm. Elma Holder, director of the
National Citizens' Coalition for Nursing Home Reform, said Roper
``should be embarrassed and ashamed to present these documents so
proudly ... At best they provide a teaser to the consumers to try to
obtain a copy of the full survey report of the facility.''
   Dr. Paul Willging, executive vice president of the 9,000-memember
American Health Care Association, the major nursing home trade
group, called the report unreliable and ``In fact, the guide could
be harmful to consumers who use it as a shortcut to selecting a
nursing home.''
   But the American Association of Retired Persons praised the
report as a ``good start'' toward full disclosure of information
about nursing home quality.
   ``We are pleased that the federal government has taken valuable
information about the quality of nursing home care out of its
computers and made it available to the individuals and families who
need it most,'' said AARP Executive Director Horace Deets.
   Roper acknowledged it should not be viewed as a one-stop guide,
and conceded that a major shortcoming was that the 32 performance
indicators were listed only as having been ``met'' or ``unmet,''
rather than showing the severity of failures.
   For example, a nursing home that needed 30 nurses on staff to
meet patient-nurse ratios and had only 26 would receive the same
``unmet'' citation as if it only had 10 nurses.
   By law, the most recent and full report has to be available for
inspection at each nursing home, giving more detail for what led to
``unmet'' citations.
   ``This document ... is not the ultimate report on nursing homes
across the country but we present national statistics in order to be
helpful in interpreting how a given nursing home compares to other
nursing homes across the country,'' Roper said at a news conference.
   In addition to showing that 42.8 percent of the nursing homes
received an ``unmet'' grade when measured against minimum federal
standards for food storage, preparation and distribution, the report
found these other ``unmet'' percentages:
   _Daily personal hygiene standard for patients, 29.8 percent.
   _Proper and timely administration of prescribed drugs, 29 percent.
   _Isolation techniques to prevent spread of infection, 24.7
percent.
   _Rehabilitative care to promote maximum physicial functioning to
prevent loss of ability to walk and otherwise move freely, 21.6
percent.
   None of the other 27 categories registered an ``unmet''
percentage above 20 percent.
   At the A-plus end of the scale, the report shows that 99.7
percent meet requirements for discharging or transferring patients;
99.6 percent allow residents to communicate freely with others; 99.5
percent provide emergency medical services as necessary.
   Willging, speaking for the industry, noted the report is based on
the judgments of more than 3,000 inspectors, and that the most
recent inspections included in the document occurred last summer.
Some are 18 months old.
   ``Consumers must not consider the HCFA report a substitute for
visiting nursing homes during the slection process,'' said Willging.
``Visting and asking the right questions are essential.''
   Sheldon L. Goldbert, president of the American Association of
Homes For The Aging, another trade group, said, ``The report renders
high-quality care and substandard care nearly indistinguishable by
its failure to separate serious, ongoing problems from minor,
one-time infractions.''
   But Ms. Holder of the non-profit reform coalition said: ``We
think the national statistics are misleading. Conditions are worse.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
