<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Senators-Arafat     12-01 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senators-Arafat,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sixty-Nine Senators Applaud Decision To Bar Arafat From U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty-one senators and eight senators-elect,
including Vice President-elect Dan Quayle, on Thursday endorsed the
decision by Secretary of State George P. Shultz to deny a visa to
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
   The 35 Republicans and 34 Democrats told Shultz in a letter that
Arafat was associated with terrorism and has ``no place in the
United States.'' Barring Arafat was entirely justified because
Arafat is chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization, which,
they said, ``engages in terrorism.''
   ``The U.S. government has convincing evidence that PLO elements
have engaged in terrorism against Americans,'' the lawmakers told
Shultz. ``As you rightfully and lawfully concluded, such an
individual has no place in the United States.''
   The letter-writing effort was organized by Sens. Dennis
DeConcini, D-Ariz., and Charles Grassley, R-Iowa.
   ``We must continue our policy of denying admission to our country
those, including Arafat, who profess terrorism as a tool of foreign
policy,'' DeConcini said.
   Grassley said the PLO under Arafat remains committed to terrorism
and added: ``Shultz's action makes it clear that the U.S. will not
tolerate such activity.''
   Arafat sought a visa to visit the United States in order to
address the United Nations General Assembly.
   Shultz's decision prompted an international uproar and the
General Assembly on Wednesday approved a resolution deploring the
move and declaring it a violation of U.S. responsibilities as the
host nation for the U.N.
   A strong sentiment developed for moving the assembly session to
Geneva in order that Arafat might address it.
   Signing the letter were DeConcini and Grassley and Sens. Don
Nickles, R-Okla.; Thad Cochran, R-Miss.; Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn.;
Bob Dole, R-Kan.; Dan Quayle, R-Ind.; William L. Armstrong, R-Colo.;
Robert W. Kasten, R-Wis.; Ted Stevens, R-Alaska; Arlen Specter,
R-Pa; Phil Gramm, R-Texas; John Heinz, R-Pa.; John McCain, R-Ariz.;
and Gordon J. Humphrey, R-N.H.
   Also Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo.; Pete Wilson, R-Calif.; John C.
Danforth, R-Mo.; Pete V. Domenici, R-N.M.; Jesse Helms, R-N.C.; Jake
Garn, R-Utah; Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah; Frank H. Murkowski, R-Alaska;
Larry Pressler, R-S.D.; Alphonse M. D'Amato, R-N.Y.; David
Durenberger, R-Minn.; William V. Roth, R-Del.; Chic Hecht, R-Nev.;
Christopher S. Bond, R-Mo.; Steve Symms, R-Idaho; Mitch McConnell,
R-Ky.; and Warren B. Rudman, R-N.H.
   Democratic senators signing were Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio;
Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn.; James Sasser, D-Tenn.; Patrick J.
Leahy, D-Vt.; Donald W. Riegle, D-Mich.; Wendell H. Ford, D-Ky.;
Daniel K. Inouye, D-Hawaii; J. James Exon, D-Neb.; Frank R.
Lautenberg, D-N.J.; Bob Graham, D-Fla.; and Carl Levin, D-Mich.
   Also, Albert Gore Jr., D-Tenn.; J. Bennett Johnston, D-La.;
Quentin N. Burdick, D-N.D.; Harry Reid, D-Nev.; Richard C. Shelby,
D-Ala.; Lawton Chiles, D-Fla.; Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va.; Alan J.
Dixon, D-Ill.; Howell Heflin, D-Ala.; Tom Harkin, D-Iowa; Kent
Conrad, D-N.D.; Thomas A. Daschle, D-S.D.; Spark M. Matsunaga,
D-Hawaii; Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas; Barbara A. Mikulski, D-Md.; Max
Baucus, D-Mont.; and Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.
   Senators-elect signing the letter were Trent Lott, D-Miss.;
Connie Mack, R-Fla.; Slade Gorton, R-Wash.; Joseph I. Lieberman,
D-Conn.; Richard H. Bryan, D-Nev.; Herbert Kohl, D-Wis.; Conrad
Burns, D-Mont.; and Charles S. Robb, D-Va.
</TEXT>
