<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brawley-McClease     12-01 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brawley-McClease,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Who Claimed He Taped Brawley Advisers Is Indicted For Perjury</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who said he recorded conversations of
advisers to Tawana Brawley _ who said she was a victim of a racist
sex attack but refused to cooperate with police _ but then produced
only blank tapes has been indicted.
   Samuel McClease, 26, a self-described surveillance expert from
Newark, N.J., was indicted by a federal grand jury Wednesday on
charges of perjury and obstruction of justice. The indictment
closely paralleled a criminal complaint filed against him last
summer.
   The action comes a month after a state grand jury concluded that
Ms. Brawley, a black teen-ager from upstate New York, had concocted
her story of abduction and sexual assault by whites.
   McClease, who has been free on $100,000 bond, will be arraigned
Dec. 8, said Deborah Corley, a spokeswoman for U.S. Attorney Rudolph
Giuliani. He faces a maximum penalty of five years in prison and a
$250,000 fine on each count, if convicted.
   There was no telephone listing for McClease in Newark. His
lawyer, Leonard Joy of the Legal Aid Society, was not in his
Manhattan office when called for comment.
   Ms. Brawley, formerly of Wappingers Falls, touched off a
nationwide controversy after claiming she had been abducted and
sexually assaulted for several days by up to six white men,
including one who flashed a police badge.
   Ms. Brawley and her family, however, refused to cooperate with
state investigators on the advice of lawyers C. Vernon Mason and
Alton H. Maddox Jr. and the Rev. Al Sharpton.
   In June, McClease told federal investigators and television
reporters that he had bugged the conversations of Ms. Brawley's
advisers and could produce tapes that undermined her story.
   McClease claimed Sharpton hired him to bug his home as well as
Mason's home and office.
   Sharpton has vigorously denied McClease's claims.
   According to the indictment, McClease claimed he had 10 audio
tapes of conversations among Mason, Maddox and Sharpton.
   But McClease could produce only blank tapes in reply to a grand
jury subpoena. He signed an affidavit saying he could not produce
the tapes.
</TEXT>
