<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1852EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest     12-01 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leadership Calls for Calm, Death Toll Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev told officials in
Armenia and Azerbaijan on Thursday to restore order in their
neighboring southern republics, where 28 people have been killed in
recent ethnic violence.
   Gorbachev called the Communist Party leaders of the republics,
and deputies to the Supreme Soviet, to a meeting after the national
parliament issued an appeal for calm in the Caucasus at the end of a
three-day session.
   Pravda, the Communist Party newspaper, said the death toll in the
past two weeks had reached 28, which brings to more than 60 the
number of people killed since trouble began between Armenia and
Azerbaijan in February over control of the Nagorno-Karabakh region.
   Nagorno-Karabakh's population is predominantly ethnic Armenian
but the territory does not have a common border with Armenia. It was
assigned to Azerbaijan in 1923.
   Armenia and Armenians in the territory want it annexed to
Armenia, but Azerbaijan and the Kremlin have refused.
   In a report on Thursday's meeting, the official news agency Tass
said: ``It was emphasized that inter-ethnic conflicts, strikes on
this basis and anti-social phenomena cause serious damage to the
economy and are objectively directed against the democratic
processes of renewal.''
   Under Gorbachev's leadership, the meeting called for ``the
resolute rejection of the attempts to sow discord and enmity on
national soil, and for the immediate establishment of close working
contacts on settling the situation in the region.''
   In a speech to the Supreme Soviet, the Kremlin representative in
the troubled region said ``the two republics literally boil,'' and
officials are finding it difficult to control the situation.
   ``Recent developments have shown most forcefuly that many levers
are still in the hands of all kinds of clans in Azerbaijan and
Armenia,'' Arkady Volsky said, and the official press in both
republics ``pour oil on the fire.''
   Tass quoted Alexander Katusev, deputy procurator-general, as
saying prosecutors, investigators and other officials were being
sent to Azerbaijan from all parts of the Soviet Union.
   An Interior Ministry spokesman identified as B. Mikhailov gave
Pravda the new death toll and said, without explanation, that it
included ``victims of circumstances not directly related to the
situation.'' He said the deaths were caused by ``provocative
incidents and even shooting.''
   Authorities have confiscated homemade pistols, sawed-off rifles
and explosives from young people in both Armenia and Azerbaijan, he
said.
   Ethnic rioting began in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait at the
end of February. At least 32 people were killed _ 26 Armenians and
six Azerbaijanis.
</TEXT>
