<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     12-01 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President David Letterman? No? How about
President Ted Koppel or Commander in Chief Mickey Mouse?
   They all got write-in votes in California. So did Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev, actor Clint Eastwood and several other famous
people.
   Los Angeles County election data made public Tuesday showed about
2,000 residents opted not to vote for either Republican George Bush
or Democrat Michael Dukakis.
   In all, 4,081 write-in votes were cast for ineligible
non-candidates for various offices.
   ``We've been getting away from a lot of the Mickey Mouse stuff,''
said Margarite Brown, division chief of election services. ``But the
write-ins were heavier this time.''
   Some of the others receiving write-in votes for president were
actor Anthony Quinn, former baseball star Steve Garvey, former
President Richard Nixon and E.T., star of the movie ``E.T. the
Extra-Terrestrial.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When a horde of husky Santas in full regalia
gathered at a downtown hotel lobby and began ho-ho-ho-ing, the
excitement was just too much for the children, who wept and clutched
their mothers in terror.
   It probably wouldn't have calmed them much to know that behind
those red suits was much of the Wheaton College football team's
offensive and defensive lines.
   ``I really love kids, but I didn't realize they'd be so scared,''
said Chris Davis, 19, of San Diego. ``I reached out to shake one's
hand and she started crying,'' he said Wednesday.
   The bravest youngster on hand was Nadia Sawtarie from Japan.
   The 3-year-old assessed the invaders from behind her mother's
skirts and then gathered the courage to venture out and offer a
tentative wave before scurrying back to safety.
   The fledgling Santas were gathered at the hotel to celebrate
their graduation from Santa school.
   The basics? Know all the reindeers' names. Forgo alcohol, tobacco
and garlic. Don't make any specific promises. And gently hold the
childrens' hands _ it's soothing and keeps him from grabbing the
beard.
</TEXT>
