<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Drug     12-01 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Drug,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Drug Arrests, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Top Mafia Leaders Arrested In U.S.-Italian Drug Raids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALERMO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of police carried out raids
Thursday as part of a U.S.-Italian crackdown on a drug ring that
brought cocaine to Italy on banana boats and sold heroin through
American pizza parlors, officials said.
   The Italian news agency ANSA said the people named in Italian
arrest warrants belonged to the Spatola, Gambino and Inzerillo crime
families in Italy and the United States. State-run RAI-TV said
several top Mafia figures were among those arrested, but gave no
names.
   An FBI statement released Thursday in Rome and Washington said
drug charges were filed against 208 people _ 75 in the United States
and 133 in Italy. The arrests followed a joint investigation of
Italian and U.S. authorities.
   Hundreds of Italian police, some using helicopters and dogs,
began the raids overnight in Milan, Naples, Florence, Bologna,
Cosenza, Trapani, Palermo and the Palermo suburb Torretta.
   They said they 12 people had been arrested by late Thursday, but
U.S. officials in Washington said 22 people had been taken into
custody in Italy.
   Italian news media said the government also asked the United
States to extradite eight reputed Mafia members living in the United
States.
   Italian authorities said the drug traffickers smuggled South
American cocaine aboard banana boats to ports in Belgium, Holland
and West Germany, then overland to Italy. The cocaine, intended for
sale in Europe, was exchanged for heroin that was smuggled into the
United States for sale throug pizzerias, officials said.
   The FBI said it also discovered cocaine was being sent from South
America to a laboratory 300 miles north of Madrid, Spain, to be
processed and sent to Italy.
   U.S. federal agents made arrests in New York; Philadelphia;
Miami; Baltimore; San Francisco; Newark, N.J.; Buffalo, N.Y., and
Rockford, Ill.
   Italian news agencies said the simultaneous drug raids came after
an investigation stemming from the so-called ``Pizza Connection''
international drug ring that sold $1.6 billion in heroin, mostly
through pizzerias in the United States.
   The U.S. part of that case ended in March 1987 with 18
convictions. Italian prosecutors have indicted 28 people for their
alleged involvement.
   FBI officials said Thursday's arrests followed a complex,
international investigation that began as separate inquiries three
years ago in Buffalo, Philadelphia and New York.
   Italian investigators joined the undercover operation two years
ago after the arrest of heroin couriers at airports in Palermo and
New York. The Italian news agency AGI said the women were paid about
$7,800 for every kilogram _ 2.2 pounds _ of heroin they smuggled
from Italy to the United States inside money belts.
</TEXT>
