<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-DebateAftermath     12-01 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Debate Aftermath,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supporters Praise Walesa for Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lech Walesa got more than 100 telegrams of
praise for his television debate with the government union chief,
and a banner saying ``Bravo, Lech'' was hung on the Warsaw
University campus Thursday.
   Solidarity supporters felt the founder of the outlawed free union
won Wednesday night's contest with Alfred Miodowicz, head of the
official labor unions, and senior advisers celebrated into the night.
   The 43-minute debate was Walesa's first appearance on Polish
television in five years and his longest ever. He vigorously
defended Solidarity's right to exist and said official unions should
join it in ``creating freedom.''
   Walesa is a shipyard electrician and led a strike in the
turbulent summer of 1980 that gave birth to Solidarity, the first
free union in the Soviet bloc.
   Poland's communist authorities initially recognized Solidarity,
but then suppressed and outlawed it after martial law was declared
in December 1981.
   Walesa complained of a touch of flu during and after debate and
returned home to the Baltic port of Gdansk on the early morning
express train. A crowd of supporters greeted him when it pulled in
at 10 a.m.
   Later in the day, the Solidarity Information Service said more
than 100 telegrams of congratulation had arrived and the ``Bravo,
Lech'' banner flew at the university for most of the day.
   Official media reported the debate prominently Thursday but
avoided comment on who won. Newspapers carried photographs of Walesa
on their front pages for the first time in seven years, standing
next to Miodowicz.
   A commentator on Thursday's evening news said: ``Last night's
television meeting of Miodowicz and Walesa gathered a record
audience. This is a new notion in our political culture. Everybody
(watched), even those who are apathetic.''
   The newspaper Express Wieczorny quoted sociology professor
Andrzej Tymowski as saying: ``The meeting was successful, but there
are no words that can do something in Poland. We need acts. ...
Basing the reform on television talks only will give us nothing.''
</TEXT>
