<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Steinberg 1stLd-Writethru a0775 12-01 0887</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steinberg, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0775,0913</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Live-in Companion Takes Stand in Steinberg Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-10, `After Steinberg ..., with 4 grafs to UPDATE
with details in court, CORRECTS phrasing of quotes; picks up 11th
graf, `Casolaro asked what ...; INSERTS 2 graf after 22nd graf,
`Steinberg then ..., with Steinberg's lawyer's comments; picks up
23rd graf: `Earlier Thursday ...; ADDS 2 grafs with admissible
testimony.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ex-girlfriend of a lawyer accused of fatally
beating his illegally adopted daughter testified Thursday that she
did not seek emergency help for the 6-year-old because she thought
her lover had healing powers.
   Hedda Nussbaum, fighting back sobs, got her first sight of Joel
Steinberg since the two were arrested in the November 1987 death of
6-year-old Lisa Steinberg. Steinberg, 47, is charged with
second-degree murder. Charges against Nussbaum have been dropped.
   Lisa's death gained national attention when it became known that
teachers and friends of the family had noticed symptoms of abuse but
failed to notify anybody. The state of New York has since passed the
so-called ``Lisa Steinberg laws'' that make it a crime not to report
such abuse.
   Nussbaum testified that she was in the bathroom when Steinberg
handed her the girl's limp body on the night of Nov. 1, 1987, after
Steinberg allegedly beat her.
   ``You knew Lisa was not asleep, didn't you?'' asked Assistant
District Attorney Peter Casolaro.
   ``Yes,'' Nussbaum replied, closing her eyes. Her mouth quivered
and she struggled to maintain her composure.
   Nussbaum, 46, had answered early questions in a steady, husky
voice, but increasingly fought back sobs.
   While on the stand, she twice looked at Steinberg _ once, for a
long moment, when she identified a photograph of Lisa, and again
when she spoke of her agreement to testify against him.
   After Steinberg left their Greenwich Village apartment to go to
dinner, Nussbaum said, ``I looked at the phone and I started
thinking, should I call 911'' or the child's doctor.
   Casolaro asked her why she didn't.
   ``Joel said he would take care of her, he'd get her up when he
got back,'' Nussbaum replied. ``I didn't want to show disloyalty or
distrust for him, so I didn't call.''
   Casolaro asked what she expected Steinberg to do.
   ``I expected him to get Lisa up because I thought he was a
healer,'' Nussbaum testified. The child died three days later.
   Steinberg, a disbarred lawyer, is accused of second-degree murder
in the death of Lisa. He has not been charged with beating Nussbaum,
his live-in companion, who was bruised and had a broken nose when
the couple was arrested.
   In earlier testimony about the night of Nov. 1, Nussbaum said
that Steinberg had asked her and the girl whether they had drunk
enough water that day. Nussbaum said she hadn't, and Steinberg,
apparently annoyed, took them into the kitchen.
   ``We went into the kitchen. He took a very hot pepper and cut a
small piece for Lisa and cut off a larger piece and gave it to me,''
she said.
   Asked why he did that, Nussbaum said, ``It made us want to drink
water. It made our mouths hot.'' She said she drank four or five
glasses, as did Lisa.
   A short time later, Nussbaum said, ``Lisa said to me that her
stomach hurt from drinking so much water.''
   The girl then asked if she could go to dinner with Steinberg, and
Nussbaum told her to go into the bedroom and ask Steinberg, she
testified.
   ``The next thing _ it's all hazy _ he came into the bathroom,''
she said. He was carrying the limp body of Lisa.
   Nussbaum, appearing on the brink of weeping, said she asked,
``What happened?''
   According to Nussbaum, Steinberg replied: ``What's the difference
what happened? This is your child. Hasn't this gone far enough?''
   She said she tried various methods to resuscitate the child,
moving her arms and pushing on her chest. Steinberg did nothing to
help, except to say, ``Relax _ go with her. Stay in harmony with
her.''
   Steinberg then left and went to dinner with a friend.
   Steinberg's attorney, Ira London, said after Nussbaum's
testimony: ``I think she was interesting, and parts of her testimony
were moving, but I don't think it was damaging.''
   London added, ``She's not filled in the gaps the district
attorney needs filled in to make a case.''
   Earlier Thursday, State Supreme Court Justice Harold Rothwax said
that Nussbaum would be allowed to testify about alleged brutality at
the hands of Steinberg, but not before she testifies about events
the night Lisa Steinberg was fatally injured.
   Rothwax said a mistrial would result if Nussbaum were to testify
about alleged beatings and so-called ``uncharged crimes'' _ and then
failed to testify about the events of Nov. 1 and Nov. 2, 1987.
   The prosecution compiled a list of 32 incidents of alleged
physical abuse by Steinberg in the past 10 years. The judge said he
would allow the prosecution to ask Nussbaum about five of them.
   The alleged incidents included two eye injuries, a
``life-threatening'' injury in 1981 that required the removal of her
spleen and one attack in which he threw her on the ground. The most
recent occurred within weeks of Lisa's death, when he allegedly beat
her with an exercise bar.
</TEXT>
