12-01 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Debate Aftermath, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0795,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Congratulates Authorities for `Courageous' TV Show</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Walesa quotes from news conference,
praising authorities for allowing debate. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa congratulated
government officials Thursday for a ``courageous'' decision to let
him speak uncensored on television, and said he hoped it bodes well
for future talks.
   Walesa got dozens of phone calls and more than 100 congratulatory
telegrams after his Wednesday night TV debate with the government
union chief, Alfred Miodowicz, Solidarity spokesmen said. A banner
saying ``Bravo, Lech'' was hung on the Warsaw University campus
Thursday.
   Supporters felt Walesa, a founder of the outlawed free trade
union movement, won the unprecedented debate and senior advisers
celebrated into the night.
   Walesa spoke to foreign and official Polish journalists at St.
Brygida's Church in his home city of Gdansk following his triumphant
return.
   ``I don't know who made the decision (to allow his appearance on
state-controlled TV), but I have to admit that this person was
courageous,'' . Walesa said, according to a TV videotape recording
of his remarks by ABC News.
   ``Knowing what I represent, this is a heroic decision and can
give cause for hope (for future talks.).''
   Walesa, the 1983 Nobel Peace laureate, praised TV producers for
an accurate program.
   ``I can say the television was honest and all right. This time
television behaved as it should be in the world, and I am nicely
surprised,'' said Walesa, wearing a red turtle neck sweater he said
he needed to protect a sore throat.
   He appeared in an ebullient mood and briefly put on a boxing
glove offered him by a Polish reporter.
   The 43-minute debate was Walesa's first appearance on Polish TV
in five years and his longest appearance ever.
   He vigorously defended Solidarity's right to exist and said the
official trade unions should join Solidarity in ``creating freedom.''
   Official mass media on Thursday prominently reported the debate,
but avoided much discussion of its content or any comment on who
won. However, Polish newspapers for apparently the first time in
seven years ran photographs of Walesa on their front pages, standing
next to Miodowicz at the TV studio.
   ``Last night's television meeting of Miodowicz and Walesa
gathered a record audience. ... Everybody came (to watch), even
those who are apathetic,'' said a commentator on the early evening
news.
   ``The meeting was successful, but there are no words that can do
something in Poland. We need acts ... Basing the reform on
television talks only will give us nothing,'' sociology professor
Andrzej Tymowski was quoted as saying by the Express Wieczorny
newspaper in Warsaw.
</TEXT>
