<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HighwayKillings 1stLd-Writethru a0793 12-01 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Highway Killings, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0793,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Search For Bodies After Four Found</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE that fifth body appears to be
female, was clothed; ADDS new quote from Pina, DELETES outdated
Gibney quote; picks up 6th graf, `Authorities said ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police dogs found a fifth body
Thursday, apparently that of a woman, in a search along two highways
in southeastern Massachusetts that was prompted by the discovery of
four women's bodies.
   The clothed and decomposed remains were found around 3:30 p.m.
near Freetown, off of Route 140, less than three miles from the site
where the first body was discovered in July, said Thomas Gibney of
the Bristol County district attorney's office.
   Gibney said authorities would continue the search. He said the
officer who found the body told him that it was appeared to be a
woman. No other details were available.
   District Attorney Ronald A. Pina has expressed fears that the
deaths are related and linked to the disappearance of several women
from the Weld Square area, known by police as a center for local
drug trading and prostitution.
   ``There are things that are not coincidence, that are in
common,'' Pina said after the fifth body was found.
   Authorities said the bodies of three women were found near the
same Interstate 195 exit in Dartmouth, and a fourth body was
discovered near Freetown, about 10 miles away.
   State Trooper Jose Gonsalves said one of the victims was
strangled and the cause of death in the other four cases is not
known. He and several other authorities discouraged early reports of
a possible serial killer.
   But there were strong similarities in the cases, the county
prosecutor said.
   ``I feel pretty confident they are connected somehow,'' Pina said.
   Two bodies were discovered in July, one in Dartmouth and the
other in Freetown. Last month, a third body was discovered near the
Dartmouth interstate exit.
   A search for more bodies began Monday when Connecticut state
police provided two dogs trained to search for bodies. On Tuesday,
the dogs found the skeletal remains of a fourth woman along the
interstate in Dartmouth. None of the women has been positively
identified.
   On Wednesday, a dog from Massachusetts state police joined the
search.
   Authorities are checking dental records of five women reported
missing in recent months to see if they match any of the bodies.
Three of the missing women were last seen or lived near or
frequented the Weld Square area.
   Jimmy Giammalvo, whose family has run a grocery store on Weld
Square since 1922, said he hadn't seen much change since the first
body was found. ``They (prostitutes) come in and out of here all the
time. It's business as usual,'' he said.
   After three days searching the Dartmouth area, the searchers
moved to along Route 140 in Freetown and Lakeville, near where the
body was found in July.
   Pina said he believes one person may have killed the three women
whose bodies were found in Dartmouth, and that the person was
familiar with the area.
   ``I personally don't believe it could have been someone traveling
through,'' he said. ``It looks like it was someone who was more
local, someone who knew the area, someone who felt confident enough
that they could go there and drop a body off by the road and leave.''
</TEXT>
