<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Australia-Yugoslavia     12-01 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Australia-Yugoslavia,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yugoslavia Rejects Australian Bid for Sentry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugoslavia rejected on Thursday an
Australian ultimatum to turn over a consulate guard accused of
shooting and wounding a demonstrator in Sydney, an official report
said.
   The diplomatic wrangle arose after a 16-year-old was shot in the
throat Sunday during a demonstration by about 1,500 Croatians
outside the Yugoslav consulate.
   Consulate officials refused to surrender the guard accused of
shooting the boy.
   Australia said Thursday the consulate will be closed down and its
staff expelled if he was not turned over by Friday evening.
   Foreign Minister Budimir Loncar summoned Australian Charge
d'Affaires Peter Shannon on Thursday and asked Australia to
re-examine its ultimatum, the Yugoslav state news agency Tanjug said.
   If not, Yugoslavia will react ``with adequate measures,'' Loncar
was quoted as saying. Tanjug did not say what these would be.
   Yugoslavia defended the guard's action, saying he ``had no choice
but, shooting into the air, to warn Australian authorities . ..
lives and security of workers in the consulate and their families
were directly imperiled.''
   Yugoslav officials said Australia failed to protect the consulate
from the protesters, whom they called ``fascist pro-Utasha emigres.''
   The Ustashas were Croatian fascists who teamed with Nazi Germany
in opposing Yugoslav resistance forces during World War II.
   Croatian extremists have been accused of killing at least two
Yugoslav diplomats abroad and wounding others in attacks over the
past 20 years.
   A group of 19 Ustashas, said to have been trained in Australia,
infiltrated Yugoslavia in 1972. Most were killed by Yugoslav
security forces, but 13 troops also died.
   Tanjug said Yugoslavia expects Australian officials ``to identify
and punish terrorist attackers.''
   However, Australian Foreign Minister Gareth Evans says his
government has enough evidence to prosecute the guard.
</TEXT>
