<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0749 12-01 0802</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0749,0827</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elementary Schools Reopen in West Bank; Palestinian Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ed: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Israeli injured; corrects
spelling of Barzilai hospital. PICKS up 7th pvs `The army...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMALLAH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Palestinian
children streamed to West Bank elementary schools Thursday after the
army lifted an order that shut down classes for most of 10 months.
   There were no reports of violence at the 612 private, state and
U.N.-run schools attended by about 230,000 first-through-sixth
graders.
   But elsewhere Thursday, a Palestinian teen-ager was killed and 15
Arabs were wounded when troops opened fire at rock-throwing
demonstrators in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, hospital
officials said.
   Near the West Bank Jewish settlement of Pisgat Zeev, an Israeli
driver was attacked with stones, lost control of his car and crashed
into an electricity pole, Israel radio said. He was reported to
suffer only slight injuries.
   The 17-year-old Palestinian was killed in the West Bank village
of Kifin, north of Jenin, when soldiers searching for protesters
opened fire after they were attacked with stones and a fire bomb, an
army statement said.
   The latest death raised to at least 317 the number of
Palestinians killed since they launched their uprising against
Israeli rule in the West Bank and Gaza Strip on Dec. 8, 1987. Eleven
Israelis also have died.
   Among the wounded was a 10-year-old boy from Deir Balah refugee
camp south of Gaza City, said the hospital officials, who demanded
anonymity. They said the boy, identified as Hamad Hassan Abu Dan,
was in critical condition with a bullet wound in his chest and was
transferred to Barzilai hospital in Israel for further treatment.
   The army confirmed that four Palestinians were wounded in clashes
in the central market of the West Bank city of Nablus and said it
was checking the other reports of wounded.
   The start of elementary school classes was the first step in the
army's three-stage opening of 1,194 West Bank schools, closed for
all but a few weeks since Feb. 3. Junior high schools will open Dec.
11 and high schools Dec. 18.
   Brig. Gen. Shaike Erez, head of the West Bank military
administration, said there was no guarantee the schools would remain
open.
   ``We have made the opening conditional on the schools being used
for learning and not to create demonstrations,'' Erez said on army
radio. ``We have no guarantees that everything will go smoothly.''
   The army closed the schools in February after charging they were
a breeding ground for anti-Israeli demonstrations.
   West Bank universities and colleges are to remain closed
indefinitely.
   The 365 schools attended by 175,000 students in the Gaza Strip
have been open, although there have been sporadic closures.
   In the West Bank city of Ramallah, nine miles north of Jerusalem,
children greeted one another happily in the schoolyard of the
Quaker-run Friends Boys School as it opened at 7:30 a.m.
   ``They were excited, perhaps more about meeting each other than
about being back in class,'' principal Khalil Mahshi said.
   Most fourth graders in an English class at the Friends School
said they were glad to be back in school.
   ``I missed school because I didn't see my friends. I studied at
home, but it wasn't the same,'' said 9-year-old Eric Kapenga.
   Ahmed Boshnah, also 9, said he had no difficulty getting up for
school Thursday even though classes started half an hour earlier to
compensate for school ending at noon instead of 1 p.m., in
compliance with PLO-issued strike orders.
   ``At home, I played a lot and watched TV. But I don't miss it. It
got boring,'' Boshnah said.
   Sam Awwad, 11, disagreed, glancing disparagingly at his
sixth-grade science text.
   ``I'd rather be throwing rocks at the Jews,'' said Awwad.
   Principal Mahshi said school attendance Thursday was about 150
students, down considerably from last year's 200 elementary pupils.
   ``In the upper grades, the loss will be even greater,'' added
Mahshi. He said this year's class of graduating seniors would number
just seven, compared to 33 before the school closure.
   The sharp drop in enrollment was due to Arab-American students
leaving for schools in the United States and hundreds of West Bank
students enrolling in schools in Jerusalem during the prolonged
closure, Mahshi said.
   Tourism Ministry officials, meanwhile, announced that religious
Christmas celebrations would take place in the West Bank town of
Bethlehem as scheduled.
   The statement came after Palestinian municipal officials said
earlier this week they were canceling city-run Christmas activities
in solidarity with the Palestinian uprising.
   The Palestinian decision means there won't be an annual reception
for Arab and Israeli dignitaries, a Christmas eve Boy Scout parade
or decorations in city streets.
   The Tourism Ministry plans to stage its annual international
choir festival and other events.
</TEXT>
