<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeltaHearing     12-01 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delta Hearing,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delta Tightens Crew Guidelines; Engineer Says Warning Switch
Corroded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IRVING, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines imposed tighter guidelines
for cockpit conduct Thursday and a federal panel probing the crash
of Flight 1141 learned of occasional lapses in communication and
procedure on Delta flight decks.
   Delta officials said they had planned to issue the new guidelines
before the National Transportation Safety Board began its public
hearing this week into the Aug. 31 crash of the flight upon takeoff
from Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport. Fourteen of the 108
people on the plane died.
   Marion Dittman, who led a team that conducted a special safety
audit of the Atlanta-based carrier in 1987, told the panel Thursday
that Delta's policy a year ago was to give pilots ``maximum
discretion'' in control of the cockpit.
   ``We were surprised at some of the things we found,'' Ms. Dittman
said.
   ``There is no evidence Delta's crew are (on the whole) either
unprofessional or purposely negligent,'' the report said. ``Rather,
it was observed that crew members are frequently acting as
individuals rather than as members of smoothly running teams.''
   The report cited some Delta captains' passive leadership, under
which fellow flight officers often ``proceeded on the assumption
that they knew what the captain wanted,'' and led to
misunderstandings, oversights and errors.
   Ms. Dittman also told the board that a followup survey in
November showed Delta was making ``great strides'' in tightening its
regulations.
   The revised regulations will require crew members to call out
items that have been cleared on a checklist.
   Earlier this week at the NTSB hearing, Flight 1141 Capt. Larry
Davis testified he had used hand gestures to signal his progress
through the checklist.
   Ken Adams, a flight instructor, told the panel Thursday that one
major change on crew members' flight checklists will be to look at
the wing flaps twice.
   ``We started deploying them (the flaps) as soon as we go so the
public can see them and say they're down,'' he said.
   The wing flaps have been the focus of much of the panel's
investigation.
   Investigators have been puzzled that the plane's flap handle was
found up, the retracted position, although some of the plane's flaps
and slats were extended.
   A switch for a system that would have warned the pilots of Delta
Air Lines Flight 1141 that the jet's wing flaps were improperly set
for takeoff had corroded, a veteran engineer told federal
investigators Thursday.
   NTSB officials say the hearing is only for fact-gathering and
that no conclusions will be released until a report is made public
in six months.
   All three crew members agreed before the board that, to the best
of their recollection, they made all necessary preflight
preparations, including setting the flaps, although they may have
bent several Delta regulations.
   One of their admitted technical violations was allowing a flight
attendant into the cockpit during a long delay before takeoff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
