<DOCNO> AP881201-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 2159EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-China     12-01 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-China,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Official Arrives in Moscow, Breaking 31-Year Hiatus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen arrived
Thursday as his nation's first high-level envoy to the Soviet
capital in 31 years.
   He will be meeting Soviet officials to seek agreement on the
conflict in Cambodia and prepare for a 1989 summit.
   The summit would be the first since 1959 when Nikita S.
Khrushchev met Chinese leader Mao Tse-Tung in Beijing. Qian's visit
is the first by a Chinese foreign minister since the visit of Chou
En-lai in 1957.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze greeted him at
Moscow's Sheremetyevo 2 Airport. They are to conduct two days of
talks, and the Chinese official said he also expected to meet with
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``China and the Soviet Union, as two great neighboring countries,
must live in peace and neighborly relations,'' Qian said in an
arrival statement distributed by the Soviet news agency Tass.
   ``We are glad that in recent years Chinese-Soviet relations
gradually are improving,'' he was quoted as saying.
   Relations between the two communist powers soured in the early
1960s in a struggle over the direction of world communism. They
reached a low point in 1969, when each side sent at least 1 million
soldiers to the border and fought a short frontier war.
   However, Gorbachev has made several recent overtures to China,
ordering a pullout of Soviet troops from Afghanistan, reducing
Soviet troops on the Chinese border, and agreeing to direct talks on
the Vietnamese presence in Cambodia.
   In late October, officials announced that negotiators had reached
agreement settling most Soviet-Chinese differences over the eastern
part of their common boundary.
   China wants the Soviet Union to use its influence to force
Vietnamese soldiers out of Cambodia, where they have been fighting
Chinese-backed rebels for the past decade.
   The dispute has been the main stumbling block to a Soviet-Chinese
summit.
   Tass said Shevardnadze and Qian spent much of their time in their
first meeting Thursday dicussing that dispute.
   Qian indicated the summit was a virtual certainty, regardless of
progress on the Cambodian issue. Gorbachev is expected to go to
Beijing for the summit because China's senior leader Deng Xiaoping
is 84 years old and rarely travels abroad.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Vadim Perfiliev told reporters
earlier that Shevardnadze would make a return visit to China.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
