<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PolygamistTrial     12-01 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polygamist Trial,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murder Trial For Three Polygamist Clan Members To Begin Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COALVILLE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for three polygamist clan
members charged with killing a state law officer say their case will
center on psychological stress from police floodlights and
loudspeakers.
   An eight-member jury and two alternates were empaneled Thursday
and opening arguments were to begin Friday in the trial of clan
leader Addam Swapp, 27, his brother Jonathan Swapp, 21, and
brother-in-law John Timothy Singer, 22.
   All are charged with second-degree murder in the Jan. 28 death of
Corrections Lt. Fred House.
   House was killed during a brief shootout that ended a standoff
between the clan and 100 officers fearful of storming the rural
compound because of the clan's nine children. The impasse had begun
13 days before when Addam Swapp bombed a nearby Mormon chapel.
   Prosecutors contend it was the wheelchair-bound Singer who fired
the fatal shot, but he told officers later that he was aiming at
dogs and never intended to harm anyone.
   Addam Swapp's attorney, John Bucher, said the defense would place
``more of an emphasis on the psychological state'' of the
defendants. During much of the standoff authorities aimed
floodlights and recordings of high-pitched sirens at the 15 clan
members inside the compound.
   Prosecutors are expected to duplicate much of the evidence
presented during a federal trial last spring in which the Swapp
brothers, Singer and his mother, Vickie Singer, were convicted of
bombing and related charges.
   Swapp, an excommunicated Mormon, admitted planting 87 sticks of
dynamite at the Kamas Stake Center. He said he was divinely inspired
to bomb the chapel to signal the impending collapse of church and
state and to trigger the return of Vickie Singer's late husband,
John Singer.
   Before jury selection began, District Judge Michael Murphy issued
a 25-page, 276-question survey asking the 250 potential jurors
whether they were active members of the Mormon Church, if they
attended services at the Marion chapel and whether they associated
with any organized polygamous group.
   On Wednesday, Murphy agreed to allow attorneys to question
prospective jurors about whether they believed in divine revelation.
   The judge said he would not reject members of The Church of
Jesus-Christ of Latter-day Saints who believe their faith's
president, Ezra Taft Benson, is a prophet who receives divine
revelations.
   The trial is expected to last up to three weeks.
</TEXT>
