<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0766,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Scores of Strikers; Guerrillas Seize, Burn Bus</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs UPDATING with more arrests. Picks up 4th
graf pvs, It was ... with minor editing to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police tore down barricades of burning tires,
fired tear gas and arrested hundreds of protesters Thursday during
an illegal general strike against government austerity measures,
officials said.
   Police reported arresting 265 people during the daylong strike
that the government had banned.
   Strike leader Valentin Pacho claimed police arrested more than
500 people, most of them when demonstrators tried to march from
surrounding neighborhoods into downtown Lima.
   Authorities said leftist guerrillas seized and burned a city bus.
However, no injuries were reported during the strike.
   It was the fourth general work stoppage this year and the fifth
against the 3-year-old government of President Alan Garcia. The
strike comes during growing unrest caused by Peru's most serious
economic recession this century.
   Prime Minister Armando Villanueva charged the strike was being
manipulated by the Maoist guerrilla movement Shining Path to
destabilize and eventually topple the elected government. Labor
leaders denied that.
   At one point, a column of 50 hooded Shining Path guerrillas
marched rapidly across a downtown plaza filled with strikers and
then dispersed in the crowds. Police exploded tear gas canisters and
fired their guns into the air to scatter the protesters.
   Pacho said 80 percent of unionized workers had joined the strike,
but the Labor Ministry claimed 90 percent of Lima's offices,
factories and other businesses were functioning.
   The capital is still reeling from a five-day power outage caused
by leftist guerrillas last week, as well as sporadic water shortages
and growing shortages of basic foods.
   The country has also been hit with a paralyzing mining strike,
that began Oct. 17 and has led to numerous clashes between strikers
and Lima police.
   Labor leaders said the strike was called to protest measures
imposed by the government last week to slow inflation estimated to
reach 2,000 percent this year.
   Gen. Oswaldo Diaz, Lima's top police official, told reporters
``several subversives'' seized and burned a city bus after forcing
passengers out.
   Authorities said 8,000 police maintained order, arresting 78
strikers as they set up roadblocks of burning tires and rubble.
Police quickly tore down the barricades.
   Lima rush hour traffic was lighter than normal with bus
transportation down about 30 percent. Many stores and shops downtown
opened late.
   Pacho said demonstrations were held in Huancayo, Cuzco and
Arequipa. Radio stations reported disturbances in those cities, but
it was unclear how effective the strike was outside Lima.
   Labor is seeking further pay increases following the austerity
measures. The measures raised the minimum monthly wage from 15,000
to 24,000 intis, equivalent to about $50, but more than doubled food
prices and devalued currency 50 percent.
</TEXT>
