<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan-UN     12-01 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan-UN,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Radio Says Rebels Hijacked UN Convoy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan's official radio said
Thursday a Moslem guerrilla group hijacked a U.N. grain convoy and
detained three employees of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees.
   Milton Merino, spokesman for the office of the U.N. Coordinator
for Afghanistan in Geneva, said two relief trucks were stopped about
100 miles north of Kabul, and ``it seems that some of the contents
... were taken.''
   A spokesman for the U.N. refugee agency in Geneva said the three
employees _two Afghans and a Canadian named Louis Barbeau _ were
detained by an unknown group and released Monday. He said they were
in a 17-truck convoy delivering grain to areas outside Kabul, the
Afghan capital.
   Merino said the convoy was the first to try delivering food to
outlying areas under the U.N.-sponsored program.
   Kabul radio said members of Gulbaddin Hekmatyar's Hezb-e-Islami
guerrilla group blocked a road in Parwan province, central
Afghanistan, and looted 10 U.N. trucks.
   The radio consistently blames Hekmatyar's group for events inside
Afghanistan. Shah Mahmood, a spokesman for the Hezb-e-Islami in
Islamabad, denied involvement in the hijacking.
   Mohammad Shoaib of the Jamiat-e-Islami insurgents, who have a
strong force in Parwan province, said, ``We don't know who would
have stopped the convoy.''
   Late last year, there were reports of medicine supplies destined
for Jamiat commander Ahmad Shah Masood being hijacked by Hekmatyar's
guerrillas in northeastern Afghanistan.
   Moslem insurgents began fighting after a Communist coup in April
1978 and Soviet military forces entered the country in December
1979. Soviet troops now are withdrawing under a U.N.-mediated
agreement.
   U.N. spokeswoman Nadia Younes said Thursday at the organization's
headquarters in New York the convoy's problems had been ``greatly
exaggerated by the press.''
   She said Sadruddin Aga Khan, the U.N. official in charge of
Afghan relief, ``feels it has been blown out of proportion by the
media.''
   ``It was a misunderstanding about the route of the convoy and he
pointed out there are many checkpoints along the way and the signals
were not functioning properly,'' she said, adding: ``The U.N. staff
who were abducted, or whatever, was in constant touch by radio with
headquarters.''
   More than $1 billion in aid is being sought by the United Nations
to assist more than 5 million refugees when they return to
Afghanistan from Pakistan and Iran.
</TEXT>
