<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Demjanjuk 1stLd-Writethru a0713 12-01 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Demjanjuk, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney for Nazi War Criminal Burned with Acid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Four grafs SUB for grafs 5-6 pvs, Police identified ...
UPDATING with reported quote by assailant. Picks up 7th graf pvs,
Reporters who ... with minor editing.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Holocaust survivor splashed acid in the face
of a lawyer for convicted Nazi war criminal John Demjanjuk at a
funeral Thursday for another Demjanjuk attorney who committed
suicide.
   The injured lawyer, Yoram Sheftel, was reported in satisfactory
condition at Jerusalem's Hadassah Hospital's eye unit, where he was
transferred for treatment after the incident.
   The attorney complained of blurred vision and pain in his left
eye and will be kept under observation for several days, said Ruth
Mekel, a Hadassah spokeswoman.
   A woman standing near Sheftel suffered a minor eye injury from
the acid.
   Police identified the assailant as 70-year-old Yisrael
Yehezkieli, who was detained after the attack at Jerusalem's
Sanhedria Cemetery. He was seen being led away with his hands cupped
over his face.
   The national Itim news agency quoted the assailant as telling
police interrogators that all his family were killed by the Nazis
and that ``these killers are not worthy of defense.''
   Israel Television, which reported the attack, announced it was
canceling the scheduled broadcast of a documentary film on the
Demjanjuk trial.
   Police officials who insisted on anonymity said Yehezkieli lived
in a home for the elderly in the working-class Katamon quarter of
Jerusalem. He was employed as a guard at the Education Ministry,
they said. Divorced and the father of three children, Yehezkieli was
believed to be from Poland, they said.
   Reporters who covered the 14-month Demjanjuk trial said
Yehezkieli was a frequent spectator.
   The police officials said Yehezkieli apparently was upset about
the suicide of Demjanjuk lawyer Dov Eitan, who was buried Thursday.
They quoted him as telling neighbors: ``I wanted to speak to Eitan,
and now I have nobody to talk to.''
   Eitan, a 53-year-old former district judge, died Tuesday after
jumping from a 15th floor hotel window in Jerusalem. Police said the
death was a suicide.
   Itim quoted an unidentified witness as saying the assailant
shouted ``Eitan died because of you!'' before hurling the acid.
   The injured woman, identified as Edna Shabtai, a writer from Tel
Aviv, was released after treatment, hospital officials said.
   Ms. Shabtai said on Israel radio that she heard Yehezkieli shout
``Everything is because of you!'' then felt the acid strike her face.
   Eitan's death has delayed Demjanjuk's Supreme Court appeal of a
death sentence until May 4. The appeal had been scheduled to begin
Monday.
   Demjanjuk, a 68-year-old retired autoworker from suburban
Cleveland, was sentenced to death in April for committing crimes
against humanity and the Jewish people as an operator of gas
chambers at Treblinka death camp in Poland, where 850,000 Jews
perished during World War II.
   He has consistently denied he was ``Ivan the Terrible'' of the
Treblinka camp.
   Demjanjuk's son-in-law, Ed Nishnic, said in a telephone interview
from Cleveland that the family was saddened by the acid-throwing
incident.
   ``It shows there is very much emotion surrounding this trial,''
he said.
   Nishnic said the attack on Sheftel could hamper the family's
efforts to find an Israeli lawyer to replace Eitan in the case.
   ``This is going to make it even more difficult to find another
attorney,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
