<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico 1stLd-Writethru a0804 12-01 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0804,0735</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salinas Becomes President of Mexico As Opposition Protests</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, COMBINING a0804 and
a0723, UPDATING with protests throughout day, Shultz comment,
Salinas U.S. quote. No pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MO5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari took
office Thursday and promised to push for political and economic
modernization, as opponents protested his inauguration in congress
and in the streets.
   Salinas, a 40-year-old economist, succeeds President Miguel de la
Madrid for a six-year term. He inherits an economy threatened by
both recession and inflation, growth squeezed by a $102 billion
foreign debt, and a population impatient after six years of
austerity that reduced earnings about 50 percent.
   ``I take office in a complex hour. ... It is a singular moment in
our history, heavy with risks but rich in opportunity,'' Salinas
said in his inaugural address. He said he would govern ``for all
Mexicans'' and promised ``nationalist, democratic and popular''
reforms.
   He said efforts to reduce Mexico's foreign debt would begin
immediately.
   About 140 delegates from the leftist National Democratic Front
walked out of the Legislative Palace just before Salinas was
inaugurated, and members of the conservative National Action Party
held up signs declaring ``Fraud.''
   ``We are walking out because we don't want to endorse with our
presence the legitimacy of the Salinas de Gortari government,'' said
delegate Jaime Hernandez. The opposition maintains that Salinas'
Institutional Revolutionary Party cheated to win the July 6
presidential election and that Democratic Front nominee Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas was the real victor.
   Outside, thousands of Democratic Front supporters threw rocks at
police. Many in the crowd carried sticks. Several police and
demonstrators were injured.
   Police used tear gas to disperse about 1,500 demonstrators in the
Zocalo, the central square in front of the National Palace where a
post-inauguration parade was held. One woman held up two dead rats
and said they symbolized Salinas.
   Red Cross paramedic Carlos Daniel Ramirez said about 150 people
were injured, including police and soldiers, and treated at the
scene. A police spokeswoman said many arrests were made.
   Scattered demonstrations persisted through the day.
   Salinas invited the opposition to a political dialogue that would
include ``perfecting'' the electoral process, but said political
change is not enough.
   Unless the economic crisis is overcome, he said, ``stagnation
will wilt democracy, political competition will turn into social
conflict and frustrate aims for social justice.''
   Salinas said negotiations will begin at once on Mexico's debt,
aimed at cutting debt payments to a level that will leave the
country with enough money to invest in development and growth.
   ``We will look for new equilibriums with the United States, an
area of opportunities and delicate differences,'' Salinas said.
   U.S. Secretary of State George Shultz had an afternoon meeting
with Salinas and praised his inaugural address. He told reporters
Salinas felt ``good chemistry'' existed between himself and
President-elect George Bush.
   In an unusual arrangement, opposition leaders were permitted to
make televised speeches questioning Salinas' election before the
inauguration. In return, they agreed not to disrupt the actual
ceremony.
   Although the speeches were televised, walkouts and protest signs
were not shown. Cameras also avoided showing the brief violence in
the Zocalo.
   The new president outlined a vision of modern Mexico in keeping
with his free market ideas, in which a paternalistic state would
give way to a partnership of political parties, business, labor,
citizens' groups and the church.
   Democratic Front delegate Marcela Lombardo said in her speech
that Mexicans had actually voted for a ``radically different
program.''
   In his campaign, Cardenas called for increased government control
of the economy and a moratorium on debt payments.
   According to official figures, Salinas won barely more than 50
percent of the vote, Cardenas won 31 percent and National Action
candidate Manuel Clouthier, 17 percent.
   During his speech Salinas introduced heads of government
attending. The biggest rounds of applause went to presidents Fidel
Castro of Cuba and Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua.
   Also there were presidents Virgilio Barco of Colombia, Raul
Alfonsin of Argentina, Jose Napoleon Duarte of El Salvador, Jose
Azcona Hoyo of Honduras and Vinicio Cerezo Arevalo of Guatemala and
Prime Minister Manuel Esquivel of Belize.
   The U.S. delegation included Bush's son, John, and John's
Mexican-American wife, Columba.
</TEXT>
