<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-PLO, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0785,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Refuses U.N. Call For Arafat Visa</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs ``The secretary-general...' to correct
spelling of Giuliani.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States refused a request by the
General Assembly to issue a visa to Yasser Arafat so the PLO
chairman can speak to the world body on the Palestine issue, a U.N.
spokesman said Thursday.
   Arab diplomats said they would introduce a resolution Friday
morning to move the General Assembly from U.N. headquarters in New
York to Geneva to hear Arafat.
   A ranking U.N. official said a vote to move to Geneva could be
taken Monday and approval was certain.
   ``The secretary-general has received from the United States a
reply to the resolution adopted by the General Assembly asking the
United States to review and rescind its decision not to issue a visa
to Mr. Arafat,'' said U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani.
   ``This reply from the United States is negative, and will be
contained in a report by the secretary-general to come out tomorrow
morning,'' he added.
   The letter of refusal was ``extremely negative,'' said a
diplomatic source who saw the note.
   Arafat wanted to speak Thursday, the original opening day of the
assembly debate on Palestinian issues. But the State Department
denied the visa last Saturday on grounds the head of the Palestine
Liberation Organization was an accessory to terrorism.
   Earlier Thursday, a rally outside U.N. headquarters intended to
welcome Arafat became a protest by about 400 people at which
Palestinians and a few dozen anti-Zionist Orthodox Jews denounced
the refusal of a visa.
   Demostrators waved Palestinian flags and pictures of Arafat,
chanting ``Long Live the PLO!'' Most of the Palestinians wore
checked head scarves, Arafat's trademark.
   Standing among them holding anti-Zionist banners were
ultra-Orthodox Jews, in long black coats and wide brimmed hats, who
belong to the Orthodox Jews Against Zionism (Neturei Karta) group
and oppose the concept of a Jewish state.
   On Wednesday, the General Assembly denounced the United States
for refusing to let Arafat address it, giving Washington until
midnight Thursday to provide a visa. Only the United States and
Israel voted against the resolution, and Britain abstained.
   Arafat wants to address the General Assembly about the
declaration of an independent Palestinian state Nov. 15 and a
political statement that implicitly recognizes Israel by accepting
U.N. resolutions on the Middle East.
   Undersecretary-General Joseph V. Reed said the Secretariat was
making plans to move the General Assembly to Geneva, where the
session is expected to reconvene in mid-December.
   The United States says it does not oppose a move to Geneva and
would participate in the debate there.
   If the meeting goes to Geneva, it would be the first time the
General Assembly has transferred a meeting out of the United States
in protest.
   The resolution authorizing the move must be heard by a 16-member
budgetary advisory committee Friday because of the expense involved,
then would go to the General Assembly's finance committee before
reaching a vote in the assembly itself.
   The PLO has had a U.N. mission since 1975 and holds non-voting
observer status. The U.N. considers it the sole legitimate
representative of the Palestinian people and invites it to speak in
debates concerning Palestinians and the Middle East.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
