<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Madagascar-Malaria Adv08   12-01 0788</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Madagascar-Malaria, Adv 08,0810</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs Dec. 8 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Malaria, Once under Control, Again Serious in Madagascar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ROBERT WELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANTANANARIVO, Madagascar (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the central highlands of this
island nation, health officials are using DTT, banned in other parts
of the world, to combat a disease that once was under control _
malaria.
   Specially trained teams are spraying the inner walls of thousands
of homes with the powerful insecticide because it is deemed the most
effective and practical way for Madagascar, a nation struggling with
economic problems.
   A resurgence of malaria in the central highlands has already
claimed thousands of lives in the last two years, and a government
report said malaria could claim 100,000 to 250,000 lives in the next
six months if emergency measures were not taken.
   Malaria had largely disappeared from the central highlands, a
strip up to 170 miles wide running nearly 850 miles north to south,
after French colonial authorities used DDT in antimalarial campaigns
and drugs to treat those who got the disease.
   But the spraying stopped after independence in 1960, and in the
economic decline that followed a Socialist revolution in 1975,
antimalarial drugs, which had to be imported, were not available. At
the same time, the highlanders lost the moderate immunity people of
hyperendemic malarious areas usually develop.
   ``When it started coming back, people didn't know what it was,''
said Dr. Daniel Rakotojoelinadrasana, who directs two Lutheran
Church clinics. ``They thought it was a new disease and they named
it `Bemangovitra,' which means the `big chills'.''
   Even if people had recognized it as the old Tazomoka (mosquito
fever) there were virtually no drugs available to combat it. The
country had no foreign exchange to import drugs, and people wouldn't
have been able to afford to buy them in a country where income has
been falling for 20 years and wages average the equivalent of a
dollar a day or less.
   ``The nutritional status had fallen so much it made it much more
severe than in a healthy population,'' said Edmond de Gaiffier of
the World Bank.
   No reliable figures are available on how many people have died of
malaria in recent years, as any fever is usually diagnosed as
malaria. Few facilities are available for blood tests, and many
people have no access to any health care.
   Health Minister Jean-Jacques Seraphin and the World Health
Organization representative, Dr. Cyprian Hakizimana, said published
reports of 100,000 deaths were exaggerated.
   World Bank specialists said the toll was probably more in the
range of 30,000 and Dr. Pierre Coulanges, director of the Pasteur
Institute here, said the toll could be as high as 50,000 and in some
villages 20 percent of the residents had died.
   The plan to combat the malaria threat includes two controversial
elements.
   The first is the use of DDT, banned in developed countries after
it was found to be entering the food chain.
   Hakizimana said the World Health Organization had approved DDT as
a one-time measure because of the grave threat Madagascar faced, and
it will only be used inside houses, not on crops.
   De Gaiffier said DDT has acquired such a bad name that it wasn't
easy to find the 50 to 80 tons needed in Madagascar. It is preferred
because it remains effective for six months or more, through the
rainy season on the 226,658-square-mile island of 11 million people.
   Spraying on the walls will be effective because the malarial
mosquitoes rest on walls after biting their victims, said
Rakotojoelinadrasana.
   The second controversy involves the World Health Organization's
policy of providing drugs for treatment after people are infected
rather than distributing them for prophylaxsis, or prevention.
   Health Minister Seraphin said the government will make drugs
available for prophylaxsis only for children up to age 6 and
pregnant women.
   The World Health Organization recommends against use of drugs for
prophylaxsis in hyperendemic areas because of the cost, fears that
it will facilitate the spread of resistance and concerns about the
side effects.
   ``The WHO recommendation is logical on theoretical grounds,''
Rakotojoelinadrasana said. ``But the problem is that people who get
malaria may die from it. As medical doctors we are hesitating to
advise people to get malaria and then come to us.''
   De Gaiffier said scientists are very worried about the increasing
prevalance of malaria in higher elevations.
   It is ``following economic development up the mountain where
there are new population reservoirs with no immunity,'' he added.
   Farmers are using every piece of land they can find, including
steep hillsides, to grow rice and other crops. Rice is heavily
consumed in Madagascar and rice fields are perfect breeding grounds
for malaria mosquitoes.
 
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs Dec. 8</NOTE>
