<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-Reviews ADV02   12-01 0869</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Reviews, ADV 02,0888</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, Dec. 2, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Tenth Man' Tedious; `Maybe Baby' Sophisticated Comedy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Spelling of Rebeca in final graf is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most irritating thing about Sunday's Hallmark
Hall of Fame presentation on CBS, ``The Tenth Man,'' is how
self-consciously Important it is.
   Based on Graham Greene's intriguing story of a French lawyer
imprisoned by the Nazis (Anthony Hopkins) who trades his wealth for
his life, ``The Tenth Man'' is tedious and overwrought, as
exemplified by the cloyingly romantic music overwhelming almost
every scene. It's composed by Lee Holdridge, who wrote the theme for
``Beauty and the Beast.''
   Hopkins can be effecting in the right role, but here he is merely
irritating, employing varying degrees of one emotion: dumbfounded.
   There is some hope when the flamboyant Derek Jacobi bursts on the
scene late in the drama to add the final plot twist, but by then
it's snoozing time.
   The movie was shot on location in France. Why? Most of the scenes
are interiors.
   Hopkins plays Jean Louis Chavel, a successful attorney with an
estate outside Paris who is accidentally picked up in a Nazi sweep
of innocent citizenry. In prison, he is selected as one of a random
few _ every 10th prisoner _ to be executed in retribution against
the Resistance.
   Chavel tries to buy his life, offering everything he has to any
man who will take his place in front of the firing squad. Michel
Mangeot (Timothy Watkins), a young man with a bad cough, takes him
up on the deal, so he can leave Chavel's wealth to his mother and
sister.
   Three years later, France is liberated, and Chavel returns to his
mansion, now in disrepair, where Michel's mother and sister are
living. He conceals his identity and Michel's attractive sister,
Therese (Kristin Scott Thomas), hires him as a handyman. She spends
most of her spare time imagining how she will kill the hated Chavel.
   The plot begins to thicken when Jacobi arrives, claiming to be
Chavel, but he's mostly lost in the headlong rush to the
inexplicable conclusion.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Hal (Dabney Coleman) and Julia (Jane Curtin) have a fabulous
life. They live in a beach house, eat exotic foods, drive
his-and-hers sports cars and vacation in romantic, out-of-the-way
places.
   Hal is 57 and has two grown children from a previous marriage. He
is perfectly satisfied to dote part-time on his two grandchildren.
Julia is 39, a career woman who displays little more than mild
anxiety when little ones are around _ until her best friend has a
baby.
   ``Maybe Baby,'' previously titled ``Sooner or Later,'' is a cute,
sophisticated story of a spoiled woman who thinks having a baby will
be as easy as having an Alfa Romeo. It airs Monday on NBC.
   Once Julia convinces herself she needs a baby, she has to
convince Hal, who doesn't want ``one of those noisy, messy little
things'' or to be the only 70-year-old on the sidelines at the
Little League games. But he goes along after his secretary (Florence
Stanley) convinces him a 39-year-old woman who's spent 20 years on
birth control pills is unlikely to get pregnant.
   How does she know about the pills? ``Put any two women in the
same room and they'll talk about birth control,'' she says. ``It's
like men and sports, only infinitely more interesting.''
   Except for a silly scene when Julia finds Hal dining with another
woman, ``Maybe Baby'' is funny and plausible. Coleman and Curtin
make a nice team, and the supporting roles are nicely played. Julia
Duffy (``Newhart'') plays Hal's daughter.
   Janet Kovalcik, who wrote the screenplay, has the confidence to
put this line in Florence Stanley's mouth: ``This is why I don't
watch soap operas. Because the plots are stupid and boring and the
people act like jerks.''
   But of course that's exactly why we watch soap operas, and movies
like ``Maybe Baby.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   CRISIS IN THREE EPISODES _ Steven suffers a heart attack and
undergoes surgery in a three-part episode of what usually is NBC's
comedy ``Family Ties'' that begins this Sunday. Anesthesia will
allow Steven (Michael Gross) to engage in a flashback to his college
days with wife, Elyse (Meredith Baxter Birney). Christina Pickles,
formerly of ``St. Elsewhere,'' guest stars. ...
   THEIR DINNER WITH KATE AND ALLIE _ Susan Saint James and Jane
Curtin (``Kate & Allie) will guest-star as unsuspecting restaurant
patrons caught in a battle of the chefs at ``Tattinger's,'' Dec. 14
on NBC. ...
   EMILY, MEET MOLLY. REALITY, MEET FICTION _ Lifetime Cablevision
Network, which picked up ``The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd'' after
NBC canceled the series, has signed Shelley Duvall's production
company to create a new show, ``Emily Undercover,'' as a companion
for ``Molly'' next April. Emily, uncast, is a former actress who
goes to work for a New York private investigation agency. The
premise sounds a lot like the real life of Rebeca Arthur of ABC's
``Perfect Strangers,'' who took a job as a private investigator in
New York while struggling to make it as an actress.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, Dec. 2</NOTE>
