<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UtilityMerger     12-01 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Utility Merger,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>San Diego Utility Accepts SoCal Edison's $2.5 Billion Buyout Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK EVJE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parent of Southern California Edison Co.
entered ``the crown jewel of service territories'' when San Diego
Gas & Electric Co. accepted its $2.5 billion buyout bid, utility
officials said.
   The stock-swap deal approved Wednesday by SDG&E directors creates
the nation's biggest public utility, and will result in lower
electricity rates for customers and higher dividends for
shareholders, Edison chairman and chief executive Howard Allen said.
   ``We have concluded that there will be savings passed on to
customers, and that this combined institution will be stronger and
better able to serve customer needs,'' said Allen, also chief
executive of Edison's unregulated parent, SCEcorp, which serves most
of Southern California.
   ``We wouldn't be going into this if we didn't think we could
produce better consumer value than each (utility) could on its own.''
   Customers of the surviving utility also will benefit from its
increased financial strength through greater market competitiveness
and more efficient energy transmission, SDG&E chairman and chief
executive Tom Page said.
   SCEcorp also has pledged to file a request for a 10 percent rate
reduction for San Diego customers with the state Public Utilities
Commission within six months of the deal's completion.
   The deal is expected to be consummated in late 1989 or early 1990
pending stockholder ratification and approval by federal and state
regulators, principally the California Public Utilities Commission.
   SCEcorp will trade 1.3 shares of its common stock for each of the
55.8 million shares of SDG&E common stock. That works out to about
$2.4 billion when calculated on SCEcorp's closing price Wednesday of
$33 a share in composite trading.
   Additionally, swaps of several classes of preferred stock would
add about $155 million to the deal, according to Rosemead-based
SCEcorp's reckoning.
   ``What we're banking on ... is that our stock will go up in value
and the dilution of Edison shareholders' (ownership in the merged
company) will be made back by a higher market price-earnings ratio
over time,'' Allen said during a news conference at SDG&E's main
building in downtown San Diego. .
   The deal would boost Edison past San Francisco's Pacific Gas &
Electric Co. as the nation's biggest public utility. It would have
4.8 million customers, a service area of 54,000 square miles
stretching from San Luis Obispo to the Mexican border, and with
$17.7 billion in assets.
   Page will be named vice president of a new San Diego division of
SCEcorp, and he and three others from the San Diego utility will
join the board of SCEcorp.
   Analysts called the offer a good one for stockholders and
customers of the San Diego company, as SCEcorp promises the deal
will boost stock dividends by 24 percent and earnings per share by
29 percent.
   Ed Tirello, who tracks the utility business for Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. in New York, estimated the merged company would save
$100 million a year in operating and maintenance costs by cutting
duplication.
   Additionally, because the combined company would use Edison's
excess capacity SDG&E would not have to undertake some $350 million
in construction to meet growing demand, he said.
   Dan Rudakas, a utility analyst with Duff & Phelps Inc. in
Chicago, cautioned that the benefit to SCEcorp stockholders was
uncertain until state regulators decide how to apportion any cost
savings due to operating efficiency. But San Diego consumers would
be almost certain winners, he said.
   SCEcorp made its first unsolicited bid for the San Diego utility
July 26. The price, raised twice since then, was 1.15 shares of
SCEcorp common stock for each share of SDG&E.
   The San Diego company initially refused to negotiate with its
huge suitor, preferring to pursue a previously announced merger with
Tucson (Ariz.) Electric Power Co. SDG&E later abandoned that merger
plan, however.
</TEXT>
