<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     12-01 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in early European trading today as
the market waited for Friday's release of U.S. unemployment figures
for November, foreign currency dealers said. Gold prices rose.
   November's unemployment rate is expected to remain at about 5.3
percent.
   ``If it's a slightly better number, the dollar may rise a bit,''
said a dealer at a large Frankfurt bank.
   But a dealer in Milan, Italy, said worse-than-expected figures
would hurt the dollar and would indicate that the U.S. economy is
overheating and that the threat of inflation was strong.
   Dealers said the dollar's weakness is partly due to the strength
of the British pound. One pound cost $1.8542 in London at
midmorning, more expensive for buyers than late Wednesday's $1.8480.
   ``The (British) government's high-interest-rate policy is
clear,'' the Frankfurt dealer said. ``Demand for the pound is
there.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.28 yen to a closing 121.57. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 121.65 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.7318 West German marks, down from 1.7375; 1.4513
Swiss francs, down from 1.4548; 5.9135 French francs, down from
5.9327; 1.9552 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9590; 1,278.65 Italian
lire, down from 1,284.97; 1.1857 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1872.
   Gold prices rose on the heels of higher platinum prices, bullion
dealers said.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $424.50 a troy ounce, up
from $423.25 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $425.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $425.00, up from $422.30 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold spurted ahead $2.90 to close at a bid
$425.52.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.18 a troy ounce,
up from Wednesday's $6.14.
</TEXT>
