<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 0752EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     12-01 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar and stock prices closed lower in cautious
trading in Tokyo today as participants awaited the release of U.S.
unemployment figures, traders said.
   The dollar opened lower at 121.28 yen, then rose slightly during
the day. It finished trading at 121.57 yen, down 0.28 yen from
Wednesday's closing, after ranging between 121.28 and 121.60 yen.
   The U.S. currency's decline in Tokyo followed an overnight drop
in New York, where the Bank of England sold dollars in an attempt to
keep the British pound from rising against the West German mark,
dealers said.
   Many market players in Tokyo remained on the sidelines ahead of
the release of the U.S. jobless rate for November, scheduled for
Friday, dealers said.
   The dollar rose in the afternoon after some trading companies
bought the currency, but was not affected strongly, a trader with
Mitsui Bank said.
   ``Dollar-yen trading is likely to remain inactive in Tokyo until
at least Monday,'' she said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
Monday is the first day that Tokyo traders will be able to respond
to the U.S. jobless rate.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
fell back 37.44 points or 0.13 percent to 29,541.46. The index
gained 94.26 points during the morning to end the early session at a
record-high 29,673.16, but reversed direction in the afternoon.
   On Wednesday, the Nikkei index closed at a record high of
29,578.90 after gaining 260.60 points.
   ``Share prices began to fall as market players became
increasingly cautious and directionless before the release of the
U.S. jobless rate,'' said an analyst with Nomura Securities,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said the most immediate concern of investors was whether the
United States would raise interest rates.
   ``Today's directionless market was easily influenced whenever
participants spread rumors, including one that U.S. interest rates
were likely to rise,'' he added.
   Volume on the market's first section was an estimated 1.5 billion
shares.
</TEXT>
