<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NortheastPipeline     12-01 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northeast Pipeline,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dual Pipeline Plan For Pumping Canadian Natural Gas To Northeast
Is
OK'd</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal official says he approved plans to
build two major pipelines to deliver Canadian natural gas throughout
the Northeast because of ``an urgent and necessary requirement'' for
the additional energy supplies.
   Curtis L. Wagner Jr., chief administrative law judge at the
Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, also said Wednesday that
timing was critical because the Canadian gas would be lost to other
markets if the projects were delayed.
   The plan calls for the construction of a 369.4-mile pipeline from
the U.S.-Canadian border near Iroquois, Ontario, through New York
and Connecticut, across the Long Island Sound and ending at South
Commack, Long Island, where it will be connected with existing
pipeline from the Long Island Lighting Co.
   Another section of the Iroquois project would be a 53.2-mile
pipeline loop in New York and Massachusetts and a third section near
Carthage, New York.
   The second project, the Champlain pipeline, would be a 339.3-mile
stretch from the Canadian border near Philipsburg, Quebec, through
Vermont, New Hampshire and Massachusetts, ending near West Medway,
Mass., outside Boston.
   ``The settlement ... is clearly in the public interest,'' he
wrote ``There is an urgent and necessary requirement for additional
supplies of natural gas to meet the needs of individuals and the
economy in the New England, New York and New Jersey areas at the
earliest possible date.''
   Wagner recommended the full commission approve the plan, which
involves eight companies. Spokeswoman Tamara Young-Allen said the
earliest vote would be Jan. 11.
   Eight companies are involved in the projects. They are Iroquois
Gas Transmission System, Champlain Pipeline Co., CNG Transmission
Corp., TransCanada Pipelines Ltd., Algonquin Gas Transmission Co.,
Tennessee Gas Pipeline Co., ANR Pipeline Co. and Texas Eastern
Transmission Corp.
   A Connecticut environmental group, the Housatonic Valley
Association, opposed the plan, as did the New England Fuel Institute
and Empoire State Petroleum Association.
   Wagner also approved a third project, a 90.5 mile stretch of new
pipeline from existing lines near Muncie, Ind., and Lebanon, Ohio.
</TEXT>
