<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 0809EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MITSuperconductor     12-01 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-MIT Superconductor,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MIT Moves To Commercialize New Superconductors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Massachusetts Institute of Technology has won
an early heat in a race to commercialize new superconductors that
many scientists believe will eventually be used to probe the brain,
detect submarines and help find oil.
   But researchers at other university and corporate laboratories
said Wednesday the race, which could bring huge financial gains to
the winner, is far from over.
   MIT received a ``notice of allowability'' from the U.S. Patent
Office last week for the first major U.S. patent in the field of
high-temperature superconductors, materials that conduct electricity
with virtually no resistance.
   MIT officials said the notice is a strong signal that the
institute will receive a patent within a few months for a process
developed by two professors, Gregory J. Yurek and John B. Vander
Sande, to make ceramic superconductors more flexible by mixing them
with metals like gold or silver.
   Researchers around the world have been competing to develop and
apply ceramic superconductors since they were discovered in January
1986 by two scientists at an International Business Machines Inc.
laboratory in Switzerland.
   The IBM scientists, Georg Bednorz and Alexander Mueller, won the
1987 Nobel Prize in physics for their discovery that certain
ceramics become superconductive when cooled with liquid nitrogen to
about 300 degrees below zero Fahrenheit.
   Previous superconductors had operated only at minus 418 degrees
or below, requiring cooling in liquid helium, which is more costly
and difficult to maintain than liquid nitrogen.
   One problem with the ceramics is that they are brittle. MIT says
its process greatly increases flexibility, allowing the materials to
be made into wire and wound into coils for small motors.
   Several other applications for patents related to ceramic
superconductors are pending, but none have been granted, said Oscar
Maston, a spokesman for the Patent Office in Arlington, Va.
   Bell Labs and other companies and universities are working on
processes similar to MIT's, said Paul A. Fleury, director of
physical research at Bell Labs in Murray Hill, N.J.
   ``The MIT technique is significant in that it's one of the
earliest,'' Fleury said, ``but it's still too early to tell which,
if any, of these processes is going to result in a commercial
application.''
   William J. Gallagher, manager of exploratory cryogenics at IBM's
research center in Yorktown Heights, N.Y., said researchers can
easily foresee using the new superconductors in devices to measure
brainwaves, locate submarines deep under the sea, detect oil
reserves and process radar signals.
   But those uses are probably at least five years away, Gallagher
said, and many problems with superconductors will have to be solved
first. Among them, he said, are limits to the amount of current the
new materials can carry.
   MIT said it has licensed exclusive rights to its patent to a
company founded last year by four of the institute's faculty
members. MIT officials refused to disclose the terms of the
licensing agreement with the company, American Superconductor Corp.
of Cambridge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881201-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 0842EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-China-FuturesMarket     12-01 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-China-Futures Market,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Delays Opening of First Futures Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China will delay for a year the opening of the
socialist world's first futures market, an official daily said
Thursday.
   The China Daily said a futures market will be launched on a trial
basis in central China's Henan province by the end of next year.
   In May, plans were announced to open a market in the southern
city of Canton by the end of 1988, but the daily said an
investigative group under the State Council, China's cabinet,
decided to put off the starting date.
   Chang Qing, senior researcher in the group, said China wanted
more time to learn from experts in Hong Kong and become better
prepared.
   A futures market, formerly regarded in China as a form of
capitalist speculation, allows traders and producers of raw
materials to negotiate a set price for what they think a commodity
will be worth at a future date.
   The producer is guaranteed that price regardless of subsequent
fluctuations in the market.
   The need for futures markets has arisen with the decontrol of
prices for many commodities that has resulted in sharp price
fluctuations. Produce markets in particular have been plagued by
gluts and shortages caused by farmers' inability to forecast the
market.
   The daily said the market in Henan, a major agriculture center,
will deal in wheat and other grains. About 150 people, mostly from
Henan, recently gathered in Beijing for a 10-day training course in
futures markets, it said.
   The Henan market will only open prices to trading twice a week
because of China's backward telecommunications system, it said.
   If it is a success, markets will be opened in Jilin in the
northeast for corn, Sichuan in the west for pigs and Guangdong and
Hebei in the south and north for raw materials.
   It said the investigative group is studying whether foreign
businessmen will be allowed to participate in China's futures
markets. Initially, only Chinese will be able to take part, it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
