<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Westinghouse-Philippines     12-01 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Westinghouse-Philippines,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philippine Lawsuit A Smokescreen, Westinghouse Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Electric Corp. says safety
concerns raised by the Aquino government over a nuclear reactor in
the Philippines amount to a smokescreen to disguise political
opposition to the project begun by former President Ferdinand Marcos.
   Westinghouse officials said Wednesday they expected the lawsuit
over the $2.3 billion plant, for which the company has been paid
$680 million as prime contractor. Westinghouse claims it is due
another $20 million to $30 million.
   The government of President Corazon Aquino announced early today
that it had sued Westinghouse in U.S. District Court in Newark,
N.J., to cancel the contract for the 620-megawatt plant, which was
finished three years ago but was never started.
   Westinghouse said today it petitioned the International Chamber
of Commerce in Paris to arbitrate the dispute as provided by the
1976 contract.
   Nathaniel D. Woodson, general manager of the Westinghouse nuclear
fuels unit, and Westinghouse Deputy General Counsel Louis J.
Briskman said Philippine officials have acknowledged during private
talks that no matter how safe the plant is, they don't intend to
allow nuclear power production in the country.
   ``It has nothing to do with safety,'' Woodson said.
   The government says the plant, 60 miles northwest of Manila in
Bataan province, is unsafe partly because of its design and its
location on an earthquake fault and near a volcano.
   The reactor's opponents also allege bribes were paid over the
awarding of the prime contract for the plant.
   ``What we're finding here are the results of a political policy
that came to life when they were running for office,'' Woodson said.
``They now feel they have a political albatross around their neck
and they're trying to blame us.''
   President Aquino's legal adviser, Adolfo Azcuna, said in late
October that the suit was ready and likely would be filed within a
month in the United States. In addition, a standstill agreement
barring either the government or the company from taking legal
action expired today.
   Westinghouse officials said the 10-year-old controversy is an
unfounded attack on the company's international standing as a
designer and builder of nuclear power plants.
   ``All over the world we have built plants, and we haven't had
this problem. If they don't want to operate this plant, that's their
decision, but don't make Westinghouse a scapegoat,'' he said.
``Westinghouse will not be a scapegoat.''
   The company cites investigations by the U.S. Justice Department
and the Securities and Exchange Commission, which produced no
evidence to warrant charges.
   A safety study commissioned by the Aquino government _ a draft of
which was published by a trade journal _ concluded the plant is
safe, Westinghouse said. But the government says the final report
concludes otherwise, although Philippine officials have refused to
release the document.
   Communist rebels have bombed the transmission towers leading from
the plant, and people have cut and sold the copper lines as scrap,
Woodson said. The plant's corps of operators has largely disbanded,
and Westinghouse has only a handful of employees still in the
Philippines, he said.
   Furthermore, the cost of the plant continues rising, Westinghouse
said. Interest on the loans the Philippine government took to build
the plant cost an estimated $300,000 per day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881201-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1016EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Popeyes-Church's     12-01 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Popeyes-Church's,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Popeyes Extends Deadline; Says It Has Been Offered 40.6 Percent Of
Stock</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Popeyes, without apostrophe, is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Popeyes Famous Fried Chicken and Biscuits
owner Al Copeland today extended the deadline on his offer for
Church's Fried Chicken Inc., saying he did so to get time to put out
a court-ordered statement.
   He also said that, since announcing his buyout plans, he has been
offered 14.6 million _ about 40.6 percent _ of the 35.97 million
shares outstanding.
   He already owned 3.2 percent of the San Antonio-based company's
stock, so the stock tendered by Nov. 30 would give him nearly 44
percent, said Rob Shepardson, a spokesman for Copeland.
   The previous deadline for the takeover bid had been midnight EST
on Wednesday, but A. Copeland Enterprises Inc. said in a prepared
statement today that it had put off the deadline until midnight EST
on Dec. 16.
   U.S. District Judge Charles Schwartz has forbidden Popeyes to buy
Church's stock until 10 working days after it reveals information on
which its buyout offer is made. He also ordered Popeyes on Tuesday
to stop using, at least for now, any confidential Church's
information it may have.
   Church's claims its former chief financial officer took
confidential files with him when he went to work for Copeland.
   Church's announced Tuesday that it was starting preliminary
negotiations with third parties that it did not identify.
   ``We do not understand how you can adequately explore
alternatives available to Church's without allowing us to
participate in such discussions on equal footing with all other
interested parties,'' Copeland wrote the board late Wednesday.
   The letter said that so far, Church's has said it will talk to
Copeland and let him see the documents he wants only if he signs a
standstill agreement. Such agreements bind the potential buyer to a
promise not to pursue the takeover attempt for a specific period,
usually years.
   Such an agreement is unnecessary, Copeland's letter said, because
he is willing to sign a confidentiality agreement requiring that any
further purchases of stock be made pursuant to the tender offer.
   The letter also said Copeland plans to go forward with his offer
after complying with Schwartz' order.
   And he repeated that he is willing to raise his $290 million,
$8-per-share bid, if the nonpublic information he wants justifies a
higher price.
</TEXT>
