<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Pepperell-Farley     12-01 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pepperell-Farley,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farley Extends Offer For West Point-Pepperell Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago-based Farley Inc. today extended
for a second time its $1.4 billion tender offer for Georgia-based
West Point-Pepperell Inc.
   The offer was to expire at midnight Wednesday, but a Farley
statement said it was being extended by one week to midnight EST
Dec. 7.
   The company also announced that a preliminary count showed about
11.4 million shares of Pepperell's common stock had been tendered by
stockholders as of the close of business Wednesday. With the shares
Farley already owns, that would give the company about 49 percent of
Pepperell's stock, it said.
   Farley officials have declined to say how much of the Georgia
company's stock they hope to acquire.
   ``We are pleased with the results of the tender offer to date,
and believe they reflect the shareholders' increasing interest and
confidence in our proposal to acquire West Point-Pepperell,'' said
William Farley, chairman of the Chicago-based company. ``We are
confident our offer will succeed, despite the efforts by Pepperell
management to impede it.''
   Pepperell's stock was up $1.12{ a share to $40 on the New York
Stock Exchange Wednesday.
   Farley, the Chicago-based maker of Fruit of the Loom underwear,
originally set Nov. 21 as the deadline for its $48-per-share offer
for the textile company based in West Point. The deadline was
extended to midnight Wednesday as Farley attempted to overcome some
of the anti-takeover obstacles set up by Pepperell.
   Pepperell and Farley have done battle in court over Pepperell's
``poison pill'' shareholder rights plan, designed to thwart hostile
takeovers.
   Last week, the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals denied
Pepperell's motion to reinstate certain key provisions of the plan,
which were thrown out earlier by a U.S. District Court judge.
   The appeals court scheduled a hearing the week of Jan. 9 to
determine the final fate of the ``poison pill'' plan. Farley's offer
is contingent on getting the plan overturned.
   Also being argued in the courts is the constitutionality of
Georgia's anti-takeover statute, which Farley is seeking to
overturn. That issue is now in the hands of U.S. District Judge G.
Ernest Tidwell of Atlanta, who has not set a hearing date. If the
law is upheld, Farley's bid cannot go through.
</TEXT>
