<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BankerSentenced     12-01 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Banker Sentenced,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Bank President Gets Additional Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Connecticut bank president who earlier was
sentenced to four months in prison for insider trading drew a longer
sentence for trying to block an investigation into his activities.
   Robert C. DiGennaro, who was chief executive of Suffield
Financial Corp., was sentenced to a year and a day in prison
Wednesday in U.S. District Court in Boston. The two sentences will
run concurrently.
   Prosecutors say that while his bank was negotiating a 1986 merger
with Coastal Savings Bank of Portland, Maine, DiGennaro tipped off a
number of associates about the pending transaction.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Gary Crossen said that when the
Securities and Exchange Commission looked into the matter,
``DiGennaro lied, convinced others to lie and destroyed documents
that had been subpoenaed.''
   DiGennaro's associates pleaded guilty but were not sent to jail.
   Wednesday, the SEC filed civil complaints in court against two
people who profited from DiGennaro's information and both agreed to
pay fines.
   Arthur Silverman, a former Hartford stockbroker, agreed to pay
back profits of $9,100 and a penalty of $18,000. He was barred from
the securities industry for six month. In June, he agreed to pay a
fine of $10,000 for insider trading.
   Joel Weisman, a Hartford business, agreed to pay back profits of
$33,000. He was not fined because he cooperated with the
government's investigation.
</TEXT>
