<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened
modestly lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade with most of the
selling due to technical factors, analysts said.
   ``The market seems to be pretty fickle right now,'' said Steve
Freed, a grain market analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in
Chicago.
   But some observers also linked the decline to recurring rumors
that the Agriculture Department may delay offering subsidized U.S.
wheat to the Soviet Union.
   The Soviets have agreed to purchase 9 million metric tons of U.S.
grain, including 4 million tons of wheat, this year and next year
under an agreement signed Monday.
   The Soviets have purchased no wheat for delivery in the current
marketing year and the USDA has not offered them wheat since the
signing of the grain deal, as the agency had been expected to do.
   In early trading, wheat was 2 cents to 5 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.20 a bushel; corn was 1 cent
lower to \ cent higher with December at $2.60\ a bushel; oats were
1{ cents to 2} cents lower with December at $1.94 a bushel; soybeans
were 1 cent to 5\ cents lower with January at $7.60 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent lower to .20 cent higher with December
at 72.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .28 cent
higher with January at 82.70 cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent
lower to .35 cent higher with December at 40.02 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .22 cent lower to .40 cent higher with
February at 44.75 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures closed mostly lower on Wednesday while pork
futures were mostly higher.
</TEXT>
