<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     12-01 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0481</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market drifted mostly lower today as
investors awaited the November employment statistics due to be
released Friday for an indication of the strength of the economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, up 12.98 points on
Wednesday and nearly 40 points over the past three sessions, was
down 4.27 at 2,110.24 at noon on Wall Street.
   Declining issues outpaced gainers by a margin of 7 to 5 among
issues listed on the New York Stock Exchange, with 528 up, 752 down
and 504 unchanged.
   Big Board volume amounted to 59.89 million shares at noontime
compared with 60.78 million shares at the same point in Wednesday's
session.
   The market rallied in the previous session on indications that
the economy may be growing at a more moderate pace.
   That presumably would mean that the Federal Reserve policymakers
who meet in mid-December may not feel compelled to encourage higher
interest rates to restrain growth and inflation.
   But the market was looking toward Friday's report on November
employment for confirmation of economic growth trends.
   Charles Jensen, an analyst for MKI Securities Corp., said today's
decline in prices reflected ``some precautionary selling on the part
of traders who don't want to be caught long if the employment
figures are negative.''
   He said the consensus estimate calls for payroll growth of about
250,000 and said that a number above 275,000 ``would be
disappointing'' because it would increase pressure on the central
bank to encourage higher interest rates.
   Rising interest rates hurt stock prices because they make yields
on fixed-income investments such as Treasury bills relatively more
attractive compared with the riskier returns on stocks.
   In a new report today, the government said its chief forecasting
gauge of future economic activity edged up a sluggish 0.1 percent in
October after falling by a revised 0.3 percent in September.
   RJR Nabisco was off 1\ at 91} and was the most active stock this
morning on the NYSE. The company said late Wednesday it had accepted
an offer of $109 a share in cash and securities from buyout
specialist Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co., spurning a competing offer
from a management group.
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co. was also active. It was down [
at 29} after saying it will take a $6.7 billion charge against its
fourth-quarter earnings to cover expenses related to getting rid of
outdated telephone equipment.
   General Cinema was up 1} at 23|. It announced it had tentatively
agreed to sell its soft-drink bottling business to Pepsico Inc. for
$1.5 billion. Pepsico was down 1~ at 39.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed stocks was off 0.34
at 153.56. On the American Stock Exchange, the market value index
was up 0.20 at 294.56.
</TEXT>
