<2ND_LINE>PM-Fort Howard Suit,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fort Howard Settles Shareholder Suits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fort Howard Corp. has agreed to pay nearly
$15 million to settle two lawsuits filed by shareholders against the
$3.6 billion management buyout of the company, according to
documents filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Plaintiffs in both lawsuits objected to the $53-a-share bid,
saying the company was worth more money.
   Fort Howard management, backed by Morgan Stanley Group Inc., last
summer submitted the only formal bid to purchase Fort Howard, a
papermaking company that posted sales of $1.4 billion during the
first nine months of this year.
   In one settlement, Fort Howard agreed to pay $13.4 million during
a one-year period to shareholders who filed six separate suits later
combined into one action.
   The suits were filed in the Court of Chancery in New Castle
County, Dela.
   In the second case, filed in Federal Court in New York City, Fort
Howard agreed to make one payment of $1.5 million to the securities
firm of Kaufman, Alsberg & Co. Inc., New York City, according to the
documents filed with the SEC by Fort Howard.
   The settlements will not be finalized until the courts hearing
the cases approve them, the SEC statements said.
   Fees and expenses incurred by the plaintiffs attorneys will be
paid out of the settlements, the documents stated.
   A Fort Howard spokesman said he could not comment on whether the
lawsuits could have blocked the management-led takeover from being
completed Oct. 24.
</TEXT>
