<1ST_LINE>u f PM-NursingHomes 1stLd-Writethru f0042 12-01 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nursing Homes, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0042,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nursing Homes Rated in Consumer Guide</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout, updating with release and Roper quotes; Also
moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 40 percent of nursing homes failed to
meet sanitary standards for food and nearly 30 percent failed to
meet standards for maintaining residents' personal cleanliness,
according to the federal government's first consumer guide to
nursing homes, released today.
   The survey also found that more than one-fourth of the nursing
homes do not administer drugs properly.
   However, Dr. William L. Roper, chief of the Health Care Financing
Administration that compiled and released the statistics, cautioned
against reading more into the figures than is warranted.
   ``This is not the ultimate report card for nursing homes around
the country,'' Roper told reporters.
   He said the ``met-unmet'' criteria for each of the 32 categories
included in the state-by-state reports contains no measure of
severity and represented a one-time ``snapshot'' of conditions at
the nursing home's most recent unannounced inspection. To some
degree, he said, it relied on the subjective judgment of the
inspector.
   At the same time, Roper defended release of the report against
industry criticism that it would mislead consumers.
   One complaint was, for example, that a nursing home might be
given an ``unmet'' mark on proper administration of medication if
one patient was five minutes late getting his or her medicine.
   ``If one person was five minutes late, I'm sure they would not
have been dinged in the survey,'' Roper said. ``What we're looking
at, what the surveyors look at is the pattern of care over time.
   ``We are not in the business of making arbitrary, bureaucratic
judgments. We are trying to evaluate what is really happening to
people in that nursing home.''
   He added:
   ``What we are looking for ... is not nursing home providers that
barely scrape by. We're looking for people who are good providers,
consistently, over time, 365 days a year. And I have to believe that
if that's where a nursing home operator has his or her nursing home,
they are not going to be worried about being dinged on some trivial
point.''
   The 75-volume guide shows how each of the 15,000 nursing homes
fared on 32 health, safety and care standards based on periodic
inspections by state agencies. About 2,400 of the 15,000 received
passing marks in all 32 categories.
   The report had been scheduled for release next week, but copies
were distributed earlier to various state and local agencies, as
well as to consumer groups. When the embargo was broken, HCFA issued
the massive guide immediately.
   Roper said all the information had been available at the state
level if people had ``been willing to work hard enough to get it''
but that HCFA felt it was worthwile to compile it in a single report.
   According to the survey, nearly 43 percent of the homes failed to
meet sanitary standards for food. Almost 30 percent failed to meet
standards for maintaining residents' personal cleanliness and 29
percent failed to administer drugs according to doctors' orders.
   However, the report also said that only a small percentage of the
nursing homes failed to meet standards in many other categories.
Overall among skilled homes, the failure rate exceeded 15 percent in
only 10 categories.
   Paul Willging, executive vice president of the American Health
Care Association, which represents more than 9,000 nursing homes,
said the report ``is misleading _ it is going to confuse the
public'' by making it appear conditions are worse than they are. He
said that something like a cracked egg in a refrigerator could lead
to a nursing home failing to meet a care standard.
   But Elma Holder, executive director of the National Citizens'
Coalition on Nursing Home Reform, said: ``We think the national
statistics are misleading. Conditions are worse.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
