<DOCNO> AP881201-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1334EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-StatelyHomes Bjt   12-01 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stately Homes, Bjt,0742</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government to Stately Home Owners: `There's No Free Lunch'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British upper-classes got a tart reminder the
other day of how far they've fallen on the ladder of national
priorities.
   It came in a speech by Nicholas Ridley, environment secretary in
the Conservative government, and concerned one of the very pillars
of British aristocracy _ the stately home.
   Addressing the Historic Houses Association on Nov. 22, Ridley
delivered a blunt message on these lines: if you can't afford the
upkeep of your stately home, don't ask the government for help; sell
it to the ``nouveaux riches.''
   The speech, which brought ripples of reproach from the landed
gentry, was another sign of how the old Britain has been transformed.
   The Conservative Party, once topheavy with squires and knights of
the shires, today is peopled with the likes of Ridley, a civil
engineer, and Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, the daughter of a
chemist and a grocer.
   Things have changed drastically since 1938, when Noel Coward
wrote:
   ``The stately homes of England
   How beautiful they stand
   To prove the upper classes
   Still have the upper hand.''
   The post-World War II Labor Party government, intent on fostering
socialist egalitarianism, imposed massive taxation on inherited
wealth, forcing many owners to turn their stately homes over to the
public.
   The homes became museums, while the owners moved into small
corners of the estate. By one estimate, the number of major stately
homes occupied by one family shrank from 10,000 to 2,000.
   Ridley recalled the days when governments, to preserve historic
mansions for the nation, had to pay ``simply to keep roofs on and
walls standing.''
   But after a decade of Thatcherism, he said, ``Things have
changed. Everywhere we see the new prosperity. Millionaires abound
and there are many more budding ones called yuppies.''
   Yet he was still hearing ``cries from some quarters for more,
rather than less state help.'' That, he said, was out.
   ``There have to be some opportunities for today's nouveaux
riches, so I am not impressed by the case of the anciens pauvres,''
he said.
   Nor was he impressed by noble lineages. ``Many families who pride
themselves on having always lived in a house in fact married into
it, bought it or stole it at some point in their murky history, when
they were robber barons, property speculators or simply won the
pools.''
   Ridley's blunt talk drew some testy responses.
   Right-wing commentator Roger Scruton suggested that as the second
son of noble family, Ridley, 59, suffered from the British
affliction of ``younger son syndrome'' _ a resentment born of
primogeniture, whereby the first-born inherits the title and estate,
while the others must fend for themselves.
   In the conservative Daily Telegraph, James Lees-Milne called
Ridley's remarks ``totally unwarranted,'' arguing that stately
families were doing a service to conservation by staying on their
land.
   Hugh Montgomery-Massingberd, author of a guide to British country
houses, says the problem is not with the larger homes, which can
easily be turned into money-spinning public attractions, but the
smaller homes, whose owners are hard-pressed to survive.
   ``The families that are still in their homes have a lot of
influence and do a lot of good,'' he said in an interview.
   They feel greater responsibility for their tenant farmers and
hold unpaid public posts like high sheriff and justice of the peace.
``I wonder whether the nouveaux riches, who use these places as
weekend pads to impress their friends, would be willing to take on
these responsibilities,'' he said.
   Also, he said, the attraction of country homes is their valuable
furnishings, historic collections that risk being broken up and sold
off by new owners lacking a sense of heritage.
   Terence Empson, director of the Historic Houses Association where
Ridley spoke, said homeowners had already proved ingenious at
fending for themselves, turning their estates into conference
centers, safari parks and even ``war games parks'' for adventurous
executives.
   Ridley's exhortations might apply to smaller homes within
commuting distance of the cities, he said in an interview. ``But if
you have a historic home on a palatial scale deep in the
countryside, I don't see millionaire yuppies queuing round the block
to buy it. The market just isn't there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
