<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were holding at slightly lower
levels this afternoon as investors awaited new evidence on the
strength of the economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, up 12.98 points on
Wednesday and nearly 40 points over the past three sessions, was
down 7.82 at 2,106.69 with two hours left in the session.
   Declining issues outpaced gainers by a margin of 4 to 3 among
issues listed on the New York Stock Exchange, with 577 up, 811 down
and 499 unchanged.
   Big Board volume amounted to 88.82 million shares at 2 p.m. on
Wall Street compared with 104.16 million shares at the same point in
Wednesday's session.
   The market rallied in the previous session on indications that
the economy may be growing at a more moderate pace.
   That presumably would mean that the Federal Reserve policymakers
who meet in mid-December may not feel compelled to encourage higher
interest rates to restrain growth and inflation.
   But the market was looking toward Friday's report on November
employment for confirmation of economic growth trends.
   Charles Jensen, an analyst for MKI Securities Corp., said today's
decline in prices reflected ``some precautionary selling on the part
of traders who don't want to be caught long if the employment
figures are negative.''
   In a new report today, the government said its chief forecasting
gauge of future economic activity edged up a sluggish 0.1 percent in
October after falling by a revised 0.3 percent in September.
   RJR Nabisco was off } at 92\ and was the most active stock on the
NYSE. The company said late Wednesday it had accepted an offer of
$109 a share in cash and securities from buyout specialist Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts & Co., spurning a competing offer from a management
group.
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co. was also active. It was down \
at 29| after saying it will take a $6.7 billion charge against its
fourth-quarter earnings to cover expenses related to getting rid of
outdated telephone equipment.
   General Cinema was up 1~ at 23}. It announced it had tentatively
agreed to sell its soft-drink bottling business to Pepsico Inc. for
$1.5 billion. Pepsico was down 1~ at 39.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed stocks was off 0.54
at 153.36. On the American Stock Exchange, the market value index
was off 0.15 at 294.21.
