<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1509EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-RJRNabisco-Local Bjt   12-01 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-RJR Nabisco-Local, Bjt,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winston-Salem Merchants See Dollar Signs In RJR Nabisco Deal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-RJR Nabisco, Bjt</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ When $2 billion from the buyout of RJR
Nabisco Inc. hits Winston-Salem, the people who sell jewels, cars
and houses for a living hope to be busy.
   Analysts estimate that 9,000 people in Winston-Salem, former
headquarters of the food and tobacco giant, own $1 billion worth of
stock in the company, and that local trusts, foundations and
retirement plans own another $1 billion.
   The estimates are based on a stock price of $100 a share. The
company was auctioned off Wednesday to buyout specialists Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts & Co. in a deal worth about $109 a share to
stockholders in cash and securities.
   When local shareholders receive their share of the proceeds, it
could make for a very merry Christmas for area merchants.
   Thomas Winstead, the general manager of Hanes Mall, said that
unlike retailers in other parts of the country, merchants at his
mall have seen strong sales so far in the Christmas shopping season.
Money from the buyout could only make it better.
   ``The merchants of Hanes Mall, as well as other retailers in this
area, are prepared to serve with whatever the stockholders need,''
Winstead said. ``Do I sound reserved enough?''
   Winstead said the people who have seen their stock climb by $37 a
share over the past six weeks might well wish to make
``celebration-type purchases'' of luxury items when their checks
arrive.
   At Windsor Jewelers in downtown Winston-Salem, Lois Simon said
she has already noticed an influx of customers who don't look like
the usual clientele for expensive jewelry.
   ``These are definitely not typical of the clientele that would be
pricing our emeralds and diamonds,'' Mrs. Simon said. She said she
assumes the prospective customers are scouting out purchases they
could make with the proceeds from the sale of their RJR Nabisco
stock.
   The company moved its headquarters to Atlanta last year but
maintains the core of its tobacco operations here.
   Tim A. Cooper, sales manager at a Mercedes dealership, said he
hasn't yet seen any customers who are eager to put down their RJR
profits on a new Mercedes.
   But he added: ``I hope we do see some increase in traffic due to
that.''
   Two local realtors _ Frank Frye and Bruce Hubbard _ said some RJR
investors may put their proceeds into new homes.
   ``What I see happening is what anyone would see if you have a
rich uncle die,'' Frye said. ``I think a lot of people will take
awhile, but they'll eventually look at upgrading their living
standards.''
   But economists at two local universities said the windfall
probably won't spawn a huge spending spree in Winston-Salem.
   Donald Frey, an economics professor at Wake Forest University,
said many investors _ and especially large institutions _ will
probably just reinvest their money.
   ``Most people aren't going to confuse it with income,'' he said.
``They would say, `These are assets that I worked to create, so I'm
not going to go out and blow it on a vacation.'''
   He said employees of subsidiary R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. who are
worried about the future of their jobs will probably be careful
about how they use the money from the sale of their company.
   ``Not all of that spending will take place immediately, and not
all of it will take place in Winston,'' said G. Donald Jud, a
professor of finance at the University of North Carolina at
Greensboro.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
