<DOCNO> AP881201-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1514EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-RJRNabisco-Fallout Bjt   12-01 0818</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-RJR Nabisco-Fallout, Bjt,0842</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Analysts Expect Asset Auction, Less New Product Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the world's best-known food brands may
ultimately be sold and spending on marketing and new product
development may be cut as a result of the $24.5 billion buyout of
RJR Nabisco Inc., analysts said Thursday.
   But the analysts said they cannot predict whether retail prices
will go up or consumers will find it harder to locate their favorite
snacks until it becomes clear who winds up with specific products.
   Many analysts expect the apparent winner in the buyout battle, a
group led by the investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co., will
be forced to sell chunks of the company to meet interest payments on
the huge debt that will be incur in making the purchase.
   ``I've got to assume they will sell a lot of the foods
operations,'' said Neal Kaplan, the food and tobacco analyst for the
investment firm Interstate-Johnson Lane in Charlotte, N.C.
   He said Kohlberg Kravis probably would keep the tobacco company
because of the strong cash flow it generated and then sell stock to
the public later to raise money.
   Officials of Kohlberg Kravis could not be reached for comment on
their plans for RJR Nabisco. A spokeswoman speaking on condition
that she not be identified said the firm had said repeatedly it
wanted ``to keep the company as intact as possible'' and avoid
``massive selling of all the food operations.''
   But Kaplan and other analysts said the debt costs would make it
all but certain that the new owners would be forced to sell some key
operations, such as Nabisco's cookie and cracker business, its
candy, cereal and snack foods interests or its Del Monte canned
vegetable and tropical fruits divisions.
   David Goldman, the food and tobacco analyst for Fahnestock & Co.,
estimated the new owners could get $8 billion for either the Nabisco
foods business or the Reynolds tobacco business, $4 billion to $7
billion for Del Monte and $800 million to $1.2 billion for the
Planters nuts and Life Savers candy business.
   The list of buyers who analysts cite as potential buyers of parts
of the Nabisco operations include the biggest names in consumer
products _ Procter & Gamble, Ralston-Purina, Quaker Oats, Pepsico
and Borden.
   John Maxwell, food and tobacco analyst for Wheat First Securities
in Richmond, Va., said Procter & Gamble, for instance, might be
keenly interested in Nabisco's ready-to-eat cookie business.
Nabisco's cookie brands include Oreo, Chips Ahoy and Fig Newton and
it also owns Ritz crackers.
   He said Ralston or Quaker might be interested in adding Nabisco's
Shredded Wheat to their line of cereals, while Pepsico and Borden
might want Planters nuts to expand their own snack food operations.
   Whether or not major assets are sold, Goldman said, the new
owners will have to cut corners to meet debt payments.
   ``You could see some modest reductions in advertising and other
marketing tools such as couponing and consumer promotions,'' he said.
   RJR Nabisco was for fifth largest national advertiser in 1987,
spending nearly $840 million in support of both its food and tobacco
businesses last year, according to the trade journal Advertising Age.
   Goldman expects a sharp decline in new product introductions
because ``you just don't have the latitude for loss that you had as
an ongoing company.''
   Martin Friedman, editor of Gorman's New Product News, said less
than 1 percent of the 11,000 new food and drug products this year
will produce the level of national sales that major companies
generally consider a success.
   Gary Stibel, a partner in the marketing firm New England
Consulting Group in Westport, Conn., said the prospects for any
given line of food products rests entirely with the group that
ultimately ends up owning them.
   Companies that buy a product line to expand their existing share
of markets generally spend heavily to promote them and may raise
prices, he said.
   But companies that buy a product line in hopes of selling it
later for a profit may be more apt to cut promotional spending and
try to live off the line's reputation as long as possible, he said.
   The fallout from the RJR Nabisco buyout would no necessarily be
limited to the food operations, Fahnestock's Goldman said.
   He said the buyout could mean an early end to RJR Nabisco's
two-month test of its smokeless cigarette, Premier, which delivers
nicotine like a cigarette without much of the smoke.
   ``The Premier appeared to be a dead product to begin with.
Consumer aceptanmce of the product has been dismal. Health
authorities have been rallying against it,'' Goldman said.
   He said the new owners might decide to spare themselves the legal
costs that might be needed to defend the product against legal
challenges.
   ``Premier will become the Edsel of 1988,'' he predicted,
referring to the automobile that proved a costly failure.
</TEXT>
