</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881201-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1554EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-RJRNabisco-Johnson Bjt   12-01 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-RJR Nabisco-Johnson, Bjt,0774</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RJR Nabisco Leader Went From Canadian Prairie to Wall Street's
Limelight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-RJR Nabisco, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As this week's deadline for final bids approached,
RJR Nabisco Inc.'s F. Ross Johnson told a reporter for Time
magazine: ``If I fail, I'm on the hook.''
   That worst-case scenario nows faces the once-confident chief
executive, whose management team launched a bidding war six weeks
ago in hopes of taking the nation's 19th largest industrial company
private.
   Johnson's group apparently lost out to buyout specialists
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. on Wednesday after running up the
price tag for the food and tobacco company to more than $24 billion.
   For Johnson, it was a stunning defeat that contrasts sharply to
his quick rise to the top of the food and tobacco conglomerate.
   Also at stake were immense financial rewards _ under his initial
bid, Johnson stood to make $100 million.
   What's worse, a corporate takeover by outsiders can mean
unemployment for a target company's top management, and a Kohlberg
Kravis buyout of RJR Nabisco makes it unlikely Johnson will stay
there for long.
   But the turmoil that generally accompanies takeovers hasn't
stopped the 56-year-old Johnson before on his path from Canada's
prairies to the riches and celebrity that accompany leadership in
the upper echelons of corporate America.
   As the youngest chairman and chief executive officer ever to head
Standard Brands Inc., Johnson made the packaged-goods company an
enticing target for a 1981 takeover by Nabisco Inc.
   He got the top post at the newly-created company three years
later, when Robert Schaerberle, Nabisco's chief executive officer,
took early retirement. Under Johnson's leadership, an increasingly
profitable Nabisco caught the eye of R.J. Reynolds Inc., which
acquired the food company for $4.9 billion in 1985.
   Again, Johnson did not immediately get the top management job.
But RJR's board presented it to him the following year.
   His willingness to take risks with his own job has contributed to
Johnson's reputation as an aggressive executive with an uncanny
intuition and lightning responses.
   ``He operates from the gut and makes some large decisions from
the gut,'' said Stanley Katz, whose FCB-Leber Katz Partners handles
some RJR advertising.
   Johnson had been RJR Nabisco's chief executive just 15 days when
he announced the company was moving its headquarters from
Winston-Salem, N.C., home for over a century to its central tobacco
division, to Atlanta.
   On Day 16, he announced the sale of RJR's Heublein liquor and
wine business for $1.2 billion. Kentucky Fried Chicken, Canada Dry
and more than two dozen other operations also went on the block
later as Johnson focused the company on packaged food and tobacco.
   Early plans to sell the tobacco division were canceled as it
became clear that cigarettes remained a profitable business. And
Johnson's previously announced plans to reorganize the company
internally to boost its stock price were canceled in mid-October
when Philip Morris Cos. Inc. offered nearly $12 billion for Kraft
Inc.
   Johnson's leveraged buyout proposal for RJR Nabisco came soon
after, amid a wave of takeovers aimed at food companies such as his.
   ``When an opportunity hits, you got to hit,'' he once told the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution, punctuating his remark with a boxer's
jab.
   ``Once he decides to make a move, he makes it,'' said longtime
associate Robert J. Carbonell. ``He likes to speak in terms of
quantum leaps in achieving competitive advantages.''
   Johnson was born in Winnipeg, Manitoba, and earned a degree in
commerce at the University of Manitoba while serving as president of
his fraternity and a member of the basketball team.
   He paid his own way to Toronto after graduation to accept a job
with General Electric of Canada. During his 12 years there, he went
to night school to earn a master's degree in business administration.
   After six years with two other companies, working in retail and
as an executive, he joined Standard Brands in 1971.
   Johnson likes to say, ``If you don't take risks, you can't
compete.'' The fruits of his risk-taking show in his Jaguar; his
corporate jet; his homes in Manhattan, Atlanta and Florida; his golf
games with Bob Hope and Gerald Ford; his friendships with Frank
Gifford and Don Meredith. He steers clear of the social scene, but
appears at company-sponsored benefits.
   ``He has a very strong aversion to two things: bureaucracy and
incompetency,'' Carbonell told the Atlanta newspapers. ``He does not
tolerate incompetency. He's demanding, and you better deliver. You
never want to let Ross down.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
