<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     12-01 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0157</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices drifted lower today in a lackluster
performance restrained by anticipation of Friday's release of
November employment statistics.
   The market had rallied earlier this week on indications that the
economy may be growing at a more moderate pace.
   That presumably would mean that the Federal Reserve policymakers
who meet in mid-December may not feel compelled to encourage higher
interest rates to restrain growth and inflation.
   But analysts said trading slowed today as investors looked toward
Friday's report on November employment for confirmation of economic
growth trends.
   If the report shows stronger-than-expected job growth, some
market watchers expect the Fed may feel obliged to encourage higher
interest rates.
   Rising interest rates hurt stock prices because they make yields
on fixed-income investments such as Treasury bills relatively more
attractive compared with the risks inherent in owning stocks.
</TEXT>
