<DOCNO> AP881201-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1720EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AT&TCharge 1stLd-Writethru   12-01 0990</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AT&T Charge, 1st Ld-Writethru,1018</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AT&T To Post First Annual Loss Because Of $6.7 Billion Charge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to add retirement as option in lede and
UPDATE with closing stock price in 2nd graf; picks up 3rd graf pvs,
The charge ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co. said Thursday
it will post the first annual loss in its 103-year history as a
result of a $6.7 billion pre-tax charge that covers the costs of
scrapping outdated equipment and moving, retiring or laying off
16,000 employees.
   Wall Street saw the giant charge as a sign that AT&T was moving
aggressively to cut costs and install a new digital network to meet
the competition. The stock was fairly stable, falling 50 cents to
$29.37{ a share in consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading.
   The charge will not affect AT&T's cash flow, its ability to pay
dividends or the money available for investment.
   ``This reflects the adjustment of going from a regulated
marketplace to a competitive marketplace,'' said Robert Morris III,
a San Francisco-based analyst for Goldman, Sachs & Co.
   AT&T said the charge would reduce its after-tax profits by $3.9
billion. That makes it likely that the company will lose about $1.6
billion in all of 1988 and $3.3 billion in the fourth quarter alone.
   The only larger quarterly losses in U.S. history were AT&T's own
$4.87 billion loss in the fourth quarter of 1983, which involved a
charge to prepare for the Bell System breakup, and Texaco Inc.'s
$4.76 billion loss in the fourth quarter of 1987 stemming from its
legal fight with Pennzoil Co.
   Long-distance phone companies have been moving aggressively to
replace their old-fashioned analog equipment with new digital
equipment that provides higher quality and is better suited to
custom services and transmission of computer data.
   The bulk of the charge, $5.0 billion, is to reflect on the books
the lower value of outdated analog network equipment. The remaining
$1.7 billion is for the costs of removing the outdated equipment,
writedowns in the value of related equipment, and reductions in
employment.
   AT&T said it would reduce the number of its network employees by
10,000 and the number of its operators by 6,000 over the next few
years.
   AT&T does not yet know how many of the employees will be given
jobs elsewhere in the company because that depends on the company's
growth, spokeswoman LuAnn Gardner said.
   The Communications Workers of America, the union representing
135,000 AT&T workers, issued a statement saying non-management
employees have suffered the loss of 78,500 jobs since 1984 while
management ranks have risen by 13,600.
   ``This company just has not bitten the bullet _ it has not come
out of its `monopoly cocoon' levels of management,'' the union said.
   AT&T spokesman Burke Stinson responded that the company had to
hire white-collar workers because of its new thrusts into computers
and foreign markets. But he said ``we're not blind to the fact''
that staff jobs need to be cut.
   AT&T has a freeze on hiring over most of the company. That gives
the displaced employees a better chance to find work elsewhere
within the company than if they had to face competition from new
hires.
   Plans to reduce 3,000 of the network jobs and all 6,000 of the
operator service jobs had already been announced to employees, AT&T
said. The company is setting aside $400 million to cover the cost of
redeploying them or giving them payments or incentives related to
separation from the company by retirement or resignation.
   The job cuts are possible because improvements in the network
reduce the need for maintenance, engineering, service, order
processing and call handling. Operators at new stations are able to
handle 25 percent more calls per hour, the company said.
   AT&T has switched over to a digital network far more rapidly than
it had previously planned.
   The company predicted early in 1987 that it would take until the
year 2010 to have an all-digital network. By the end of 1987 it said
it could do the job by 1991. On Thursday, it said it could do the
job by the end of next year.
   MCI Communications Corp. and US Sprint Communications Co., the
No. 2 and No. 3 competitors in long distance, have also moved
rapidly to put in digital networks and have taken big charges to
write down the book value of their outdated analog equipment.
   Executives of AT&T had said in October that writedowns in the
fourth quarter could be substantial. By taking the pain of the
writedown all at once, AT&T no longer has to lower its quarterly
profits to reflect the costs of depreciating the older equipment.
   ``We view this as very positive news,'' Ms. Gardner said. ``Our
network will continue to be the best out there.''
   AT&T took a $10 billion pre-tax charge at the end of 1983 to
prepare for the divestiture of its local telephone companies. It
also took pre-tax charges of $200 million in 1985 and $3.2 billion
at the end of 1986.
   AT&T has reduced employment by 64,000 since the breakup of the
Bell System on Jan. 1, 1984. It has about 310,000 employees now, and
that could drop to below 300,000 over the next three to five years,
Ms. Gardner said.
   As large as the job cuts are, securities analysts said they could
be even larger.
   ``They have grossly too many people. At the time of divestiture,
a lot of people were unloaded onto them,'' said James McCabe, an
analyst at Nomura Securities International Inc. He said the cuts
have occurred gradually because ``they're a very humane employer.''
   The Communications Workers of America said AT&T had originally
indicated it had a surplus of 12,000 to 14,000 operators, and that
the union bargained the company down to 6,000.
   Stinson said the thrust of the statement was correct but AT&T
could not confirm the union's numbers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
