<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-01 0791</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Slide on Absence of Soviet Wheat Purchase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices fell sharply Thursday on the Chicago Board
of Trade, reflecting disappointment that the new grain deal with the
Soviet Union had not yet produced a wheat transaction, analysts said.
   Other grain futures closed mostly lower and soybeans posted
substantial losses on fears of a wet weekend in the South American
soybean belt.
   On other markets, sugar futures rose sharply; precious metals
declined; energy futures rallied; livestock and meat futures were
higher; and stock-index futures advanced.
   Many wheat traders had expected the Agriculture Department to
offer the Soviet Union a large amount of subsidized U.S. wheat under
the Export Enhancement Program within days of Monday's signing of a
27-month grain agreement.
   The absence of such an offer spawned speculation Thursday that
the superpowers were still haggling over price and that any
purchases would not be immediately forthcoming, said Dale Gustafson,
a grain market analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   ``The trade is beginning to believe that we may not see the wheat
business coming in December, and maybe not until well after that,''
he said.
   The new grain agreement calls for the Soviets to purchase 4
million metric tons of wheat, 4 million tons of corn and 1 million
tons of their choice in both the current year, which began Oct. 1,
and the following year.
   Conflicting forecasts for the weekend weather in Brazil and
Argentina, where soybean planting is under way, prompted a sell-off
in the soybean pit, analysts said.
   If the dry weather that has marked the early part of the planting
period persists into the growing season, South American forecasts
could lend a fair amount of volatility to the U.S. futures market,
Gustafson said.
   Wheat settled 3 cents to 10\ cents lower with the contract for
delivery in December at $4.16 a bushel; corn was 4 cents lower to }
cent higher with December at $2.57\ a bushel; oats were 3{ cents to
5 cents lower with December at $1.91 a bushel; soybeans were 5{
cents to 8{ cents lower with January at $7.58 a bushel.
   Sugar futures made strong gains on New York's Coffee, Sugar &
Cocoa Exchange in a rally linked to bullish technical signals and
indications that world production may fall short of consumption this
year, leading to a reduction in stockpiles.
   At this point, though, ``there appears to be plenty of physical
sugar available, so it seems to be just a speculative rally,'' said
Erik Dunlaevy, sugar market analyst with Balfour Maclaine Corp. in
New York.
   Sugar settled .31 cent to .49 cent higher with the active March
contract at 11.44 cents a pound, the highest price for March
delivery since July 25.
   Platinum prices dipped amid profit-taking on the New York
Mercantile Exchange following Wednesday's stunning advance of nearly
$25 a troy ounce.
   A strengthening of the dollar also contributed to lower
precious-metals prices, as did jitters prior to Friday's release of
November unemployment figures.
   ``That always makes traders uneasy,'' said Bette Raptopoulos,
metals analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   Platinum settled $7.80 to $13.80 lower with January at $600.90 a
troy ounce.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled 90 cents to $1.10
lower with December at $423.90 a troy ounce; silver was 4 cents to
5.1 cents lower with December at $6.096 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures prices rose on the New York Mercantile Exchange in
technically-inspired trading in the absence of new supply-demand
developments, analysts said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 10 cents to 29 cents higher
with January at $15.61 a barrel; heating oil was .17 cent to .94
cent higher with January at 49.18 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was .25 cent lower to .83 cent higher with January at 45.98 cents a
gallon.
   Cattle futures firmed in a rebound from three consecutive days of
lower prices on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   ``People know the long-term outlook is bullish,'' said Charles
Levitt, senior livestock analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in
Chicago.
   Expectations for a mid-December slowdown in hog slaughters
boosted pork futures, he said.
   Live cattle settled .18 cent to .35 cent higher with December at
72.50 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .45 cent to .73 cent higher
with January at 83.15 cents a pound; hogs were .28 cent to .55 cent
higher with December at 40.37 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .15 cent to .55 cent higher with February at 45.07 cents a
pound.
   Stock-index futures finished slightly higher on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of the
Standard & Poor's 500 settled .15 point higher at 273.20. Each point
is worth $500.
</TEXT>
