<HEAD>London Shares Fall in Gloomy Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS new 3rd graf with volume; picks up 3rd graf pvs bg'ng,
British fashion ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices dropped Thursday on the London Stock
Exchange in an edgy session, as players grew nervous about forecasts
of difficult conditions in the British retailing industry.
   The FT-SE 100-share index finished down 13.7 points, or 0.76
percent, at 1,778.7, above its late-afternoon low of 1,771.7.
   Volume was a sparse 343.4 million shares, down sharply from 444.8
million traded Wednesday.
   British fashion retailer Next said recent rises in domestic
interest rates and other economic factors would produce a
``significant'' drop in the company's profit for fiscal 1988.
   The statement sent shares of retailers plunging as analysts'
concerns about difficulties in the retailing industry spilled over
to the broader market.
   Nervousness over the prospects for the planned British Steel
privatization, as well as the general economic outlook, also
provided a gloomy backdrop to the market.
   Traders said a wobbly start on Wall Street added to the mounting
pessimism in the London market.
   The Financial Times index of 30 industrials closed at 1,450.2,
down 7.8.
   The Financial Times 500-share index finished at 1,004.68, down
8.7.
