<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1835EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 2ndLd-Writethru   12-01 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Drift Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, If the ... to DELETE incorrect reference
to
timing Fed policymaking meeting. Picks up 9th graf pvs, Higher rates
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices drifted lower Thursday in a sluggish
session marked by worries that interest rates may be headed higher.
   Analysts said many investors appeared to prefer standing aside in
advance of the November employment report due Friday which could
provide some indication of whether the economy is moderating or
overheating.
   ``Right now everybody is sitting back waiting for the employment
figures,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, an analyst for the brokerage A.G.
Edwards & Sons Inc. in St. Louis. ``Nobody has any conviction one
way or the other.''
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, up 12.98 points on
Wednesday and nearly 40 points over the past three sessions, lost
12.63 to close at 2,101.88.
   Declining issues outnumbered gainers by about 8-to-7 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
680 issues up, 805 down and 486 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE came to 129.38 million shares,
down from 157.81 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at
regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled
155.12 million shares.
   Analysts said traders were worried that employment growth in
November would indicate faster-than-expected expansion in the
economy.
   If the economy were found to be expanding too quickly, many
analysts fear that the Federal Reserve may feel compelled to push
interest rates higher to slow it down and restrain inflation.
   Higher rates make short-term fixed-income investments more
competitive with the uncertain returns on stocks. Three-month
Treasury bills, for instance, are yielding about 8.10 percent.
   Goldman said most economists expect payroll growth of between
225,000 and 250,000 in November.
   A number significantly higher than that, he said, ``would mean
the economy is in fact overheating and the Fed is going to have to
step on the monetary brakes more heavily than they have already.''
   But there is considerable uncertainty about how fast the economy
is expanding.
   Stocks rallied earlier this week on indications that the economy
may be growing at a more moderate pace.
   In a new report Thursday, the government said its chief
forecasting gauge of future economic activity edged up a sluggish
0.1 percent in October after falling by a revised 0.3 percent in
September.
   RJR Nabisco fell 1\ to 91} and was the most active stock on the
NYSE. The company said late Wednesday it had accepted an offer of
$109 a share in cash and securities from buyout specialist Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts & Co., spurning a competing offer from a management
group.
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co. was also active. It fell { to
29] after saying it will take a $6.7 billion charge against its
fourth-quarter earnings to cover expenses related to getting rid of
outdated telephone equipment.
   General Cinema climbed 2 to 23~ after announcing its planned to
sell its soft drink bottling business to Pepsico Inc. for $1.5
billion. Pepsico fell 2 to 38~.
   Stocks of some of the major retailing companies slipped after
they reported November sales that analysts called sluggish. Sears
Roebuck lost ] to 39{ and J.C. Penney fell { to 52~ but K mart rose
[ to 35}.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market fell $5.91 billion, or 0.22
percent, in value.
   The NYSE composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
0.53 to 153.37.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index lost 1.34 to 313.78, and S&P's
500-stock composite index fell 1.21 to 272.49.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index rose 0.89
to 295.25.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose
2.42 to 373.87.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
