<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Mexico-OPEC     12-01 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Mexico-OPEC,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico Offers Export Reduction to Firm Up OPEC Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An OPEC team plans to visit Mexico and other
non-OPEC producing nations to discuss mutual reductions in export
quotas, according to a published report Thursday.
   The report followed an offer by Mexico's Energy Department to
negotiate a reduction in Mexico's oil exports in a bid to put some
teeth into the OPEC cartel agreement to restrict production.
   Energy Secretary Fernando Hiriart this week repeated an offer,
previously spurned by the 13-member cartel, to reduce Mexico's 1.35
million-barrel daily export platform, provided OPEC members enact
similar reductions.
   Reductions also would be sought from other independent producers,
Hiriart said.
   He said department officials planned informal talks with OPEC and
independent producers on possible quota reductions.
   The Energy Department announced that an OPEC committee plans to
visit Mexico and other independent producers to negotiate reductions
to buttress Monday's OPEC pact, the Mexico City newspaper La Jornada
reported Thursday.
   Department officials could not be reached for comment Thursday, a
national holiday called to mark the inauguration of President Carlos
Salinas de Gortari.
   The agreement by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries calls for a cartel export ceiling of 18.5 million barrels
daily, roughly 4 million barrels below current production.
   A statement issued this week by former President Miguel de la
Madrid praised the agreement and urged immediate consultations
between cartel and independent producers. But he warned much
remained to be done to shore up the weak global market.
   ``Mexico urges all producers _ whether or not they are members of
OPEC _ to act with caution in the next few months,'' the statement
said.
   Mexico, the world's sixth-largest oil producer, has closely
followed the cartel's pricing and production guidelines.
   Only two weeks ago, Hiriart announced Mexico was abandoning that
policy, because overproduction by OPEC members had rendered its
market quotas useless.
   Mexico severely criticized OPEC this year for engaging in a price
war it said threatened Mexico's share of the U.S. market and dragged
down average prices of Mexican export crude to under $10.
   Mexico loses an estimated $500 million in foreign earnings for
each $1 drop in crude prices. Energy Department officials
acknowledge the country has lost $2 billion in anticipated revenue
this year.
</TEXT>
