<1ST_LINE>u f AM-DisneyStudio     12-01 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Disney Studio,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walt Disney Co. Forming Third Movie Production Arm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an effort to capitalize on a string of
box office successes, Walt Disney Co. on Thursday announced
formation of a third movie production arm called Hollywood Pictures.
   Disney, presently the nation's top producer of movies through its
Touchstone Films and Disney Films divisions, said the new company
would start up Feb. 1. Within three years, it is to be making 12
movies a year, the company said.
   Hollywood Pictures will make movies similar to those from
Touchstone, which produces mainline fare considerably racier than
Disney's traditional animated features and kids' comedies. Budgets
will be similar to those at Touchstone, which is known in the
business for holding the line on production costs and stars'
salaries.
   All Disney films are distributed through a unit called Buena
Vista, which, according to a ranking by the Hollywood trade paper
Daily Variety, has the biggest share of the nation's box office this
year.
   Up to Nov. 13, Buena Vista movies grabbed 20.5 percent of
domestic movie ticket sales, according to Variety. Disney is
followed on that list by Paramount Studios at 14.1 percent, 20th
Century Fox at 12.3 percent, Warner Bros. at 10.7 percent and MGM-UA
Communications at 9.8 percent.
   Touchstone, formed in 1984, surprised many moviegoers by
departing from the Disney tradition of family-oriented
entertainment, producing some films that earned R ratings.
Touchstone reaped a box office bonanza last year with ``Good
Morning: Vietnam,'' and ``Three Men and a Baby.''
   Touchstone has had three recent non-starters: ``Heartbreak
Hotel,'' ``The Good Mother'' and ``Ernest Saves Christmas.''
</TEXT>
