<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 2037EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-S&P-InsuranceCompanies     12-01 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-S&P-Insurance Companies,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Standard & Poor's Places Four Insurance Companies on Creditwatch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Standard & Poor's Corp. said Thursday it was
re-evaluating its credit ratings of four insurance companies
following the passage of California's Proposition 103.
   Standard & Poor's said it was placing Allstate Insurance Co.,
Farmers Group Inc., Fireman's Fund and Safeco Insurance Co. on its
``Creditwatch'' list with negative implications. That means Standard
& Poor's might downgrade the ratings of the four insurers.
   The firm lowers credit ratings, which are a factor in determining
how much a company must pay to borrow money in the bond markets,
when it determines the company's ability to raise the money for
repaying its debt has been affected.
   Proposition 103, which California voters approved Nov. 8,
requires that rates for motor vehicle, homeowner and other property
and casualty insurance be rolled back to November 1987 levels and
then reduced 20 percent and frozen until November 1989.
   Insurers can request exemptions, but they are to be granted only
if the companies show a ``substantial threat of insolvency'' would
result from the rate cuts.
   Among the measure's other provisions is a requirement that,
beginning in November 1989, the state insurance commissioner approve
all rate increases. Any increases that are ``excessive, inadequate
or unfairly discriminatory'' will be prohibited.
   A number of insurance companies have filed suit in the California
Supreme Court to challenge the constitutionality of Proposition 103,
and many insurers have restricted or eliminated their California
coverage.
   The Supreme Court has blocked enforcement of the 20 percent rate
reduction and other provisions while the suit is under consideration.
</TEXT>
