<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Lilly     12-01 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lilly,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lilly to Buy Vascular Catheter Maker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eli Lilly and Co. announced Thursday an
agreement to purchase Devices for Vascular Intervention Inc., a
leading developer and manufacturer of catheter systems for the
treatment of cardiovascular disease.
   DVI, a privately-owned company based in Redwood City, Calif.,
manufactures catheter systems that treat cardiovascular disease by
cutting, capturing and removing vascular plaque from diseased blood
vessels.
   Lilly will pay about $50 million with the potential for up to
another $150 million in contingency payments over the next five
years if certain clinical objectives and performance criteria are
met, said Lilly Chairman Richard D. Wood.
   DVI will join Lilly's Medical Instrument Systems Division as a
wholly-owned subsidiary. The division already markets internal and
external pacemakers, catheters for balloon angioplasty, implantable
and external defibrillators and systems for fluid and drug delivery.
   The agreement is subject to approval by DVI shareholders. Owners
of about 65 percent of DVI's common stock have agreed to vote in
favor of the merger, according to the Lilly announcement.
   A special meeting of DVI shareholders will be held early next
year to vote on the merger proposal.
</TEXT>
