<DOCNO> AP881201-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 2002EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-PriceFixing     12-01 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Price Fixing,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pepsi Unit Pleads Guilty to Price-Fixing, Fined $1 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Knoxville soft drink bottler was fined
$1 million Thursday after pleading guilty to price-fixing in a dozen
east Tennessee counties in 1983.
   Robert J. Habig, vice president of Atlantic Soft Drink Co. Inc.,
entered the guilty plea in U.S. District Court in Knoxville on
behalf of the company's board of directors. The $1 million fine, the
maximum, was part of the plea agreement between the company and
prosecutors.
   The company also agreed to cooperate with a continuing
investigation of price-fixing in the soft drink industry, said
Assistant U.S. Attorney Jimmie Baxter, who represented the
government.
   Because the investigation is still underway, Baxter said, he
could not comment further on the circumstances of the price-fixing.
   PepsiCo, the giant soft-drink company, bought Atlantic Soft Drink
in June, said corporate spokesman Jim Griffith in New York.
   ``All these incidents occurred when the company was owned by
another company,'' Griffith said, although he said he could not
disclose the identity of the former owners. ``All the individuals
involved in the price-fixing have since left the company, had in
fact already left when we assumed ownership.''
   He said PepsiCo was aware of the price-fixing investigation when
it bought Atlantic Soft Drink.
   Atlantic, based in Columbia, S.C., bottles Pepsi and Seven-Up
products. It employs 1,200 people in five states.
   The charge against Atlantic alleges that the company and others
``engaged in a conspiracy to suppress and eliminate competition by
fixing discount prices of soft drink products sold in six-pack,
12-ounce cans'' in the following Tennessee counties: Loudon,
Campbell, Anderson, Knox, Sevier, Blount, Union, Claiborne,
Grainger, Jefferson, Hamblen and Cocke.
   The government charged the company with violating the Sherman
Antitrust Act.
   In exchange for the guilty plea, $1 million fine and continued
cooperation, the government agreed not to bring further criminal
charges against the company or any of its subsidiaries for actions
taken prior to the agreement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
