<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   12-01 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0559</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buyout specialist Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.
has claimed victory in a free-for-all record takeover war for RJR
Nabisco Inc. with a $24.53 billion offer for the tobacco and food
giant.
   The $109-a-share offer accepted late Wednesday by RJR's board of
directors shattered a rival effort by an RJR management group and
came in a day of frantic maneuvering that at times left the
unprecedented auction for the company in utter confusion.
   Kohlberg's offer of $81 in cash, $18 in stock and additional
securities worth $10 beat out a last-minute offer valued at $112, or
$25.2 billion, by the management group that instigated the takeover
struggle last month at a price that was $8.3 billion cheaper.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans' personal income posted its largest
gain in a year in October, the government says.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that personal income rose
1.8 percent, the biggest rise since October 1987, to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of $4.18 trillion last month. The gain followed
modest increases of 0.5 percent in September and 0.4 percent in
August.
   The department attributed about half of last month's increase to
farm subsidy payments and bonuses to auto workers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve's district banks reported
``apparently slower'' growth, moderate wage increases and slightly
easing price pressures in several manufacturing industries,
according to a new report.
   The report, based on surveys conducted by the 12 Fed district
banks, stirred a rally in financial markets Wednesday as investors
interpreted the findings as a signal that the Fed might be williing
to loosen its credit policy because of signs of a slowing economy
and easing inflationary pressures.
   But some private economists said they believed the Fed district
banks were overstating the economic slowdown and the central bank
still will be forced to tighten credit conditions in coming months.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co. will cut its
basic interstate long-distance rates an average 3.8 percent while 60
cents will be added to monthly local phone bills.
   AT&T's $697 million annual reduction announced Wednesday reflects
the company's lower costs of connecting to the local phone network.
Those costs will drop because residential and small business
subscribers will be paying more to maintain the local network.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices farmers got for raw products in November
declined slightly from a month earlier but remained nearly 8 percent
above their level of a year earlier, the Agriculture Department
reports.
   The department's Agricultural Statistics Board said Wednesday in
its preliminary report that lower prices for hogs, corn, grapefruit
and soybeans were partly offset by higher prices for tomatoes,
potatoes, milk and sweet corn, resulting in an overall drop of
nearly 1 percent for the month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top federal bank regulator says $30 billion
should be spent next year to close the nation's worst 100 savings
institutions quickly and that it could be done without inflating the
federal budget deficit.
   Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. Chairman L. William Seidman,
emphasizing that the shakiest institutions should be closed, rather
than rescued, said Wednesday insolvent S&Ls now are ``reporting
losses of over a billion dollars per month.''
</TEXT>
