<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   12-01 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0514</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright has called for George
Bush to quickly present Congress with an ``honest and responsible''
budget, and says the president-elect has a duty to detail his plan
for attacking the country's deficit problems.
   Wright joined a number of other witnesses Wednesday before the
National Economic Commission in urging quick and decisive action on
the part of the new administration and Congress to break the
seven-year deadlock over huge budget deficits.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SPRINGDALE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tyson Foods Inc. has sweetened its buyout
offer for Holly Farms Corp., but made completion of the deal
contingent on the termination of Holly Farms' merger with ConAgra
Inc.
   The nation's biggest poultry processor boosted its cash tender
offer Wednesday to $54 a share, or about $1.1 billion for Holly
Farms' 20.4 million outstanding common shares and equivalents, from
$52 a share.
   The offer was subject to termination or invalidation of Holly
Farms' merger with ConAgra and its agreement to sell ConAgra some of
its prize assets if acquired by a third company, such as Tyson.
   Holly Farms had no immediate comment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. has told Grand Metropolitan PLC
that its $60-a-share takeover offer is inadequate and a meeting
between officials of the two companies would ``serve no purpose.''
   Philip L. Smith, Pillsbury's chairman, said Wednesday in a letter
to Grand Met Chairman Allen Sheppard that the Pillsbury board
unanimously determined that its offer ``is financially inadequate
and not in the best interests of Pillsbury and its shareholders,''
   Grand Met spokesman Walter Montgomery was not immediately
available for comment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street leaders are increasingly
concluding _ and admitting _ that they aren't going to win their
decade-long battle to keep banks out of the stocks and bonds
business.
   The latest sign of their retreat from the lobbying effort came
Wednesday when the head of the Securities Industry Association said
he no longer opposes repeal of the Glass-Steagall Act of 1933. The
law which set sharp boundaries between the financial services that
banks and brokers could offer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Jones & Co. Inc. has agreed to sell its 17
percent interest in Continental Cablevision Inc. to the
privately-held cable television operator's chairman for $299.8
million.
   Continental Cablevision is based in Boston and is the nation's
third-largest cable operator with about 2.3 million subscribers in
15 states.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices advanced Wednesday, boosting the Dow Jones average
of 30 industrial stocks 12.98 points to 2,114.51.
   The dollar fell slightly in New York after rising in Europe.
   Bond prices advanced and most short-term interest rates tumbled.
   Platinum futures prices rocketed above $600 a troy ounce for the
first time in nearly six months. On other futures markets, gold and
silver rose; pork bellies were sharply higher while livestock
futures were mixed; sugar futures were sharply lower; and energy,
grains, soybeans rose.
</TEXT>
